  "question": "A 40-year-old man who weighs 65 kg is being observed in the ICU. Twenty-four hours postoperatively, he develops convulsions. His serum sodium is 118 mEq/L. Appropriate management includes which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Administration of normal saline (0.9%)",
    "B": "Administration of hypertonic saline (3%)",
    "C": "Emergency hemodialysis",
    "D": "Administration of vasopressin",
    "E": "Administration of Lasix, 40 mg intravenously (IV)"
  },
  "answer": "B) Hyponatremia occurs because of overhydration and/or inadequate sodium replacement. When serum sodium is <130 mEq/L, acute symptomatic hyponatremia is manifested by CNS symptoms due to increased intracranial pressure. Muscle twitching and increased tendon reflexes seen in moderate hyponatremia progress to convulsions, loss of reflexes, and hypertension with severe hyponatremia. Oliguric renal failure may become irreversible if not immediately treated. Mild asymptomatic hyponatremia is treated with fluid restrictions. In the presence of CNS symptoms, the patient should be given hypertonic saline.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the brain seizes from low sodium, give it salt fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, administration of hypertonic saline (3%). This patient presents with acute, severe symptomatic hyponatremia (serum Na 118 mEq/L) manifesting as convulsions, which necessitates urgent correction to prevent irreversible neurological damage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSymptomatic hyponatremia, especially with neurological manifestations like convulsions, is a medical emergency. The low serum sodium creates an osmotic gradient, causing water to shift from the extracellular space into brain cells, leading to cerebral edema and increased intracranial pressure. Hypertonic saline (3%) works by rapidly increasing the serum osmolality, thereby drawing water out of the swollen brain cells and reducing cerebral edema. This immediate osmotic shift is crucial to alleviate life-threatening CNS symptoms and prevent brain herniation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Administration of normal saline (0.9%) would be inappropriate. While 0.9% saline is isotonic to normal plasma, it is hypotonic relative to the patient's severely hyponatremic serum (118 mEq/L) and would further dilute the serum sodium, worsening cerebral edema.\nOption C (Incorrect): Emergency hemodialysis is an overly aggressive and generally not a first-line treatment for acute symptomatic hyponatremia unless there is severe renal failure or refractory cases unresponsive to medical management. It carries risks and is not the most direct initial intervention for cerebral edema.\nOption D (Incorrect): Administration of vasopressin (antidiuretic hormone, ADH) would worsen hyponatremia. ADH promotes water reabsorption in the kidneys, which would further dilute the serum sodium concentration.\nOption E (Incorrect): Administration of Lasix (furosemide) is a loop diuretic that promotes free water excretion but also sodium excretion. While it can be used in conjunction with hypertonic saline in specific cases to prevent volume overload, it is not the primary treatment for acute symptomatic hyponatremia with convulsions and would not rapidly correct the underlying osmotic imbalance causing cerebral edema.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hyponatremia Type | Serum Na (mEq/L) | Symptoms | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mild Asymptomatic | 125-135 | None or mild (fatigue, nausea) | Fluid restriction, address underlying cause |\n| Moderate Symptomatic | 120-125 | Headache, confusion, lethargy | Hypertonic saline (3%) with careful monitoring, consider loop diuretic if volume overloaded |\n| Severe Symptomatic | <120 | Seizures, coma, brain herniation | Urgent hypertonic saline (3%) bolus, rapid initial correction, close monitoring |\n| Chronic Hyponatremia | Variable | Variable, often subtle | Slower correction rate to avoid osmotic demyelination syndrome (ODS) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic hyponatremia with CNS signs demands urgent hypertonic saline.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a brain CT or MRI, severe hyponatremia can manifest as diffuse cerebral edema, characterized by effacement of sulci, narrowing of ventricles, and loss of gray-white matter differentiation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe European Society of Endocrinology Clinical Practice Guideline on Diagnosis and Treatment of Hyponatremia (2014) recommends urgent administration of hypertonic saline for patients with severe symptomatic hyponatremia, aiming for a rapid initial increase in serum sodium.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Administration of normal saline (0.9%) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Administration of hypertonic saline (3%) | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Emergency hemodialysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Administration of vasopressin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Administration of Lasix, 40 mg intravenously (IV) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Hyponatremia occurs because of overhydration and/or inadequate sodium replacement. When serum sodium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
