  "question": "A30-year-old man with a history of Crohn’s disease of the small bowel is admitted with enterocutaneous fistula. The daily output from the fistula is 2 L. The approximate composition of the fluids in mEq/Lis which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Na 10 K 26 Cl 10 HCO3 30",
    "B": "Na 60 K 10 Cl 130 HCO3 0",
    "C": "Na 140 K 5 Cl 104 HCO3 30",
    "D": "Na 140 K 5 Cl 75 HCO3 115",
    "E": "Na 60 K 30 Cl 40 HCO3 40"
  },
  "answer": "C) The composition of various GI secretions is different. They are as follows: A, saliva; B, gastric; C, ileal; D, pancreatic; and E, colonic. The composition of intestinal fluid is the closest to that of plasma.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Small bowel fistulas mimic plasma; replace accordingly!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. This option accurately reflects the electrolyte composition of ileal fluid, which is the most likely source of a high-output enterocutaneous fistula in a patient with Crohn's disease of the small bowel. Ileal fluid is isotonic with plasma, characterized by high sodium and chloride, and lower potassium and bicarbonate.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIleal fluid, particularly from a high-output fistula, has an electrolyte profile remarkably similar to plasma, with high sodium (Na ~140 mEq/L), moderate chloride (~104 mEq/L), and low potassium (~5 mEq/L) and bicarbonate (~30 mEq/L). This isotonicity is critical for understanding the significant fluid and electrolyte losses in patients with small bowel fistulas, as large volumes can rapidly lead to dehydration and electrolyte imbalances. The 2 L/day output underscores the need for precise fluid and electrolyte replacement, often requiring intravenous solutions that mirror this composition to prevent complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This composition (Na 10 K 26 Cl 10 HCO3 30) is characteristic of saliva, which has very low sodium and chloride.\nOption B (Incorrect): This composition (Na 60 K 10 Cl 130 HCO3 0) is typical of gastric fluid, which is highly acidic with high chloride and low sodium.\nOption D (Incorrect): This composition (Na 140 K 5 Cl 75 HCO3 115) is characteristic of pancreatic fluid, which is isotonic but has very high bicarbonate.\nOption E (Incorrect): This composition (Na 60 K 30 Cl 40 HCO3 40) is typical of colonic fluid, which has lower sodium and chloride but higher potassium and bicarbonate than ileal fluid.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Secretion Type | Na (mEq/L) | K (mEq/L) | Cl (mEq/L) | HCO3 (mEq/L) | pH |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Plasma | 135-145 | 3.5-5.0 | 98-108 | 22-28 | 7.35-7.45 |\n| Saliva | 10-20 | 10-20 | 10-20 | 20-30 | 6.0-7.0 |\n| Gastric | 20-80 | 5-20 | 100-150 | 0 | 1.0-3.5 |\n| Ileal | 120-140 | 5-10 | 90-110 | 20-30 | 7.0-8.0 |\n| Pancreatic | 120-140 | 5-10 | 40-80 | 70-110 | 8.0-8.3 |\n| Colonic | 50-80 | 20-30 | 40-60 | 30-40 | 7.0-8.0 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know GI fluid electrolyte compositions for fistula management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT with oral contrast, an enterocutaneous fistula appears as contrast extravasation from the bowel lumen to the skin. Intraoperatively, one would identify the fistulous tract originating from an inflamed or diseased small bowel segment, often with surrounding adhesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition (ASPEN) Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016) recommend tailored fluid and electrolyte replacement based on fistula output composition.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Na 10 K 26 Cl 10 HCO3 30 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Na 60 K 10 Cl 130 HCO3 0 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Na 140 K 5 Cl 104 HCO3 30 | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Na 140 K 5 Cl 75 HCO3 115 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Na 60 K 30 Cl 40 HCO3 40 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The composition of various GI secretions is different. They are as follows: A, saliva; B, gastric; C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
