  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a villous adenoma drain your patient's potassium!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Villous adenoma of the colon. This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the patient's progressively worsening watery diarrhea and associated hypokalemia, a classic presentation of these tumors due to their copious mucin secretion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVillous adenomas, particularly large ones, are characterized by their frond-like architecture and ability to secrete large volumes of potassium-rich, electrolyte-laden mucus. This secretory diarrhea leads to significant gastrointestinal loss of potassium, resulting in profound hypokalemia. The progressive nature of the diarrhea further supports the ongoing loss of electrolytes, making this the most likely cause in the given clinical scenario.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Myoglobinemia, typically seen in rhabdomyolysis, involves massive tissue injury and release of intracellular contents, including potassium, leading to hyperkalemia, not hypokalemia.\nOption C (Incorrect): High-output renal failure implies impaired renal function, which would lead to reduced potassium excretion and thus hyperkalemia, not hypokalemia.\nOption D (Incorrect): Massive blood transfusion, especially with older stored blood, can lead to a potassium load from lysed red blood cells, causing hyperkalemia, not hypokalemia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Spironolactone is a potassium-sparing diuretic. Its use would typically lead to hyperkalemia or help maintain potassium levels, not cause hypokalemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Hypokalemia | Mechanism | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Villous Adenoma | Secretion of K+-rich mucus | Watery diarrhea, progressive |\n| Loop/Thiazide Diuretics | Increased renal K+ excretion | Polyuria, drug history |\n| Vomiting/NG Suction | Gastric acid loss, renal compensation | Metabolic alkalosis, volume depletion |\n| Primary Aldosteronism | Increased renal K+ excretion | Hypertension, metabolic alkalosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Watery diarrhea + hypokalemia = think villous adenoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, a villous adenoma appears as a broad-based, often sessile, velvety or cauliflower-like lesion with a frond-like surface, typically larger than other polyps.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) 2023 Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Colorectal Polyps recommend surveillance colonoscopy intervals based on polyp type and size, with villous adenomas requiring closer follow-up due to their malignant potential.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Myoglobinemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Villous adenoma of colon | ✅ Correct |\n| C | High-output renal failure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Massive blood transfusion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Spironolactone (Aldactone) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Villous adenoma of colon can result in watery diarrhea and hypokalemia. Massive tissue injury produc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
