  "question": "A42-year-old man with small-bowel fistula has been receiving TPN with standard hypertonic glucose-amino acid solution for 3 weeks. The patient is noticed to have scaly, hyperpigmented lesions over the acral surfaces of elbows and knees, similar to enterohepatic acrodermatitis. What is the most likely cause of the condition?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Copper deficiency",
    "B": "Essential fatty acid deficiency",
    "C": "Excess glucose calories",
    "D": "Hypomagnesemia",
    "E": "Zinc deficiency"
  },
  "answer": "E) Zinc is one of the metalloenzymes involved in lipid, carbohydrate, protein, and nucleic acid metabolism. Skin lesions similar to enterohepatic acrodermatitis are the most common sign seen in zinc deficiency. Other manifestations include hypogonadism, diminished wound healing, and immunodeficiencies. Copper deficiency is characterized by microcytic hypochromic anemia.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When skin screams \"acrodermatitis,\" zinc is the nutrient to address.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation of scaly, hyperpigmented lesions over acral surfaces, resembling enterohepatic acrodermatitis, in the context of prolonged TPN, is pathognomonic for zinc deficiency. Zinc is a crucial metalloenzyme involved in skin integrity and its absence leads to these characteristic dermatological findings.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nZinc acts as a vital metalloenzyme involved in numerous metabolic pathways, including lipid, carbohydrate, protein, and nucleic acid metabolism. Its deficiency impairs cellular function, particularly in rapidly dividing cells like those of the skin and gut. The classic skin lesions, often described as acrodermatitis enteropathica-like, are the most common and specific sign of zinc deficiency, especially in patients receiving TPN without adequate supplementation or those with high-output fistulas leading to increased zinc losses.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Copper deficiency typically presents with microcytic hypochromic anemia, neutropenia, and myeloneuropathy, not acral skin lesions.\nOption B (Incorrect): Essential fatty acid deficiency can cause a generalized scaly dermatitis, but it lacks the specific acral, hyperpigmented, and often periorificial distribution characteristic of zinc deficiency.\nOption C (Incorrect): Excess glucose calories in TPN primarily lead to hyperglycemia, hepatic steatosis, and increased CO2 production, not specific skin lesions.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hypomagnesemia manifests primarily with neuromuscular irritability (tremors, tetany, seizures) and cardiac arrhythmias, not dermatological signs similar to acrodermatitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nutrient Deficiency | Key Clinical Manifestations |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------- |\n| Zinc                | Acral dermatitis (enterohepatic acrodermatitis-like), poor wound healing, hypogonadism, alopecia, immunodeficiency |\n| Copper              | Microcytic anemia, neutropenia, myeloneuropathy, hair changes |\n| Essential Fatty Acid| Scaly dermatitis, alopecia, poor wound healing, growth retardation |\n| Magnesium           | Neuromuscular irritability (tremors, tetany), cardiac arrhythmias, weakness |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acral dermatitis in a TPN patient = think zinc deficiency.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, these lesions are typically erythematous, scaly, and pustular, often affecting the periorificial areas (mouth, anus), hands, feet, and pressure points like elbows and knees. Lab tests would confirm low serum zinc levels.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN Clinical Guidelines: Parenteral Nutrition. 2014. Recommends routine monitoring and supplementation of trace elements, including zinc, in TPN patients, especially those with increased losses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Copper deficiency | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Essential fatty acid deficiency | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Excess glucose calories | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypomagnesemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Zinc deficiency | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Zinc is one of the metalloenzymes involved in lipid, carbohydrate, protein, and nucleic acid metabol** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
