  "answer": "B) The presence of an adequate urine output does not preclude a diagnosis of high-output renal failure. The mechanism is based in part on prior ischemia to the nephron structure of the kidneys. There may be an initial period of oliguria. Urea, potassium, and acids are still partly excreted in the urine, and lactate or bicarbonate is given to avoid development of acidosis.",
