  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, think X-linked for male bleeding.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nHemophilia is the most likely diagnosis for a bleeding disorder presenting in infancy, especially in males. This is due to its characteristic sex-linked recessive inheritance pattern and presentation with spontaneous or trauma-induced bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemophilia A (Factor VIII deficiency) and Hemophilia B (Factor IX deficiency) are X-linked recessive disorders, meaning they predominantly affect males. The deficiency in these specific coagulation factors impairs the intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade, leading to a prolonged activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT). Clinically, this manifests as deep tissue bleeding, hemarthrosis (bleeding into joints), and excessive bleeding after trauma or surgery, often presenting in infancy or early childhood.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Diethylstilbestrol (DES) exposure in utero is associated with reproductive tract anomalies and clear cell adenocarcinoma of the vagina/cervix in female offspring, not coagulation disorders.\nOption B (Incorrect): Aplastic anemia is a bone marrow failure syndrome resulting in pancytopenia (deficiency of all blood cell types), leading to bleeding primarily due to thrombocytopenia, not a specific coagulation factor deficiency.\nOption C (Incorrect): Henoch-Schönlein purpura is an IgA vasculitis characterized by palpable purpura, arthritis, abdominal pain, and nephritis, typically following an infection, and is not a primary coagulation factor disorder.\nOption E (Incorrect): Wilson’s disease is a disorder of copper metabolism leading to copper accumulation in various organs, including the liver, causing cirrhosis. While severe cirrhosis can impair the synthesis of clotting factors, Wilson's disease itself is not a primary coagulation disorder, and the question implies a more direct cause.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Disorder | Deficient Factor | Inheritance | Key Clinical Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Hemophilia A | Factor VIII | X-linked recessive | Deep tissue bleeding, hemarthrosis |\n| Hemophilia B | Factor IX | X-linked recessive | Clinically similar to Hemophilia A |\n| Von Willebrand Disease | Von Willebrand Factor (vWF) | Autosomal dominant | Mucocutaneous bleeding, prolonged bleeding time |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: X-linked recessive bleeding disorders primarily affect males.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (MRI, ultrasound) would reveal hemarthrosis (blood in joints) or deep muscle hematomas. Intraoperatively, persistent and excessive bleeding despite standard hemostatic measures would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Federation of Hemophilia (WFH) Guidelines for the Management of Hemophilia, 3rd Edition (2020). Recommends comprehensive care, prophylaxis, and on-demand treatment with factor concentrates.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Diethylstilbestrol (DES) was taken by the mother during pregnancy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Aplastic anemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Henoch-Schönlein purpura | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hemophilia | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Wilson’s disease with cirrhosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Hemophilia (factor VIII deficiency) usually occurs during infancy. It is sex-linked, recessive, and ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
