  "answer": "B) Spontaneous bleeding occurs when factor VIII is reduced below 2–3%. Once serious bleeding occurs, a higher factor VIII activity— probably approaching 30%—is required for adequate hemostasis. The half-life of factor VIII is 8–12 hours. In minor lesions, 10 U/kg body weight of factor VIII is administered. For severe lesions, the dosage is 40–50 U/kg body weight of factor VIII. After major surgical procedures, factor VIII must be given daily for 7–10 days. Penicillamine is used to inhibit excess copper deposition (e.g., in Wilson’s disease).",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
