  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 vWD: Bleed longer, clot slower, but PT's a no-show!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Von Willebrand disease (vWD) is a common inherited bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or defect in von Willebrand factor (vWF), which impairs both primary hemostasis and the intrinsic coagulation pathway.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nvWF has two critical functions: it mediates platelet adhesion to subendothelial collagen at sites of vascular injury (primary hemostasis), and it acts as a carrier protein for Factor VIII, protecting it from proteolytic degradation. A deficiency in vWF therefore leads to a prolonged bleeding time due to impaired platelet adhesion, and a prolonged PTT due to a secondary reduction in Factor VIII activity. The PT, which assesses the extrinsic coagulation pathway, remains normal as it is not directly affected by vWF or Factor VIII levels.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Normal bleeding time, PT, and PTT would indicate normal hemostasis, which is not consistent with a diagnosis of von Willebrand disease.\nOption B (Incorrect): In von Willebrand disease, platelets *fail* to aggregate with ristocetin, as ristocetin-induced platelet aggregation is dependent on functional vWF. Normal patients *do* aggregate with ristocetin.\nOption D (Incorrect): PT is normal in von Willebrand disease because the extrinsic pathway is not affected.\nOption E (Incorrect): PTT is typically increased in von Willebrand disease due to the secondary deficiency of Factor VIII, which is stabilized by vWF.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Coagulation Disorder | Bleeding Time | PT | PTT | Ristocetin Aggregation |\n|----------------------|---------------|----|-----|------------------------|\n| von Willebrand Disease | Increased     | Normal | Increased | Decreased/Absent       |\n| Hemophilia A         | Normal        | Normal | Increased | Normal                 |\n| Platelet Dysfunction | Increased     | Normal | Normal | Variable               |\n| Vitamin K Deficiency | Normal        | Increased | Increased | Normal                 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: vWD = prolonged bleeding time + prolonged PTT + normal PT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative imaging for cholecystectomy would not directly show vWD. Intraoperatively, one might observe increased or prolonged oozing from surgical sites, even with meticulous local hemostasis, necessitating careful attention to systemic factor replacement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASH-ISTH-NHF-WFH 2021 Guidelines for the Management of von Willebrand Disease recommend specific diagnostic criteria and treatment strategies, including desmopressin or vWF concentrate for surgical prophylaxis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Normal bleeding time, PT, and PTT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Platelet aggregate with restocetin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Increased bleeding time and PTT, and normal PT | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Increased bleeding time and PT, and normal PTT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Increased bleeding time, and normal PT and PTT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) von Willebrand disease is characterized by decreased level of factor VIIIc (procoagulant). It has au** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
