  "id": 130050,
  "question": "Following admission to the emergency depart-ment, a 26-year-old woman with severe men-orrhagia states that both her father and sister have a bleeding disorder. The hemostatic dis-order transmitted by autosomal-dominant mode is which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Factor X deficiency",
    "B": "von Willebrand’s disease",
    "C": "Factor VIII deficiency (true hemophilia)",
    "D": "Factor IX deficiency (Christmas disease)",
    "E": "Factor V deficiency (parahemophilia)"
  },
  "answer": "B) von Willebrand disease is the most common hemostatic disorder transmitted by autosomal-dominant mode. Other disorders transmitted by this mode are hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia and factor XI deficiency. Diseases transmitted by an autosomal-recessive mode are factor X, factor V, factor VII, and factor I deficiencies. Factor VIII (true hemophilia) and factor IX (Christmas disease) deficiencies are sex-liked recessive.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 vWD: The dominant bleeder in the family tree.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is von Willebrand's disease (vWD) because it is the most common inherited bleeding disorder and is transmitted in an autosomal dominant pattern. This inheritance pattern directly explains the family history of both the father and sister being affected.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nvon Willebrand factor (vWF) plays a crucial role in primary hemostasis by mediating platelet adhesion to the subendothelium and acting as a carrier protein for Factor VIII, protecting it from degradation. A deficiency or defect in vWF leads to impaired platelet plug formation and reduced Factor VIII levels, causing bleeding symptoms like menorrhagia. Its autosomal dominant inheritance means only one copy of the affected gene is needed for expression, making it common to see in multiple family members across generations, as described in the clinical vignette.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Factor X deficiency is transmitted by an autosomal recessive mode, not autosomal dominant.\nOption C (Incorrect): Factor VIII deficiency (true hemophilia) is an X-linked recessive disorder, primarily affecting males and passed from carrier mothers.\nOption D (Incorrect): Factor IX deficiency (Christmas disease) is also an an X-linked recessive disorder, similar to Factor VIII deficiency.\nOption E (Incorrect): Factor V deficiency (parahemophilia) is transmitted by an autosomal recessive mode, not autosomal dominant.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Disorder | Inheritance Pattern | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| von Willebrand Disease | Autosomal Dominant | Most common inherited bleeding disorder; affects platelet adhesion and Factor VIII stability |\n| Hemophilia A (Factor VIII deficiency) | X-linked Recessive | Affects males; deep tissue bleeding, hemarthroses |\n| Hemophilia B (Factor IX deficiency) | X-linked Recessive | Affects males; deep tissue bleeding, hemarthroses |\n| Factor X Deficiency | Autosomal Recessive | Rare; affects common pathway of coagulation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Autosomal dominant bleeding disorder? Think von Willebrand's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, patients with vWD may exhibit diffuse mucosal oozing or prolonged bleeding from surgical sites, rather than discrete hematomas. Imaging is typically used to evaluate complications of bleeding (e.g., hemarthrosis, intracranial hemorrhage) rather than diagnosing the disorder itself.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2021 Guidelines for the Management of von Willebrand Disease. These guidelines provide recommendations for diagnosis, classification, and treatment strategies including desmopressin, vWF concentrates, and antifibrinolytics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Factor X deficiency | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | von Willebrand’s disease | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Factor VIII deficiency (true hemophilia) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Factor IX deficiency (Christmas disease) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Factor V deficiency (parahemophilia) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) von Willebrand disease is the most common hemostatic disorder transmitted by autosomal-dominant mode** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
