  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When platelets plummet on heparin, it's time to hit the brakes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Discontinue heparin. The patient's severe thrombocytopenia (platelet count 30,000/mm3) occurring on the seventh day of heparin therapy is highly suggestive of Heparin-Induced Thrombocytopenia (HIT) Type II, a life-threatening complication requiring immediate cessation of heparin.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHeparin-Induced Thrombocytopenia (HIT) Type II is an immune-mediated adverse drug reaction characterized by the formation of antibodies against the heparin-platelet factor 4 (PF4) complex. This leads to platelet activation, aggregation, and consumption, resulting in thrombocytopenia and a paradoxical prothrombotic state. The typical onset is 5-10 days after heparin initiation, or sooner with prior heparin exposure. A platelet count drop of >50% from baseline or below 100,000/mm3, especially in the context of new thrombosis, mandates immediate discontinuation of all heparin products and initiation of an alternative anticoagulant.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Continue with heparin at the same dosage) is incorrect because continuing heparin in the setting of HIT Type II would exacerbate platelet consumption, increase the risk of thrombosis, and potentially lead to severe bleeding.\nOption B (Increase heparin) is incorrect as it would worsen the underlying immune reaction and increase the risk of both thrombosis and hemorrhage.\nOption C (Decrease heparin) is incorrect because any amount of heparin can perpetuate the immune response in HIT Type II, making complete cessation necessary.\nOption E (Continue heparin and start warfarin (Coumadin)) is incorrect. Continuing heparin is contraindicated, and initiating warfarin alone in acute HIT can lead to warfarin-induced skin necrosis if the platelet count has not recovered and an alternative non-heparin anticoagulant is not also used.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | HIT Type I (Non-immune) | HIT Type II (Immune-mediated) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Onset | Early (1-2 days) | Delayed (5-10 days, or sooner with prior exposure) |\n| Platelet Count | Mild drop (>100,000/mm3) | Significant drop (<100,000/mm3 or >50% from baseline) |\n| Mechanism | Direct effect of heparin on platelets | IgG antibodies against heparin-PF4 complex |\n| Clinical Significance | Benign, no thrombosis risk | High risk of thrombosis (venous and arterial) |\n| Management | Continue heparin | Discontinue all heparin, start alternative anticoagulant (e.g., argatroban, bivalirudin) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: New thrombocytopenia on heparin? Think HIT, especially if it's severe and delayed.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, you might see new or worsening deep vein thrombosis (DVT) or arterial thrombosis, despite therapeutic anticoagulation, which is a hallmark of HIT-associated thrombotic complications.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2018 guidelines for the management of HIT recommend immediate cessation of all heparin products and initiation of a non-heparin anticoagulant (e.g., argatroban, bivalirudin, fondaparinux) for suspected or confirmed HIT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Continue with heparin at the same dosage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Increase heparin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Decrease heparin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Discontinue heparin | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Continue heparin and start warfarin (Coumadin) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Thrombocytopenia is a common complica-tion of heparin therapy. The most common form, type I (seen in** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
