  "id": 130073,
  "question": "A60-year-old man had undergone exploratory laparotomy for perforated gastric ulcer with severe peritoneal contamination. Six hours after surgery, he is tachycardic, hypertensive, and has shallow respirations. Intubation and insti-tution of ventilatory support is indicated in the presence of which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Respiratory rate of 23 breaths/min",
    "B": "PaCO of 45 mm Hg",
    "C": "PaO of 55 mm Hg on room air",
    "D": "HR of 140 bpm",
    "E": "BP of 150/100 mm Hg"
  },
  "answer": "C) The criteria for need for ventilatory support are apnea, respiratory rate >30 breaths/min, PaO <60 mm Hg on room air, and PaCO >55 mm Hg (except in patients with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease [COPD]).",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When oxygen drops, intubation pops!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. A PaO2 of 55 mm Hg on room air indicates significant hypoxemia, which is a critical criterion for initiating ventilatory support to ensure adequate oxygenation and prevent organ damage. This patient's post-operative state with severe peritoneal contamination increases the risk of respiratory compromise.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe body's primary goal is to maintain adequate oxygen delivery to tissues. In the context of a 60-year-old man post-laparotomy for perforated gastric ulcer with peritonitis, shallow respirations suggest impaired respiratory mechanics, likely due to pain, abdominal distension, or developing sepsis. A PaO2 of 55 mm Hg on room air signifies acute respiratory failure, where the lungs are unable to adequately oxygenate the blood. This level of hypoxemia can lead to tissue hypoxia, metabolic acidosis, and multi-organ dysfunction if not corrected promptly with mechanical ventilation, which provides positive pressure to improve gas exchange and reduce the work of breathing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A respiratory rate of 23 breaths/min, while slightly elevated, is not an absolute indication for intubation; the threshold is typically >30 breaths/min.\nOption B (Incorrect): A PaCO2 of 45 mm Hg is within the normal range (35-45 mm Hg) or only mildly elevated, not meeting the critical threshold of >55 mm Hg for acute ventilatory support.\nOption D (Incorrect): A HR of 140 bpm is tachycardia and a sign of distress, but it is a systemic response and not a direct respiratory parameter indicating the need for intubation on its own.\nOption E (Incorrect): A BP of 150/100 mm Hg is hypertension, which is not a direct indication for intubation or ventilatory support.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Parameter | Indication for Ventilatory Support | Normal Range |\n|---|---|---|\n| Respiratory Rate | >30 breaths/min or Apnea | 12-20 breaths/min |\n| PaO2 (room air) | <60 mm Hg | 80-100 mm Hg |\n| PaCO2 (acute) | >55 mm Hg | 35-45 mm Hg |\n| Vital Capacity | <10-15 mL/kg | 60-70 mL/kg |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hypoxemia (PaO2 <60 mmHg on room air) is a critical trigger for intubation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a chest X-ray, you might see evidence of atelectasis, pleural effusions, or early signs of ARDS (bilateral infiltrates) that would further support the need for ventilatory support. Intraoperatively, severe abdominal distension or ongoing peritoneal contamination could predispose to post-operative respiratory compromise.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Surviving Sepsis Campaign Guidelines (2021) recommend early recognition and management of respiratory failure in septic patients, often necessitating mechanical ventilation for hypoxemic or hypercapnic respiratory failure.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Respiratory rate of 23 breaths/min | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | PaCO of 45 mm Hg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | PaO of 55 mm Hg on room air | ✅ Correct |\n| D | HR of 140 bpm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | BP of 150/100 mm Hg | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The criteria for need for ventilatory support are apnea, respiratory rate >30 breaths/min, PaO <60 m** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
