  "id": 130081,
  "question": "A50-year-old man with small-bowel fistula has been receiving TPN for the previous 3 weeks through a single-lumen central venous catheter. He is scheduled for exploratory laparotomy and closure of fistula. On the morning of the day of surgery, TPN is discontinued and intravenous infusion with balanced salt solution (Ringer’s lactate) is started. An hour later, the patient is found to be anxious, sweating, and tachycardic. What is the most likely cause?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Anxiety",
    "B": "Hypoglycemia",
    "C": "Hypovolemia",
    "D": "Unexplained hemorrhage",
    "E": "Hyperglycemia"
  },
  "answer": "B) Patients on TPN with hypertonic glucose solutions have elevated islet-cell production of insulin. Sudden cessation of TPN can lead to rebound hypoglycemia, because pancreatic islet-cell insulin secretion is not immediately downregulated. Symptoms are attrbutable to high catecholamine release secondary to hypo-glycemia. In general, the TPN rate should be reduced to 50 mL/h during surgery. This prevents both hypoglycemia and the hyper-glycemia seen with higher infusion rates. Weaning from TPN should be done gradually over 24–48 hours. In instances where TPN is discontinued suddenly, a solution of D W should be administered in the interim.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't stop TPN cold turkey; your pancreas doesn't get the memo!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Hypoglycemia. The patient's symptoms of anxiety, sweating, and tachycardia are classic signs of rebound hypoglycemia, which occurs when hypertonic glucose-containing TPN is abruptly discontinued.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPatients on TPN with high glucose concentrations develop sustained pancreatic islet-cell stimulation, leading to increased insulin production. When TPN is suddenly stopped, the exogenous glucose supply ceases, but the pancreas continues to secrete high levels of insulin for a period, causing a rapid and significant drop in blood glucose. The body's counter-regulatory response to hypoglycemia involves the release of catecholamines, which manifest as the observed anxiety, sweating, and tachycardia. To prevent this, TPN should be gradually weaned over 24-48 hours, or a dextrose-containing solution (e.g., D10W) should be administered if TPN is abruptly discontinued.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Anxiety) (Incorrect): While anxiety is a symptom, it is a physiological response to the underlying hypoglycemia, not the primary cause of the entire clinical picture.\nOption C (Hypovolemia) (Incorrect): The patient was started on a balanced salt solution (Ringer's lactate), making acute hypovolemia an unlikely primary cause of these specific symptoms, which are more indicative of metabolic derangement.\nOption D (Unexplained hemorrhage) (Incorrect): There are no signs or symptoms (e.g., hypotension, pallor, specific pain) to suggest hemorrhage, and the clinical presentation is not typical for acute blood loss.\nOption E (Hyperglycemia) (Incorrect): TPN, the source of high glucose, was discontinued. Therefore, hyperglycemia is highly improbable; hypoglycemia is the expected metabolic consequence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Pathophysiology | Management | Prevention |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Sudden TPN cessation | Rebound hypoglycemia due to persistent hyperinsulinemia | Administer D10W or D50W bolus, then D10W infusion | Gradual TPN weaning (24-48h) or reduce TPN to 50 mL/h intraoperatively |\n| TPN-associated hyperglycemia | Excessive glucose infusion, insulin resistance, stress response | Insulin administration (IV or subcutaneous) | Monitor blood glucose, adjust TPN glucose content, consider insulin drip |\n| TPN-associated liver dysfunction | Overfeeding, lipid overload, lack of enteral stimulation | Reduce TPN calories, cycle TPN, consider enteral feeds | Gradual introduction of TPN, avoid overfeeding, cycle TPN |\n| Catheter-related bloodstream infection (CRBSI) | Contamination of central line | Remove catheter, antibiotics | Strict aseptic technique, daily dressing changes, prompt removal when not needed |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Abrupt TPN cessation = rebound hypoglycemia. Always give dextrose.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the central venous catheter used for TPN would be visible, typically in the subclavian or internal jugular vein, with its tip in the SVC. No specific imaging findings for acute hypoglycemia itself.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition (ASPEN) Clinical Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in Adult Patients (2016). Recommends gradual tapering of TPN or administration of dextrose-containing solutions upon abrupt cessation to prevent hypoglycemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anxiety | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypoglycemia | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Hypovolemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Unexplained hemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hyperglycemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Patients on TPN with hypertonic glucose solutions have elevated islet-cell production of insulin. Su** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
