  "id": 130088,
  "question": "A 34-year-old male has serum sodium of 114 mEq/L. Correction of hyponatremia can be done by raising serum sodium by what amount?",
  "options": {
    "A": "1 mEq/L/h",
    "B": "3 mEq/L/h",
    "C": "5 mEq/L/h",
    "D": "7 mEq/L/h",
    "E": "10 mEq/L/h"
  },
  "answer": "A) Rapid correction of hyponatremia >1–2 mEq/L/h can lead to central pontine myeli-nolysis. Serum sodium level should not be raised >25 mEq/L within 48 hours of starting therapy. Only symptomatic hyponatremia requires treatment with hypertonic saline, oth-erwise fluid restriction is sufficient.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't rush hyponatremia; your pons will thank you.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, indicating that serum sodium should be raised by no more than 1 mEq/L/h. This slow correction rate is crucial to prevent severe neurological complications, specifically central pontine myelinolysis (CPM).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn chronic hyponatremia, brain cells adapt to the hypotonic environment by expelling osmolytes to prevent swelling. Rapid correction of serum sodium reverses this osmotic gradient too quickly, causing water to rush out of brain cells, leading to cellular dehydration and demyelination, particularly in the pons. Therefore, a gradual increase of 0.5-1 mEq/L/h, with a maximum of 8-10 mEq/L in the first 24 hours and 18 mEq/L in 48 hours, is recommended to allow the brain to re-equilibrate safely and prevent irreversible neurological damage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Raising serum sodium by 3 mEq/L/h is too rapid and significantly increases the risk of central pontine myelinolysis, especially in chronic hyponatremia.\nOption C (Incorrect): A correction rate of 5 mEq/L/h is dangerously fast and almost guarantees neurological damage, including central pontine myelinolysis, due to rapid osmotic shifts.\nOption D (Incorrect): Correcting hyponatremia at 7 mEq/L/h is far beyond safe limits and would lead to severe brain cell dehydration and irreversible neurological injury.\nOption E (Incorrect): A correction rate of 10 mEq/L/h is extremely aggressive and would almost certainly result in central pontine myelinolysis and other severe neurological sequelae.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Hyponatremia (<48h) | Chronic Hyponatremia (>48h) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Symptoms** | Often severe (seizures, coma) | Often mild or absent |\n| **Brain Adaptation** | Minimal | Brain cells expel osmolytes |\n| **Correction Rate** | Up to 4-6 mEq/L/h initially for severe symptoms, then slow | 0.5-1 mEq/L/h, max 8-10 mEq/L/24h |\n| **Risk of CPM** | Lower if corrected appropriately | High with rapid correction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Slow and steady wins the race against central pontine myelinolysis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, central pontine myelinolysis appears as a symmetric, non-enhancing T2 hyperintensity in the central pons, often described as a 'trident' or 'bat wing' sign, indicating demyelination.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Society of Endocrinology (ESE), European Society of Intensive Care Medicine (ESICM), and European Renal Association – European Dialysis and Transplant Association (ERA-EDTA) 2014 Clinical Practice Guideline on the Diagnostic and Treatment of Hyponatraemia recommends that the serum sodium concentration should not be increased by more than 10 mmol/L during the first 24 hours and by 8 mmol/L during every 24 hours thereafter.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1 mEq/L/h | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 3 mEq/L/h | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 5 mEq/L/h | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 7 mEq/L/h | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 10 mEq/L/h | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Rapid correction of hyponatremia >1–2 mEq/L/h can lead to central pontine myeli-nolysis. Serum sodiu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
