  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stored plasma: V and VIII vanish, leaving you wanting more.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies Factor V and Factor VIII as the coagulation factors most likely to be deficient in stored plasma. This is because these factors are highly labile and degrade significantly during the storage process, unlike other more stable coagulation factors.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFactor V (proaccelerin) and Factor VIII (antihemophilic factor) are known as labile coagulation factors. Their activity rapidly diminishes when plasma is stored at 4°C, which is the typical storage temperature for liquid plasma. This degradation is due to their inherent instability and proteolytic cleavage over time. In contrast, fresh-frozen plasma (FFP) is rapidly frozen after collection and stored at -18°C or colder, which preserves the activity of all coagulation factors, including the labile ones, making it a more complete replacement product for factor deficiencies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Factor II - prothrombin) (Incorrect): Factor II is a stable coagulation factor and maintains its activity well in stored plasma.\nOption C (Factor VII) (Incorrect): Factor VII is a stable coagulation factor and its levels are well-preserved in stored plasma.\nOption E (Factor IX) (Incorrect): Factor IX is a stable coagulation factor and its activity is maintained in stored plasma.\nOption F (Factor X) (Incorrect): Factor X is a stable coagulation factor and its levels remain adequate in stored plasma.\nOption G (Factor XII) (Incorrect): Factor XII is a stable coagulation factor and its activity is not significantly reduced in stored plasma.\nOption H (Calcium) (Incorrect): Calcium is an essential cofactor for coagulation but is not a protein factor itself and is not deficient in stored plasma in a clinically relevant way; rather, citrate in stored blood products chelates calcium.\nOption I (Fibrin split products) (Incorrect): Fibrin split products are markers of fibrinolysis, not a deficiency in plasma. Their presence indicates ongoing clot breakdown, not a lack of coagulation factors.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Stored Plasma (Liquid Plasma) | Fresh Frozen Plasma (FFP) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Factor V & VIII** | Significantly reduced/deficient | Preserved (full activity) |\n| **Other Coag Factors** | Preserved (stable factors) | Preserved (all factors) |\n| **Storage Temp** | 1-6°C | -18°C or colder |\n| **Shelf Life** | Up to 5 days (after thawing if frozen) | Up to 1 year (frozen) |\n| **Primary Use** | Volume expansion, stable factor replacement | Multiple factor deficiencies, DIC, liver disease |\n| **Risk of Hepatitis** | Present (similar to FFP) | Present (similar to stored plasma) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stored plasma loses its 'V' and 'VIII'igor over time.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, a patient requiring plasma transfusion for coagulopathy might exhibit diffuse microvascular bleeding, oozing from surgical sites, or persistent hemorrhage despite surgical hemostasis. Stored plasma itself appears as a clear, straw-colored liquid.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAABB (formerly American Association of Blood Banks) Guidelines for Transfusion Medicine (most recent edition, e.g., 2023). These guidelines recommend FFP or thawed plasma for patients with multiple coagulation factor deficiencies who are bleeding or undergoing an invasive procedure, emphasizing that FFP contains all coagulation factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Factor II (prothrombin) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Factor V | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Factor VII | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Factor VIII | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Factor IX | ❌ Incorrect |\n| F | Factor X | ❌ Incorrect |\n| G | Factor XII | ❌ Incorrect |\n| H | Calcium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| I | Fibrin split products | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, D) Factor V and VIII are deficient in stored plasma. In contrast, fresh-frozen plasma con-tains all the** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
