  "id": 130103,
  "question": "A 55-year-old male presents to the emergency room (ER) with a history suggestive of myocar-dial infarction, but without a diagnostic ECG pattern of ST-segment elevation. Which of the following ECG patterns strongly suggests that thrombolytic therapy should be administered.",
  "options": {
    "A": "Right bundle branch block",
    "B": "Left bundle branch block",
    "C": "Second-degree AV block (Wenckebach type)",
    "D": "Complete artrioventricular (AV) block",
    "E": "Runs of V tachycardia"
  },
  "answer": "B) The only ECG rhythm, which can obscure ST-segment changes seen in acute myocardial infarction, is left bundle branch block. All the other rhythms would allow visualization of the ST-segment changes.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When LBBB hides the truth, treat it like a STEMI!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Left Bundle Branch Block (LBBB). In a patient presenting with symptoms suggestive of myocardial infarction, the presence of a new or presumably new LBBB on ECG is considered a STEMI equivalent and necessitates immediate reperfusion therapy, such as thrombolytics.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLBBB significantly alters the normal ventricular depolarization and repolarization sequence, leading to wide QRS complexes and secondary ST-T wave changes that can mask the primary ST-segment elevation indicative of acute myocardial injury. This masking effect means that in the setting of acute coronary syndrome symptoms, a new or presumably new LBBB is treated as an acute ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) equivalent, demanding urgent reperfusion to preserve myocardial function and reduce mortality. The altered electrical activity makes direct assessment of ST segments unreliable for ischemia.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Right bundle branch block) (Incorrect): RBBB primarily affects the right ventricle's depolarization and does not typically obscure ST-segment changes in the left ventricle, allowing for direct assessment of ST elevation.\nOption C (Second-degree AV block (Wenckebach type)) (Incorrect): AV blocks are conduction disturbances between atria and ventricles and do not inherently alter ventricular depolarization in a way that masks ST-segment elevation.\nOption D (Complete artrioventricular (AV) block) (Incorrect): Similar to other AV blocks, complete AV block is a conduction disturbance that does not obscure the ST-segment changes indicative of myocardial ischemia.\nOption E (Runs of V tachycardia) (Incorrect): While ventricular tachycardia is a critical arrhythmia often associated with myocardial ischemia, it does not inherently mask ST-segment elevation in the same way LBBB does. Its presence might indicate ischemia, but it's not the *masking* pattern.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| ECG Pattern | Impact on STEMI Diagnosis | Reperfusion Indication (with symptoms) |\n|---|---|---|\n| New/Presumed New LBBB | Masks ST-elevation; considered STEMI equivalent | Yes, urgent |\n| RBBB | Does not mask ST-elevation; ST changes can be assessed | Yes, if ST elevation present |\n| AV Blocks (2nd/3rd degree) | Does not mask ST-elevation; ST changes can be assessed | Yes, if ST elevation present |\n| Ventricular Tachycardia | May indicate ischemia, but does not mask ST-elevation | Yes, if STEMI criteria met or unstable |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: New LBBB + MI symptoms = STEMI equivalent, treat urgently!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ECG, LBBB is characterized by a wide QRS (>0.12s), dominant S wave in V1, and broad, notched R wave in lateral leads (I, aVL, V5, V6). An angiogram would reveal the culprit coronary artery occlusion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2013 ACCF/AHA Guideline for the Management of ST-Elevation Myocardial Infarction: Recommends that patients with symptoms of ischemia and new or presumably new LBBB should be treated as STEMI and receive reperfusion therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Right bundle branch block | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Left bundle branch block | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Second-degree AV block (Wenckebach type) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Complete artrioventricular (AV) block | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Runs of V tachycardia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The only ECG rhythm, which can obscure ST-segment changes seen in acute myocardial infarction, is le** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
