  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Milky discharge? Think pituitary, not just breast tissue!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nGalactorrhea, a milky discharge from the nipple in non-pregnant women, is most commonly associated with a pituitary adenoma. Specifically, a prolactinoma, a type of pituitary adenoma, leads to hyperprolactinemia, which directly stimulates milk production.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe anterior pituitary gland produces prolactin, a hormone essential for lactation. A pituitary adenoma, particularly a prolactinoma, can autonomously secrete excessive amounts of prolactin. This hyperprolactinemia overrides the normal tonic inhibition of dopamine on prolactin release, leading to inappropriate milk production from the mammary glands. Other causes of hyperprolactinemia include certain medications (e.g., antipsychotics, antidepressants), hypothyroidism, and chest wall stimulation, but a pituitary adenoma is a primary endocrine cause requiring specific evaluation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fibroadenoma is a common benign breast tumor composed of glandular and stromal tissue. It does not typically cause nipple discharge, especially not milky galactorrhea, as it has no direct hormonal effect on prolactin levels.\nOption B (Incorrect): Tubular adenoma is another rare, benign epithelial tumor of the breast. Like fibroadenomas, it is a structural lesion and does not cause hormonal imbalances leading to galactorrhea.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hyperparathyroidism is a condition of excessive parathyroid hormone secretion, leading to hypercalcemia. While it affects endocrine function, it has no direct causal link to elevated prolactin levels or galactorrhea.\nOption E (Incorrect): A breast abscess is a localized collection of pus within the breast tissue, usually due to infection. The discharge from an abscess would be purulent (pus-like), not milky, and is associated with inflammation, pain, and fever, not hormonal imbalance.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nipple Discharge Type | Common Causes | Key Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Milky (Galactorrhea) | Prolactinoma, medications (e.g., antipsychotics), hypothyroidism, stress, chest wall stimulation | Bilateral, multiductal, non-bloody, often spontaneous |\n| Purulent | Breast abscess, mastitis | Unilateral, single duct, thick, foul-smelling, associated with inflammation/infection |\n| Bloody | Intraductal papilloma, ductal ectasia, ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS), invasive carcinoma | Unilateral, single duct, spontaneous, may be associated with a palpable mass |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Galactorrhea in a non-pregnant woman demands prolactin level check and pituitary imaging.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI of the brain, a pituitary adenoma (prolactinoma) would appear as a well-circumscribed mass within the sella turcica, often enhancing with contrast. Microadenomas are <10mm, macroadenomas >10mm.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of Hyperprolactinemia (2011, updated 2023). It recommends measuring serum prolactin levels in patients with galactorrhea and considering pituitary imaging (MRI) if levels are elevated and other causes are excluded.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fibroadenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tubular adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pituitary adenoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Hyperparathyroidism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Breast abscess | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Galactorrhea is fairly common up to old age. The discharge may vary in color from brown to milky. Ho** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
