  "answer": "C) This entity is known as Mondor’s disease and is caused by superficial thrombophlebitis usually induced by surgery, infection, or trauma. The process is self-limiting and resolves within 2–10 weeks.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a cord appears, think Mondor's; it's a benign, self-limiting vein game.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Superficial thrombophlebitis. The clinical presentation of a painful, palpable subcutaneous cord after breast surgery or trauma is classic for Mondor's disease, which is superficial thrombophlebitis of the thoracoepigastric or lateral thoracic veins.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMondor's disease is characterized by inflammation and thrombosis of superficial veins, most commonly affecting the breast, chest wall, or axilla. It is often triggered by trauma, surgery (like a breast biopsy), or vigorous exercise. The condition is self-limiting, typically resolving spontaneously within 2 to 10 weeks, and management is primarily symptomatic with NSAIDs and warm compresses. The palpable cord represents the thrombosed vein, which can be tender and sometimes associated with skin retraction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Fat necrosis) (Incorrect): Fat necrosis typically presents as a firm, irregular mass, sometimes with skin dimpling or retraction, but not usually as a linear, painful cord. It's a sterile inflammatory process of adipose tissue.\nOption B (Infection) (Incorrect): While infection can cause pain and inflammation, it would typically present with more overt signs such as erythema, warmth, swelling, purulent discharge, or fever, rather than a distinct subcutaneous cord.\nOption D (Suture granuloma) (Incorrect): A suture granuloma is a localized inflammatory reaction to suture material, presenting as a firm nodule or mass, not a linear cord. It's usually less diffuse and more focal than Mondor's disease.\nOption E (Misdiagnosed breast cancer) (Incorrect): Breast cancer rarely presents as a painful, superficial linear cord. While some inflammatory breast cancers can cause skin changes, a cord-like presentation after a benign biopsy is highly atypical for malignancy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Etiology | Presentation | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Mondor's Disease** | Trauma, surgery, inflammation | Painful, palpable subcutaneous cord; self-limiting | NSAIDs, warm compresses |\n| **Fat Necrosis** | Trauma, surgery, radiation | Firm, irregular mass; can mimic cancer | Observation, excision if symptomatic |\n| **Hematoma** | Post-surgical bleeding | Swelling, bruising, palpable mass; can be painful | Observation, drainage if large/symptomatic |\n| **Suture Granuloma** | Reaction to suture material | Firm, localized nodule; can be tender | Observation, excision if symptomatic/persistent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A painful, linear cord post-breast biopsy is Mondor's until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, Mondor's disease appears as a non-compressible, tubular, anechoic or hypoechoic structure within the subcutaneous fat, often with a 'string of beads' appearance and absent color Doppler flow.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBS) Consensus Guideline on Image-Guided Breast Biopsy (2018): Addresses post-biopsy complications, though Mondor's is typically managed symptomatically.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fat necrosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Superficial thrombophlebitis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Suture granuloma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Misdiagnosed breast cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) This entity is known as Mondor’s disease and is caused by superficial thrombophlebitis usually induc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
