  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Supraclavicular nodes are locally advanced, not distantly spread.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is IIIC. This patient's breast cancer is classified as Stage IIIC because the presence of ipsilateral supraclavicular lymph node metastasis, as per the current AJCC staging system, places it in this locally advanced category.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe AJCC 8th edition staging system for breast cancer specifically reclassified ipsilateral supraclavicular lymph node involvement from Stage IV (distant metastatic disease) to Stage IIIC (locally advanced disease). This distinction is crucial as it guides treatment strategies, often necessitating neoadjuvant systemic therapy to downstage the disease before local treatment. While still representing significant disease burden, IIIC implies regional spread amenable to aggressive local and systemic treatment, unlike Stage IV which indicates widespread dissemination.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Stage IV indicates distant metastatic disease (e.g., lung, liver, bone). While supraclavicular nodes were historically considered Stage IV, the current AJCC staging reclassifies them as IIIC.\nOption C (Incorrect): Stage IIB typically involves larger tumors (T2, N1 or T3, N0) or more extensive axillary nodal involvement (T2, N1), but does not include supraclavicular nodes.\nOption D (Incorrect): Stage IIIB involves locally advanced disease with direct extension to the chest wall or skin (T4), or internal mammary nodes, but not supraclavicular nodes.\nOption E (Incorrect): Stage IIA involves smaller tumors (T1, N1 or T2, N0) or minimal axillary nodal involvement, which is less advanced than the patient's presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stage | Key Features |\n|---|---|\n| IIA | T1 N1 M0 or T2 N0 M0 |\n| IIB | T2 N1 M0 or T3 N0 M0 |\n| IIIC | Any T, N3 M0 (including ipsilateral supraclavicular nodes) |\n| IV | Any T, Any N, M1 (distant metastasis) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ipsilateral supraclavicular node = IIIC, not IV.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or PET scan, an enlarged, hypermetabolic supraclavicular lymph node would be visible, confirming regional spread. Fine needle aspiration (FNA) or core biopsy would confirm malignancy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology: Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024). Recommends systemic therapy for Stage IIIC disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | IIIC | ✅ Correct |\n| B | IV | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | IIB | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | IIIB | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | IIA | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Ipsilateral supraclavicular lymph node dis-ease is stage IIIC in breast cancer. The new AJCC staging** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
