  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pregnancy doesn't stop cancer, but it changes the rules.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Breast cancer is indeed the most common cancer diagnosed during pregnancy, making this a crucial point for patient education and management. Understanding its unique characteristics and treatment considerations during gestation is paramount.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBreast cancer is the most frequently diagnosed malignancy during pregnancy, occurring in approximately 1 in 3,000 to 1 in 10,000 pregnancies. These cancers often present at a later stage and tend to be more aggressive, frequently characterized by estrogen receptor-negative (ER-), progesterone receptor-negative (PR-), and HER2-positive subtypes. This aggressive biology, coupled with diagnostic delays due to physiological breast changes in pregnancy, contributes to a generally poorer prognosis compared to non-pregnant women of similar age and stage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Chemotherapy, specifically non-methotrexate regimens, can be safely administered to pregnant patients after the first trimester, not only after delivery. \nOption B (Incorrect): Therapeutic abortion is not a requirement to proceed with radiotherapy. Radiotherapy is generally contraindicated during pregnancy and is typically deferred until postpartum, or mastectomy is performed. \nOption D (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is contraindicated during pregnancy due to potential fetal harm and is therefore not indicated. It is usually postponed until after delivery. \nOption E (Incorrect): Contrary to this statement, breast cancers diagnosed during pregnancy are typically more aggressive and are often estrogen receptor-negative (ER-) and progesterone receptor-negative (PR-).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Breast Cancer in Pregnancy | General Breast Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Incidence** | Most common cancer during pregnancy | Most common cancer in women |\n| **ER/PR Status** | Usually ER-/PR- (more aggressive) | Often ER+/PR+ |\n| **Chemotherapy** | Possible after 1st trimester (non-methotrexate) | Standard, depends on stage/type |\n| **Radiotherapy** | Contraindicated during pregnancy, deferred postpartum | Standard for breast conservation or post-mastectomy with high risk |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Breast cancer is the most common cancer in pregnancy, often ER- and treatable with chemo post-1st trimester.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, a palpable mass in a pregnant woman should be evaluated with ultrasound first, followed by mammography with abdominal shielding if indicated. Biopsy is essential for diagnosis. Intraoperatively, sentinel lymph node biopsy can be performed safely using technetium-99m, avoiding blue dye.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023): Recommends that chemotherapy can be considered after the first trimester, and radiation therapy should be delayed until after delivery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | She cannot undergo chemotherapy until after she delivers. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | She should have a therapeutic abortion in order to proceed with radiotherap | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Breast cancer is the most common cancer during pregnancy. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Radiotherapy is indicated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Most of these cancers are ER+. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Breast cancer is the most common cancer during pregnancy. It is usually ER–/PR–. Patients can underg** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
