  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keep it simple: Hands-on and mammograms save lives.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. This option accurately reflects the standard of care for breast cancer follow-up, which prioritizes routine clinical examination and yearly mammography due to their proven efficacy in detecting recurrence or new primary cancers. Other tests lack evidence of survival benefit in asymptomatic patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRoutine clinical examinations every 3-6 months for the first 5 years are crucial for detecting local recurrence, new primary cancers, or symptoms suggestive of distant metastasis. Yearly mammography is the cornerstone of imaging surveillance, effectively identifying new primary cancers in either breast or local recurrence in the treated breast. The rationale for these specific recommendations is based on extensive clinical trials demonstrating their utility in early detection, without the added cost, radiation exposure, or anxiety associated with more aggressive, unproven surveillance strategies. The absence of a survival advantage for other routine tests reinforces this focused approach.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Blood tumor markers like CA15-3 are not routinely recommended for surveillance in asymptomatic patients due to a lack of proven survival benefit and potential for false positives leading to unnecessary anxiety and further investigations.\nOption B (Incorrect): Routine monitoring of liver function tests (LFTs) every 3-6 months is not standard practice for breast cancer follow-up unless there are specific clinical indications or symptoms suggestive of liver metastasis or drug toxicity.\nOption C (Incorrect): Yearly bone scans are not recommended for routine surveillance in asymptomatic patients. Imaging for distant metastasis (including bone scans) is reserved for patients with symptoms or suspicious findings on other tests.\nOption E (Incorrect): Yearly breast MRI with gadolinium is not routinely recommended for surveillance after lumpectomy and radiation in all patients. Mammography remains the primary imaging modality for surveillance; MRI is typically reserved for high-risk screening or specific diagnostic indications.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Surveillance Test | Recommendation | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Clinical Exam | Recommended (3-6 months for 5 years, then annually) | Detects local recurrence, new primary, symptoms of mets |\n| Mammography | Recommended (annually) | Detects new primary or local recurrence |\n| Tumor Markers (e.g., CA15-3) | Not Recommended | No survival benefit, high false positive rate, anxiety |\n| Routine Imaging (CT, Bone Scan, PET, MRI) | Not Recommended (for asymptomatic) | No survival benefit, radiation exposure, cost, false positives |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Clinical exam and mammogram are the pillars of breast cancer surveillance.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a surveillance mammogram, a new spiculated mass or architectural distortion in the treated breast or a new mass in the contralateral breast would raise suspicion for recurrence or a new primary.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer Survivorship (2023) recommend annual mammography and regular clinical examinations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Blood tumor markers drawn every 3–6 months after treatment. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Routine monitoring of liver function tests (LFTs) every 3–6 months after tr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Yearly bone scans. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Routine clinical examination every 3–6 months for the first 5 years after t | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Yearly breast MRI with gadolinium. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Follow-up after breast cancer treatment is very variable. There is no consensus and no follow-up tes** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
