  "answer": "A) Cancer of the breast in males constitutes <1% of total cases. It tends to present at a more advanced stage in men than in women, because it is often overlooked. It may easily be confused with the more commonly occurring condition of gynecomastia. Careful clinical radiological follow-up studies are indicated.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't overlook the male breast; cancer can lurk there too!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, <1%, because male breast cancer is a rare disease, accounting for a very small fraction of all breast cancer cases. This low incidence often leads to delayed diagnosis due to lack of awareness and misattribution to more common benign conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMale breast cancer constitutes less than 1% of all breast cancer diagnoses, making it a statistically uncommon malignancy. Its rarity often contributes to a delayed presentation, as symptoms may be overlooked by both patients and clinicians, or initially mistaken for benign conditions like gynecomastia. The absence of routine screening for men, unlike women, further exacerbates this issue, leading to diagnosis at a more advanced stage with potentially poorer prognoses.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 4% is significantly higher than the actual incidence of male breast cancer, which is well under 1%.\nOption C (Incorrect): 7% is a substantial overestimation of the true prevalence of breast cancer in males.\nOption D (Incorrect): 10% represents an extremely high and inaccurate figure for male breast cancer incidence.\nOption E (Incorrect): >10% is grossly incorrect, as male breast cancer is a rare disease, not a common one.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Male Breast Cancer | Female Breast Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | <1% of all breast cancers | ~1 in 8 women lifetime risk |\n| Typical Age | Older (60-70s) | Younger (50-60s, but can be any age) |\n| Presentation | Often later stage, palpable mass, nipple changes | Palpable mass, screening detection, nipple changes |\n| Histology | Predominantly invasive ductal carcinoma | Diverse, including ductal, lobular, etc. |\n| Prognosis | Generally worse due to late presentation | Variable, depends on stage and biology |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Male breast cancer is rare, often late, and easily missed.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, male breast cancer often presents as a subareolar, eccentric, irregular mass with spiculated margins or microcalcifications. Intraoperatively, it typically appears as a firm, fixed, irregular mass, often involving the nipple-areolar complex due to the limited breast tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., Version 1.2024). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of male breast cancer, emphasizing the need for similar diagnostic workup and treatment principles as female breast cancer, adapted for the male anatomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | <1% | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 4% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 7% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 10% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | >10% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Cancer of the breast in males constitutes <1% of total cases. It tends to present at a more advanced** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
