  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let GCA steal their sight; steroids are the light!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Temporal Arteritis. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic triad of severe, acute onset temporal headache, visual changes, and systemic inflammatory symptoms (sweating, malaise, low-grade fever) in an elderly patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTemporal arteritis, also known as Giant Cell Arteritis (GCA), is a systemic vasculitis primarily affecting medium-to-large arteries, particularly branches of the carotid artery. The inflammation of the temporal artery causes the characteristic throbbing headache. Ocular involvement, often due to ischemic optic neuropathy from ophthalmic artery involvement, can lead to irreversible vision loss, making prompt diagnosis and high-dose corticosteroid treatment critical. Diagnosis is typically confirmed by temporal artery biopsy showing inflammatory cell infiltrates and giant cells, though ultrasound can also be used.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Myocardial infarction (MI)) (Incorrect): MI presents with chest pain, dyspnea, and other cardiac symptoms, not primarily a temporal headache and vision changes.\nOption B (Pneumonia) (Incorrect): Pneumonia is a lung infection characterized by cough, fever, and respiratory distress, not the specific neurological and inflammatory symptoms described.\nOption C (Diabetes) (Incorrect): Diabetes is a metabolic disorder with chronic symptoms like polyuria, polydipsia, and weight changes, not an acute presentation of severe headache and vision loss.\nOption D (Cerebral vascular accident) (Incorrect): While a CVA can cause acute neurological deficits, the specific constellation of severe temporal headache, vision changes, and prominent systemic inflammatory symptoms (sweating, malaise, low-grade fever) points more directly to a vasculitic process like temporal arteritis rather than a typical stroke.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Temporal Arteritis (GCA) | Migraine | CVA (Ischemic Stroke) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Age** | >50 years (typically >60) | Any age (often younger) | Any age (risk increases with age) |\n| **Headache** | Severe, unilateral temporal, throbbing | Unilateral/bilateral, throbbing, pulsatile | Variable, often sudden, can be absent |\n| **Vision Changes** | Acute, transient or permanent loss (amaurosis fugax, AION) | Aura (scintillating scotoma), photophobia | Monocular/binocular vision loss, diplopia, visual field defects |\n| **Systemic Symptoms** | Fever, malaise, jaw claudication, weight loss, polymyalgia rheumatica | Nausea, vomiting, phonophobia | Focal neurological deficits (weakness, speech changes) |\n| **Key Diagnostic** | ESR/CRP elevation, temporal artery biopsy/ultrasound | Clinical criteria | Imaging (CT/MRI brain) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: New onset temporal headache + vision changes + systemic symptoms in an elderly patient = GCA. Treat urgently!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound of the temporal arteries may show a \"halo sign\" (hypoechoic wall thickening) or stenosis/occlusion. Temporal artery biopsy reveals transmural inflammation with giant cells, fragmentation of the internal elastic lamina, and intimal hyperplasia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Rheumatology (ACR) 2021 Guideline for the Management of Giant Cell Arteritis. It recommends immediate high-dose glucocorticoid therapy upon suspicion of GCA to prevent irreversible vision loss, followed by consideration of adjunctive therapies like tocilizumab.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Myocardial infarction (MI) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pneumonia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Diabetes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cerebral vascular accident | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Temporal arteritis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Temporal artery inflammation causes severe throbbing unilateral temporal headache, low-grade fever, ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
