  "id": 130154,
  "question": "A 60-year-old veteran with a 40-pack year smoking history underwent supraglottic laryn-gectomy and right radical neck dissection for laryngeal squamous cell cancer. Postoperatively, he complained of difficulty swallowing. The most likely cause of his symptom was which of the following:",
  "options": {
    "A": "Recurrent cancer",
    "B": "Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury",
    "C": "Superior laryngeal nerve injury",
    "D": "Sternocleidomastoid muscle injury",
    "E": "Brain metastasis"
  },
  "answer": "C) Dysphagia and aspiration can result from disruption of the internal branch of the superior laryngeal nerve, resulting in sensory loss of the larynx. Contralateral superior laryngeal nerve compensation usually corrects these symptoms.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Laryngeal sensation is the unsung hero of safe swallowing.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Post-supraglottic laryngectomy and neck dissection, dysphagia is a common complication. Injury to the superior laryngeal nerve, particularly its internal branch, leads to sensory loss in the larynx, impairing the protective cough reflex and coordination of swallowing, making it the most likely cause of the patient's difficulty swallowing.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe superior laryngeal nerve (SLN) divides into internal and external branches. The internal branch is purely sensory, providing sensation to the laryngeal mucosa above the vocal cords, including the epiglottis and aryepiglottic folds. This sensation is crucial for triggering the swallow reflex and protecting the airway from aspiration. Damage during neck dissection or laryngectomy can result in a \"silent aspiration\" risk due to impaired sensation, where food or liquid enters the airway without eliciting a cough, leading to dysphagia and aspiration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Recurrent cancer) (Incorrect): While possible in the long term, it is highly unlikely to be the immediate post-operative cause of dysphagia. Dysphagia from recurrence typically develops gradually.\nOption B (Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury) (Incorrect): RLN injury primarily causes vocal cord paralysis, leading to hoarseness and aspiration due to glottic incompetence. While aspiration can cause dysphagia, the primary symptom of \"difficulty swallowing\" in this context, especially after supraglottic laryngectomy, points more towards sensory deficits affecting swallow initiation and coordination rather than glottic closure issues alone.\nOption D (Sternocleidomastoid muscle injury) (Incorrect): Injury to the SCM muscle, common in radical neck dissection, primarily affects neck movement and cosmesis, not directly the act of swallowing.\nOption E (Brain metastasis) (Incorrect): Brain metastasis is a distant complication and would present with broader neurological symptoms. It is highly improbable as the immediate and most likely cause of isolated dysphagia post-operatively without other neurological signs.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve Branch | Primary Function | Injury Symptom |\n|---|---|---|\n| Superior Laryngeal Nerve (Internal) | Sensory to supraglottic larynx (above vocal cords) | Dysphagia, aspiration (silent aspiration) due to impaired sensation and cough reflex |\n| Superior Laryngeal Nerve (External) | Motor to cricothyroid muscle | Loss of vocal pitch, vocal fatigue, inability to tense vocal cords |\n| Recurrent Laryngeal Nerve | Motor to all intrinsic laryngeal muscles (except cricothyroid); Sensory to subglottic larynx | Hoarseness, dysphonia, aspiration (glottic insufficiency) due to vocal cord paralysis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-laryngectomy dysphagia = think SLN sensory loss.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring endoscopy, impaired laryngeal sensation above the vocal cords (e.g., lack of cough reflex to touch) would be observed. Intraoperatively, the superior laryngeal nerve is at risk during dissection around the superior thyroid artery and hyoid bone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (e.g., Version 1.2024) recommend comprehensive swallowing assessment and rehabilitation post-laryngectomy to address dysphagia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Recurrent cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Superior laryngeal nerve injury | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Sternocleidomastoid muscle injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Brain metastasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Dysphagia and aspiration can result from disruption of the internal branch of the superior laryngeal** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
