  "question": "A 35-year-old man with duodenal stump leak after partial gastrectomy is receiving central parenteral nutrition containing the standard D W, 4.25% amino acid solution. Which is TRUE of essential fatty acid deficiency seen after hyperalimentation?",
  "options": {
    "A": "It occurs if soybean oil is given only once weekly.",
    "B": "It is usually noted at the end of the first week.",
    "C": "It causes dry scaly skin with loss of hair.",
    "D": "It is accompanied by hypercholesterolemia.",
    "E": "It is treated with insulin."
  },
  "answer": "C) 63. (C) Essential fatty acid deficiency usually occurs if hyperalimentation is extended for more than 1 month and when soybean oil is not administered at least twice a week. There is a decrease in linolenic, linoleic, and arachidonic acids and an increase in oleic and palmitoleic acid. In addition to the skin changes, there may be poor wound healing, increased susceptibil-ity to infection, lethargy, and thrombocytope-nia. It is characterized by a triene-to-tetraene ratio >0.4.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't forget the fats, or your skin will crack!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct because essential fatty acid deficiency (EFAD) manifests with characteristic dermatological changes like dry, scaly skin and hair loss, which are direct consequences of inadequate lipid intake during prolonged parenteral nutrition. This reflects the critical role of essential fatty acids in maintaining skin barrier function and cellular integrity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEssential fatty acids (EFAs), specifically linoleic and linolenic acids, are precursors to longer-chain polyunsaturated fatty acids like arachidonic acid, which are vital for cell membrane structure, eicosanoid synthesis, and overall cellular function. In the context of hyperalimentation (TPN) without adequate lipid emulsion, the body's stores of these EFAs become depleted. This leads to a shift in fatty acid metabolism, characterized by a decrease in linolenic, linoleic, and arachidonic acids and a compensatory increase in oleic and palmitoleic acids, reflected by an elevated triene-to-tetraene ratio (>0.4). The resulting cellular dysfunction, particularly in rapidly dividing cells like those of the skin and hair follicles, manifests as dry, scaly skin, hair loss, poor wound healing, and increased susceptibility to infection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): EFAD typically occurs if soybean oil (lipid emulsion) is not administered at least twice a week, or if TPN is extended for more than a month without adequate lipid provision, not if given only once weekly.\nOption B (Incorrect): EFAD is usually noted after prolonged hyperalimentation, typically more than 1 month, not as early as the end of the first week, as the body's EFA stores take time to deplete.\nOption D (Incorrect): EFAD is not typically accompanied by hypercholesterolemia; in fact, lipid metabolism can be deranged, but hypercholesterolemia is not a defining feature and may even be lower due to overall lipid deficiency.\nOption E (Incorrect): EFAD is a nutritional deficiency treated by providing essential fatty acids (lipid emulsions), not with insulin, which is used to manage glucose metabolism.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Essential Fatty Acid Deficiency (EFAD) | Refeeding Syndrome | TPN-Associated Liver Disease (PNALD) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Cause** | Inadequate lipid emulsion in TPN, prolonged TPN (>1 month) | Rapid reintroduction of nutrition in malnourished patients | Prolonged TPN, overfeeding, lack of enteral stimulation, lipid overload |\n| **Key Symptoms** | Dry, scaly skin; hair loss; poor wound healing; lethargy; thrombocytopenia | Hypophosphatemia, hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia; fluid retention; cardiac arrhythmias | Elevated LFTs (AST, ALT, bilirubin); cholestasis; steatosis; fibrosis |\n| **Treatment** | Provide lipid emulsion (e.g., soybean oil, SMOFlipid) | Slow reintroduction of nutrition, electrolyte repletion (P, K, Mg) | Reduce TPN calories, cycle TPN, promote enteral feeding, consider alternative lipid emulsions |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prolonged TPN without lipids causes dry skin and hair loss.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile EFAD itself doesn't have specific imaging findings, the underlying duodenal stump leak might be visualized on an upper GI series with contrast showing extravasation, or on CT with oral contrast demonstrating a leak and potential fluid collections. Clinically, the skin changes of EFAD are visible on physical exam.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition (ASPEN) Clinical Guidelines: Parenteral Nutrition in Adults (2014) recommends providing adequate essential fatty acids to prevent deficiency.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It occurs if soybean oil is given only once weekly. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is usually noted at the end of the first week. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It causes dry scaly skin with loss of hair. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | It is accompanied by hypercholesterolemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It is treated with insulin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 63. (C) Essential fatty acid deficiency usually occurs if hyperalimentation is extended for more tha** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
