  "question": "A 32-year-old teacher presents at her physician’s office complaining of hearing loss in her right ear. Physical examination reveals cerumen completely obstructing the ear canal. Ear wax removal is recommended using which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Jet irrigation (Water Pik)",
    "B": "3% hydrogen peroxide ear drops",
    "C": "Irrigation of the eardrum if perforated",
    "D": "Aqueous irrigation if a bean is present",
    "E": "Aqueous irrigation if an insect is present far in the ear"
  },
  "answer": "B) 82. (B) Jet irrigation (e.g., Water Pik) should be avoided to remove cerumen impaction. Detergent ear drops (such as 3% hydrogen peroxide) may be used. Aqueous irrigation should be avoided if organic material is present, because further swelling will be induced.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When wax attacks, hydrogen peroxide hacks!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, 3% hydrogen peroxide ear drops. This is recommended because detergent ear drops are effective cerumenolytics, softening and breaking down ear wax, making it easier to remove or allowing it to clear spontaneously.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCerumen, or ear wax, is a mixture of secretions from sebaceous and ceruminous glands, along with desquamated epithelial cells. Detergent ear drops like 3% hydrogen peroxide act as cerumenolytics by releasing oxygen when in contact with cerumen, which helps to soften and break down the wax into smaller, more manageable pieces. This chemical action reduces the need for forceful mechanical removal, minimizing the risk of iatrogenic injury to the ear canal or tympanic membrane.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Jet irrigation (e.g., Water Pik) should be avoided due to the high pressure, which can cause tympanic membrane perforation, otitis externa, or push cerumen deeper into the canal.\nOption C (Incorrect): Irrigation of the eardrum if perforated is a contraindication for any form of ear irrigation, as it can introduce infection into the middle ear and cause pain.\nOption D (Incorrect): Aqueous irrigation if a bean is present is contraindicated because organic materials like beans absorb water, swell, and can become more firmly lodged, making removal more difficult and potentially causing more trauma.\nOption E (Incorrect): Aqueous irrigation if an insect is present far in the ear is contraindicated for similar reasons as other organic foreign bodies; the water can cause the insect to swell, making extraction harder and potentially causing more distress or injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Method | Indication | Contraindication/Caution |\n|---|---|---|\n| Detergent Ear Drops (e.g., 3% H2O2) | Softening impacted cerumen | Perforated TM, otitis externa, tympanostomy tubes |\n| Aqueous Irrigation | Softened cerumen, non-organic foreign bodies | Perforated TM, otitis externa, organic foreign bodies (e.g., beans, insects) |\n| Manual Removal (curette, suction) | Impacted cerumen, foreign bodies | Uncooperative patient, risk of TM perforation |\n| Jet Irrigation (Water Pik) | Generally avoided | High risk of TM perforation, otitis externa, pushing cerumen deeper |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Detergent drops soften wax; avoid irrigation with perforation or organic foreign bodies.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn otoscopy, cerumen impaction would appear as a yellowish-brown to dark brown, waxy mass completely or partially occluding the external auditory canal, obscuring visualization of the tympanic membrane.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery Foundation (AAO-HNSF) Clinical Practice Guideline: Cerumen Impaction (2017). It recommends cerumenolytic agents as a treatment option for cerumen impaction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Jet irrigation (Water Pik) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 3% hydrogen peroxide ear drops | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Irrigation of the eardrum if perforated | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Aqueous irrigation if a bean is present | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Aqueous irrigation if an insect is present far in the ear | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) 82. (B) Jet irrigation (e.g., Water Pik) should be avoided to remove cerumen impaction. Detergent ea** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
