  "answer": "D) 91. (D) Blowout fractures of the orbit exhibit epistaxis; subcutaneous emphysema and periorbital ecchymosis are also frequently encountered. Treatment of most severe injuries is by surgical repair, often by a lower lid blepharoplasty incision. Enopthalmous, lateral diplopia and blindness do not generally occur.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the orbit breaks, the nose often bleeds.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Epistaxis. Orbital floor fractures, often resulting from direct trauma like a baseball impact, frequently involve the maxillary sinus, leading to bleeding that manifests as a nosebleed.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOrbital floor fractures typically involve the thin bone separating the orbit from the maxillary sinus. The force of the impact can cause a fracture that extends into the sinus, leading to bleeding from the sinus mucosa. This blood can then drain into the nasal cavity, manifesting as epistaxis, making it a highly likely physical finding in such injuries. Other common findings include periorbital ecchymosis and subcutaneous emphysema.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Exophthalmos): Incorrect. Blowout fractures typically cause enophthalmos (posterior displacement of the globe) due to increased orbital volume from herniation of orbital contents into the sinus, not exophthalmos. The provided answer also states enophthalmos does not generally occur.\nOption B (Lateral diplopia): Incorrect. Lateral diplopia is typically associated with abducens nerve (CN VI) palsy or lateral rectus muscle entrapment, which is less common in isolated orbital floor fractures. The provided answer explicitly states lateral diplopia does not generally occur.\nOption C (Cheek numbness): Incorrect. While infraorbital nerve injury causing cheek numbness (hypoesthesia) is a common finding in orbital floor fractures, epistaxis (D) is also very common and is the designated correct answer in this context.\nOption E (Blindness): Incorrect. While severe orbital trauma can lead to blindness, it is not a generally occurring finding in isolated orbital floor fractures. It would indicate more severe complications like optic nerve injury or globe rupture. The provided answer explicitly states blindness does not generally occur.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign/Symptom | Description | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Epistaxis | Nosebleed | Fracture extending into maxillary sinus/nasal cavity |\n| Periorbital ecchymosis | Bruising around the eye | Soft tissue trauma, bleeding |\n| Subcutaneous emphysema | Air under the skin | Air from sinus/nasal cavity enters subcutaneous tissues |\n| Enophthalmos | Sunken eye | Increased orbital volume due to herniation of contents |\n| Infraorbital nerve paresthesia | Numbness of cheek/upper lip/teeth | Injury to infraorbital nerve along orbital floor |\n| Vertical diplopia | Double vision (vertical) | Entrapment of inferior rectus muscle |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Orbital floor fractures = epistaxis, infraorbital nerve injury, vertical diplopia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT scan will show a 'trapdoor' fracture of the orbital floor, herniation of orbital fat/inferior rectus muscle into the maxillary sinus, and fluid (blood) in the maxillary sinus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Pattern for Orbital Fractures (most recent year) recommends CT imaging for diagnosis and surgical repair for significant entrapment or enophthalmos.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Exophthalmos | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lateral diplopia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cheek numbness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Epistaxis | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Blindness | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 91. (D) Blowout fractures of the orbit exhibit epistaxis; subcutaneous emphysema and periorbital ecc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
