  "question": "A 2-year-old child undergoes tympanostomy tube placement for treatment of chronic bilateral serous otitis media. Which of the following complications is least likely to occur subsequent to surgery?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Otorrhea",
    "B": "Chronic perforation",
    "C": "Cholesteatoma",
    "D": "Tympanosclerosis",
    "E": "Scarring of the external auditory canal"
  },
  "answer": "E) 92. (E) Tympanostomy tube placement is performed through the external auditory canal with microscopic guidance. The tympanic membrane is directly visualized after clearing wax and debris from external auditory canal. Otorrhea is the most common sequela, requiring tube removal in 13.5% of long-term tubes and 0.9% of short-term tubes.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tubes fix the ear, but the canal stays clear!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E because tympanostomy tube placement primarily affects the tympanic membrane and middle ear, not the external auditory canal itself. While the canal is used for access, scarring of the canal is not a typical complication of this specific procedure. The other options represent known complications directly related to the tube or the tympanic membrane.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTympanostomy tube insertion involves a myringotomy (incision in the tympanic membrane) and placement of a small tube to ventilate the middle ear. This procedure directly impacts the tympanic membrane and the middle ear environment. Complications like otorrhea, chronic perforation, cholesteatoma, and tympanosclerosis are all directly related to the tympanic membrane incision, the presence of the tube, or the altered middle ear physiology. The external auditory canal, while providing access, is generally not traumatized to the extent of scarring.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Otorrhea) (Incorrect): Otorrhea (ear discharge) is the most common complication following tympanostomy tube placement, often due to infection.\nOption B (Chronic perforation) (Incorrect): A persistent tympanic membrane perforation is a known complication, occurring in a small percentage of cases after tube extrusion.\nOption C (Cholesteatoma) (Incorrect): Although rare, iatrogenic cholesteatoma can occur if squamous epithelium migrates through the myringotomy site into the middle ear.\nOption D (Tympanosclerosis) (Incorrect): Tympanosclerosis, characterized by white plaques on the tympanic membrane, is a common sequela of inflammation and tube placement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Description | Likelihood |\n|---|---|---|\n| Otorrhea | Ear discharge, often infectious | Most Common |\n| Tympanosclerosis | White calcified plaques on TM | Common |\n| Chronic Perforation | Persistent hole in TM after tube extrusion | Less Common (1-2%) |\n| Cholesteatoma | Epithelial ingrowth into middle ear | Rare but Serious |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tubes ventilate the middle ear, but the EAC is just the highway.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the external auditory canal is cleared of cerumen to visualize the tympanic membrane, where a small incision (myringotomy) is made, and the tube is inserted. Post-operatively, otorrhea would be visible as discharge, and tympanosclerosis as white plaques on otoscopy. Cholesteatoma might appear as a pearly mass behind the TM or through a perforation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery Foundation (AAO-HNSF) Clinical Practice Guideline: Otitis Media with Effusion (2016). This guideline discusses indications and potential complications of tympanostomy tube placement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Otorrhea | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chronic perforation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cholesteatoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Tympanosclerosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Scarring of the external auditory canal | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 92. (E) Tympanostomy tube placement is performed through the external auditory canal with microscopi** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
