  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Mono means EBV, don't forget the spleen!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Epstein-Barr virus (EBV). This verdict is accurate because EBV is the primary causative agent of infectious mononucleosis, a common viral illness characterized by its presence in the blood, leading to systemic symptoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEpstein-Barr virus (EBV) is a gammaherpesvirus that primarily infects B lymphocytes and epithelial cells. Upon infection, EBV establishes latency within B cells, leading to their proliferation and the activation of cytotoxic T lymphocytes, which are responsible for controlling the infection and causing the characteristic symptoms of mononucleosis, such as fever, pharyngitis, lymphadenopathy, and fatigue. The presence of atypical lymphocytes (Downey cells) in the peripheral blood smear is a hallmark of this immune response. EBV's ability to persist in B cells also links it to certain malignancies like Burkitt's lymphoma and nasopharyngeal carcinoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Human papillomavirus (HPV) is associated with cervical cancer, anogenital warts, and oropharyngeal cancers, not infectious mononucleosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): HIV causes acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) and related opportunistic infections, which is distinct from infectious mononucleosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Varicella zoster virus (VZV) is the cause of chickenpox and shingles, not infectious mononucleosis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Herpes type 2 virus (HSV-2) is primarily responsible for genital herpes, not infectious mononucleosis.\nOption F (Incorrect): Microcytic anemia is a type of anemia characterized by small red blood cells, a hematological condition, not a viral cause of mononucleosis.\nOption G (Incorrect): Autoimmune deficiency is a broad term for immune system dysfunction, not a specific viral etiology for mononucleosis.\nOption H (Incorrect): A meningioma is a type of brain tumor, completely unrelated to infectious mononucleosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Virus | Primary Disease | Other Associations |\n|---|---|---|\n| Epstein-Barr Virus (EBV) | Infectious Mononucleosis | Burkitt's Lymphoma, Nasopharyngeal Carcinoma |\n| Human Papillomavirus (HPV) | Warts, Cervical Dysplasia | Oropharyngeal Cancer, Anogenital Cancers |\n| Varicella Zoster Virus (VZV) | Chickenpox | Shingles (Herpes Zoster) |\n| Herpes Simplex Virus Type 2 (HSV-2) | Genital Herpes | Neonatal Herpes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EBV = Mono, Burkitt's, Nasopharyngeal CA.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound or CT), splenomegaly is a common finding in patients with infectious mononucleosis, which can predispose to splenic rupture.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC (2023) provides guidance on infectious mononucleosis, recommending supportive care, rest, and avoidance of contact sports due to splenic rupture risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Human papillomavirus (HPV) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Epstein-Barr virus | ✅ Correct |\n| C | HIV | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Varicella zoster virus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Herpes type 2 virus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| F | Microcytic anemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| G | Autoimmune deficiency | ❌ Incorrect |\n| H | Meningioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) 101. (B) Nasopharyngeal cancer is most closely associated with Epstein-Barr virus. This virus is als** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
