  "id": 130265,
  "question": "A 66-year-old female has had two MIs in the past. She is admitted to the emergency department in congestive heart failure. After admission and appropriate therapy her Holter monitor shows frequent PVCs and her ejection fraction is found to be 35%. Appropriate treatment would include which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Single chamber pacemaker",
    "B": "Cardioversion",
    "C": "Dual chamber pacemaker",
    "D": "Internal cardiac defibrillator (ICD)",
    "E": "Greenfield filter"
  },
  "answer": "D) 7. (D) ICD. In a patient with history of MI, congestive heart failure, and decreased ejection fraction coupled with frequent premature ventricular beats studies have shown that this subset of patient benefits from internal cardiac defibrillators, as the most frequent cause of death in these patients is sudden cardiac death from ventricular fibrillation. Single and dual chamber pacemakers are used for bradyarrythmias. The other choices do not apply.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a low EF shock you; an ICD can save you!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Internal cardiac defibrillator (ICD). This patient presents with a history of myocardial infarction, congestive heart failure, a significantly reduced ejection fraction (35%), and frequent premature ventricular contractions, placing her at high risk for sudden cardiac death due to ventricular arrhythmias.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPatients with ischemic cardiomyopathy, reduced left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF < 35%), and symptoms of heart failure are at increased risk for life-threatening ventricular tachyarrhythmias (ventricular tachycardia or ventricular fibrillation). These arrhythmias are often the cause of sudden cardiac death in this population. An ICD continuously monitors the heart rhythm and delivers appropriate therapy (antitachycardia pacing or defibrillation shock) to terminate these dangerous arrhythmias, thereby preventing sudden cardiac death. This is a crucial intervention for primary prevention in high-risk individuals or secondary prevention in those who have survived a prior event.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Single chamber pacemaker) (Incorrect): Single chamber pacemakers are primarily used for bradyarrhythmias (slow heart rates) or specific types of heart block, not for preventing sudden cardiac death from ventricular tachyarrhythmias.\nOption B (Cardioversion) (Incorrect): Cardioversion is an acute intervention used to terminate unstable tachyarrhythmias, not a chronic preventative measure for sudden cardiac death in a patient with chronic risk factors.\nOption C (Dual chamber pacemaker) (Incorrect): Similar to single chamber pacemakers, dual chamber pacemakers are indicated for bradyarrhythmias and atrioventricular conduction abnormalities, not for the prevention of ventricular fibrillation or ventricular tachycardia.\nOption E (Greenfield filter) (Incorrect): A Greenfield filter (inferior vena cava filter) is used to prevent pulmonary embolism in patients with deep vein thrombosis who have contraindications to anticoagulation. It has no role in the management or prevention of cardiac arrhythmias.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Device/Intervention | Primary Indication(s) | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Internal Cardiac Defibrillator (ICD) | Primary/secondary prevention of sudden cardiac death due to VT/VF in high-risk patients (e.g., LVEF < 35%, ischemic cardiomyopathy) | Monitors rhythm, delivers antitachycardia pacing or defibrillation shocks |\n| Pacemaker (Single/Dual Chamber) | Symptomatic bradycardia, high-grade AV block, sinus node dysfunction | Delivers electrical impulses to maintain adequate heart rate/rhythm |\n| Cardioversion | Acute termination of unstable tachyarrhythmias (e.g., AF with RVR, VT) | Delivers synchronized electrical shock to reset heart rhythm |\n| Greenfield Filter (IVC Filter) | Prevention of pulmonary embolism in DVT patients with contraindications to anticoagulation | Traps emboli migrating from lower extremities to lungs |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Low EF + PVCs = High SCD risk, think ICD.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a chest X-ray, an ICD appears as a pulse generator (battery/computer) typically implanted in the left pectoral region, with leads extending into the right atrium and/or right ventricle, often with a coil for defibrillation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 AHA/ACC/HRS Guideline for Management of Patients With Ventricular Arrhythmias and the Prevention of Sudden Cardiac Death recommends ICD implantation for primary prevention in patients with LVEF ≤35% due to ischemic heart disease at least 40 days post-MI and NYHA Class II or III symptoms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Single chamber pacemaker | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cardioversion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dual chamber pacemaker | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Internal cardiac defibrillator (ICD) | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Greenfield filter | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 7. (D) ICD. In a patient with history of MI, congestive heart failure, and decreased ejection fracti** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
