  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't operate on a ticking heart bomb!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, \"Increased frequency and severity of attacks of angina.\" This condition signifies unstable angina, indicating a rapidly worsening cardiac status and a high risk of perioperative myocardial infarction, making elective surgery highly dangerous.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUnstable angina is characterized by new-onset angina, accelerating angina (increasing frequency, intensity, or duration), or rest angina. It represents an acute coronary syndrome where there is an imbalance between myocardial oxygen supply and demand, often due to plaque rupture and non-occlusive thrombus formation. Proceeding with elective surgery in the presence of unstable angina significantly elevates the risk of perioperative cardiac events, including MI and death, due to the physiological stress of anesthesia and surgery. Therefore, cardiac stabilization and further evaluation (e.g., angiography, revascularization) are paramount before considering any elective procedure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): MI 9 months earlier. While a recent MI is a significant risk, an MI 9 months prior is generally considered stable enough for elective surgery, especially if the patient has been optimized and is asymptomatic. The highest risk period is typically within 3-6 months post-MI.\nOption B (Incorrect): Persistent nonspecific changes on ECG. Nonspecific ECG changes are common and, without other symptoms or signs, do not indicate acute cardiac instability or a contraindication to elective surgery. They require further investigation but are not as immediately concerning as unstable angina.\nOption D (Incorrect): Elevated alkaline phosphatase levels. Elevated alkaline phosphatase is an indicator of cholestasis or liver disease, which might be related to the cholecystectomy itself, but it is not a cardiac risk factor that would contraindicate elective surgery from a cardiovascular standpoint.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hypertension controlled with diuretics. Controlled hypertension, even with medication, is not a contraindication to elective surgery. Uncontrolled hypertension would be a concern, but \"controlled\" implies stability.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cardiac Condition | Preoperative Risk for Elective Surgery | Management Strategy |\n| :---------------- | :----------------------------------- | :------------------ |\n| Unstable Angina   | Very High (30% MI risk in 3 months)  | Defer surgery; urgent cardiac evaluation/stabilization |\n| MI < 6 months     | High                                 | Defer surgery if possible; optimize cardiac status |\n| MI > 6 months     | Moderate to Low                      | Proceed with surgery after full cardiac workup and optimization |\n| Controlled HTN    | Low                                  | Continue medications; monitor BP |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unstable angina trumps all other cardiac risks for elective surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative cardiac stress testing (e.g., exercise ECG, pharmacologic stress echo/nuclear scan) or coronary angiography would be indicated to assess the extent of coronary artery disease and guide revascularization if unstable angina is present. Intraoperatively, close hemodynamic monitoring (e.g., arterial line, CVP) and vigilance for ischemic changes on ECG are crucial if surgery proceeds after stabilization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2014 ACC/AHA Guideline on Perioperative Cardiovascular Evaluation and Management of Patients Undergoing Noncardiac Surgery. It recommends deferring elective noncardiac surgery in patients with unstable angina until the condition is treated and stabilized.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | MI 9 months earlier | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Persistent nonspecific changes on ECG | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Increased frequency and severity of attacks of angina | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Elevated alkaline phosphatase levels | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hypertension controlled with diuretics | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Changes in the nature of angina should alert the physician to the possible progression of the underl** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
