  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When chest pain walks in, make the heart work out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Stress electrocardiography because it directly assesses for inducible myocardial ischemia, which is the underlying cause of angina pectoris, especially in a patient with classic exertional symptoms. Given the patient's history and upcoming surgery, confirming the diagnosis and assessing risk is crucial.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStress electrocardiography involves monitoring the heart's electrical activity (ECG) while the patient exercises, typically on a treadmill or stationary bike, or receives pharmacologic stress. The goal is to increase myocardial oxygen demand to unmask ischemia. A positive test is indicated by significant ST-segment depression (typically >1 mm horizontal or downsloping) in two or more contiguous leads, which signifies subendocardial ischemia. It can also precipitate the patient's symptoms. The test is stopped if symptoms are severe, significant ST changes occur, or arrhythmias develop, indicating a high-risk patient.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cholesterol/high-density lipid ratio is a risk factor for coronary artery disease but does not diagnose active angina pectoris or inducible ischemia.\nOption B (Incorrect): Isoenzymes (e.g., troponin, CK-MB) are markers of acute myocardial injury or infarction, not the diagnostic test for stable angina pectoris.\nOption D (Incorrect): Echocardiography assesses cardiac structure and function, including wall motion abnormalities, but is not the primary diagnostic test for inducible ischemia in stable angina, though stress echo can be used.\nOption E (Incorrect): Chest x-ray provides information on lung fields, cardiac silhouette size, and great vessels but is not diagnostic for angina pectoris or coronary artery disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Method | Primary Use | Key Finding |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stress Electrocardiography | Inducible Ischemia (Angina) | ST-segment depression |\n| Cardiac Troponins/CK-MB | Acute Myocardial Infarction | Elevated enzyme levels |\n| Echocardiography | Cardiac Structure/Function | Wall motion abnormalities, EF |\n| Coronary Angiography | Coronary Artery Anatomy | Stenosis, blockages |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stress ECG unmasks inducible ischemia, the hallmark of angina.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an ECG during stress, you would observe horizontal or downsloping ST-segment depression of 1 mm or more, often accompanied by chest pain.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2021 AHA/ACC/ASE/CHEST/SAEM/SCCT/SCMR Guideline for the Evaluation and Diagnosis of Chest Pain: Recommends exercise ECG as a first-line test for patients with intermediate pretest probability of CAD who can exercise and have an interpretable ECG.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cholesterol/high-density lipid ratio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Isoenzymes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Stress electrocardiography | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Echocardiography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Chest x-ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) In about one-quarter of patients with angina pectoris, the ECG findings will be normal. Exercise ele** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
