  "answer": "B) Angioplasty and stenting of the iliac vessels has a patency rate of 75% at 5 years; PTA and stenting of all other vessels has a much lower patency than bypass procedures. The FDAhas only approved illiac artery stenting.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Go with the flow, especially in the iliacs!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Iliac artery. Angioplasty and stenting of iliac vessels demonstrate superior long-term patency rates, specifically around 75% at 5 years, which is significantly higher than endovascular interventions in more distal vessels. This makes them the preferred target for endovascular revascularization when feasible.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe excellent patency of iliac artery interventions stems from several anatomical and physiological advantages. Iliac arteries are large-caliber vessels with relatively straight courses, experiencing lower shear stress and less mechanical flexion compared to femoropopliteal or infrapopliteal segments. This favorable environment minimizes intimal hyperplasia and stent fracture, which are common causes of restenosis in smaller, more mobile arteries. The robust inflow and outflow also contribute to better hemodynamic outcomes and sustained patency.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Medial circumflex artery is a small, deep branch off the profunda femoris, rarely a primary target for angioplasty for PAD, and its small size would predict very poor patency.\nOption C (Incorrect): Superficial femoral artery (SFA) interventions are prone to restenosis due to vessel movement (flexion/extension of the knee), longer lesion lengths, and smaller diameter compared to iliacs, leading to lower patency rates.\nOption D (Incorrect): Popliteal artery interventions also suffer from significant mechanical stress across the knee joint and smaller caliber, resulting in patency rates inferior to iliac arteries.\nOption E (Incorrect): Tibial arteries are small-caliber vessels with high rates of restenosis and reocclusion after angioplasty or stenting, making them the most challenging segment for durable endovascular patency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Vessel Segment | Endovascular Patency (5-yr) | Bypass Patency (5-yr) | Key Challenges for Endovascular |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Iliac Artery | ~75% | >80% (Aorto-femoral) | Calcification, ostial lesions |\n| Superficial Femoral Artery (SFA) | ~50-60% | ~70-80% (Fem-Pop) | Mechanical stress, long lesions, intimal hyperplasia |\n| Popliteal Artery | ~40-50% | ~60-70% (Fem-Pop) | Mechanical stress, small diameter |\n| Tibial Arteries | ~20-30% | ~50-60% (Infrapopliteal) | Small diameter, diffuse disease, high restenosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Iliac artery stenting offers the best long-term endovascular patency in PAD.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn angiography, iliac artery stenosis appears as a focal narrowing or occlusion. During intervention, successful angioplasty and stenting result in immediate restoration of laminar flow and elimination of the pressure gradient, visible as a widely patent lumen on completion angiography.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AHA/ACC Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease. It recommends endovascular therapy as a first-line treatment for symptomatic iliac artery disease due to its high success and patency rates, especially for TASC A and B lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Medial circumflex artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Iliac artery | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Superficial femoral artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Popliteal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Tibial arteries | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Angioplasty and stenting of the iliac vessels has a patency rate of 75% at 5 years; PTA and stenting** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
