  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Selective nerve cuts, fewer gut woes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. A parietal (highly selective) vagotomy is often chosen over truncal vagotomy and antrectomy because it carries a significantly lower complication rate, making it a more appealing option for patients despite its higher ulcer recurrence rate.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nParietal vagotomy is a highly selective procedure where only the vagal branches supplying the acid-secreting parietal cells in the fundus and body of the stomach are divided. Crucially, the main vagal trunks (nerves of Latarjet) and the nerve supply to the pylorus, liver, gallbladder, pancreas, and intestines are preserved. This preservation avoids the need for a gastric drainage procedure and minimizes systemic side effects like dumping syndrome or diarrhea, which are common after truncal vagotomy and antrectomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The provided text explicitly states that the recurrence rate is higher with parietal vagotomy compared to truncal vagotomy and antrectomy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Parietal vagotomy is primarily indicated for duodenal ulcers, not specifically antral ulcers, and its benefit is not exclusive to antral ulcers.\nOption C (Incorrect): Truncal vagotomy with antrectomy involves more extensive denervation and removal of acid-producing mucosa, leading to a greater reduction in acid secretion than parietal vagotomy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Vagotomy is a nerve-cutting procedure to reduce acid secretion, not a procedure that physically removes the ulcer itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Parietal (Highly Selective) Vagotomy | Truncal Vagotomy + Antrectomy |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Complication Rate** | Lower | Higher |\n| **Ulcer Recurrence** | Higher | Lower |\n| **Acid Secretion Reduction** | Moderate | Greater |\n| **Drainage Procedure Needed** | No (pylorus intact) | Yes (antrectomy removes pylorus) |\n| **Systemic Side Effects** | Fewer (e.g., less dumping) | More (e.g., dumping, diarrhea) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lower complications, higher recurrence: the trade-off of highly selective vagotomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring a parietal vagotomy, the surgeon meticulously identifies the anterior and posterior nerves of Latarjet along the lesser curvature. The individual branches supplying the fundus and body of the stomach are carefully divided, while preserving the main trunks and the 'crow's foot' branches to the pylorus. The proximal (criminal) nerve of Grassi is also identified and divided to ensure completeness.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017). This guideline outlines the current medical and historical surgical approaches for refractory peptic ulcer disease, acknowledging the role of vagotomy procedures in specific contexts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It results in a lower incidence of ulcer recurrence. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It benefits patients with antral ulcers the most. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It reduces acid secretion to a greater extent. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The complication rate is lower. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | It includes removal of the ulcer. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) In highly selective vagotomy (Fig. 5–6), the nerve supply to the pylorus is left intact (and therefo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
