  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Patch it up, wash it out, save a life!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B because an anterior duodenal ulcer perforation with bilious fluid requires immediate surgical closure to prevent ongoing peritonitis and sepsis. An omental patch (Graham patch) is the standard, least morbid, and most effective initial surgical intervention for this acute condition, especially in a frail patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Graham patch involves suturing a pedicled piece of omentum over the perforated ulcer, effectively sealing the defect. This simple technique provides immediate control of contamination, allows for thorough peritoneal lavage, and is well-tolerated in critically ill or frail patients. While it doesn't address the underlying cause of the ulcer, it is life-saving in the acute setting by preventing further leakage of gastrointestinal contents.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lavage alone is insufficient as it does not close the perforation, leading to continued leakage of GI contents and ongoing peritonitis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Total gastrectomy is an extremely aggressive and morbid procedure, never indicated for a simple perforated duodenal ulcer. It is reserved for extensive gastric malignancy or intractable bleeding.\nOption D (Incorrect): While vagotomy and gastroenterostomy are definitive acid-reducing procedures, they are complex and not the primary acute intervention for a perforated ulcer, especially in a frail patient. The priority is immediate closure of the perforation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Laser is used endoscopically for hemostasis of bleeding ulcers, not for the repair of a full-thickness perforation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Recommended Procedure | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Acute perforated duodenal ulcer (stable patient) | Omental (Graham) patch | Simple, effective closure of perforation, low morbidity. |\n| Acute perforated duodenal ulcer (unstable/septic) | Omental (Graham) patch + resuscitation | Immediate source control, life-saving. |\n| Recurrent/complicated duodenal ulcer (elective) | Highly selective vagotomy, truncal vagotomy + antrectomy/pyloroplasty | Definitive acid reduction, addresses underlying cause. |\n| Bleeding peptic ulcer | Endoscopic therapy (clips, injection) or surgical oversewing | Achieve hemostasis. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For acute perforated duodenal ulcers, a Graham patch is the go-to, life-saving procedure.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT or upright CXR), free air under the diaphragm (pneumoperitoneum) is the hallmark sign of a perforated viscus. Intraoperatively, one would see bilious fluid and food particles in the peritoneal cavity, and a small, often anterior, defect in the duodenum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Perforated Peptic Ulcer (2020) recommends laparoscopic or open omental patch repair as the primary surgical treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lavage of the peritoneal cavity alone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lavage and omental patch closure of the ulcer | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lavage, vagotomy, and gastroenterostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Laser of the ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Although surgery is generally recom-mended for perforation, conservative measures can be considered ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
