  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When medical therapy fails, cut it out before it gets worse.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. This answer is correct because a benign gastric ulcer that fails to heal after 3 months of appropriate medical therapy, especially with persistent symptoms like anemia and guaiac-positive stool, warrants surgical intervention due to the risk of missed malignancy and continued morbidity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe primary concern with a non-healing gastric ulcer, even with negative biopsies, is the possibility of an underlying malignancy that was not captured by the initial biopsies. Gastric ulcers on the greater curvature are also statistically more likely to be malignant. Surgical intervention, specifically a partial gastrectomy with excision of the ulcer, provides definitive treatment by removing the symptomatic lesion and allowing for complete histopathological examination to rule out malignancy. Unlike duodenal ulcers, gastric ulcers are not typically associated with acid hypersecretion, so vagotomy is generally not indicated.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Continuing medical therapy and observation after 3 months of failure with persistent symptoms is inappropriate and delays definitive management, risking progression or missed malignancy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Endoscopic therapy like electrocautery or laser photocoagulation is primarily indicated for acute bleeding control, not for chronic, non-healing ulcers with persistent symptoms and anemia.\nOption C (Incorrect): While TPN and admission might be considered for severe malnutrition or complications, they do not address the underlying non-healing ulcer or the risk of malignancy; surgical intervention is the definitive next step.\nOption E (Incorrect): Total gastrectomy is an overly aggressive procedure for a benign, non-healing ulcer. Partial gastrectomy is sufficient to remove the lesion and achieve cure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication for Gastric Ulcer Surgery | Rationale | Surgical Procedure |\n|:------------------------------------|:----------|:-------------------|\n| Failure of medical therapy (3 months) | Persistent symptoms, risk of missed malignancy | Partial gastrectomy (Billroth I or II) |\n| Suspicion of malignancy (even with negative biopsies) | Definitive diagnosis and treatment | Partial gastrectomy or total gastrectomy (depending on extent) |\n| Complications (perforation, intractable bleeding, obstruction) | Life-threatening events, acute management | Ulcer excision/repair, partial gastrectomy |\n| Ulcers > 2 cm on greater curvature | Higher risk of malignancy | Partial gastrectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-healing gastric ulcer after 3 months of medical therapy = surgical excision.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a non-healing ulcer might appear indurated, with rolled margins, or have an irregular base, even if biopsies were negative. Intraoperatively, the ulcer would be palpably firm or indurated, and the partial gastrectomy would involve resecting the ulcer-bearing segment of the stomach.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Guidelines for the Management of Gastric Ulcers (e.g., 2019). They recommend repeat endoscopy with biopsies for non-healing ulcers and consider surgery for refractory cases or high suspicion of malignancy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Treatment of the anemia and repeat all studies in 6 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Endoscopy and bipolar electrocautery or laser photocoagulation of the gastr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Admission of the patient for total parenteral nutrition (TPN), treatment of | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Surgical intervention, including partial gastric resection | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Surgical intervention, including total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) In general, vagotomy with a gastric drainage procedure is less satisfactory in the treatment of prim** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
