  "answer": "D) A gastric ulcer that does not respond to medical therapy requires surgical intervention. An appropriate operation for an antral ulcer is an antrectomy with a gastroduodenal anasto-mosis (Billroth I). Vagotomy is not nearly as effective in preventing recurrences in gastric ulcers. It is important to realize that the man-agement of gastric and duodenal ulcers is not identical because the etiologies are different. Duodenal ulcers are associated with acid hypersecretion while gastric ulcers are associ-ated with impaired mucosal defense mecha-nisms. Both are associated with H. pylori (duodenal ulcers 90% and gastric ulcers 75%). Agastric ulcer is much more likely to harbor a malignancy as compared to a duodenal ulcer. A gastric ulcer should always be biopsied. If a gastric ulcer fails to heal after appropriate med-ical management, it should be excised.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a gastric ulcer won't heal, cut it out, don't just seal it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. A non-healing gastric ulcer, despite appropriate medical therapy for H. pylori and PPIs, mandates surgical excision due to the significant risk of underlying malignancy. Distal gastrectomy with Billroth I anastomosis effectively removes the ulcer and the antrum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastric ulcers, particularly those in the antrum, carry a higher risk of malignancy compared to duodenal ulcers. When medical management fails, surgical resection is crucial not only for definitive treatment of the ulcer but also to exclude or treat gastric cancer. A distal gastrectomy (antrectomy) removes the ulcer-bearing portion of the stomach and is typically reconstructed with a gastroduodenal anastomosis (Billroth I) for physiological continuity. This approach addresses both the ulcer and the potential for malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): H2 blockers are less potent than PPIs, which have already failed in this patient. Switching to a weaker acid suppressant would be ineffective.\nOption B (Incorrect): Vagotomy primarily reduces acid secretion and is more relevant for duodenal ulcers. It does not address the non-healing nature or the malignancy risk of a gastric ulcer.\nOption C (Incorrect): Endoscopic laser treatment is not a definitive therapy for a non-healing gastric ulcer, especially given the high suspicion for malignancy. Excision is required.\nOption E (Incorrect): Elevating the head of the bed is a lifestyle modification for gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) and has no role in the treatment of a non-healing gastric ulcer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gastric Ulcer | Duodenal Ulcer |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Impaired mucosal defense, H. pylori (75%), NSAIDs | Acid hypersecretion, H. pylori (90%), NSAIDs |\n| **Malignancy Risk** | High (requires biopsy/excision if non-healing) | Very Low |\n| **Pain Pattern** | Often worse with food | Often relieved by food, worse 2-3 hours after |\n| **Surgical Tx (non-healing)** | Distal gastrectomy (antrectomy) | Vagotomy + drainage (less common now), oversew perforation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A non-healing gastric ulcer is a cancer until proven otherwise; excise it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would show a persistent ulcer despite therapy, requiring repeat biopsies. Intraoperatively, a distal gastrectomy involves resecting the antrum and potentially part of the body, followed by a Billroth I anastomosis connecting the remaining stomach to the duodenum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017). It recommends that gastric ulcers failing to heal after 8-12 weeks of PPI therapy should be re-evaluated with repeat endoscopy and biopsy to exclude malignancy. Surgical intervention is indicated for refractory or complicated ulcers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Treatment with H blockers | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Vagotomy alone without additional surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Endoscopy and laser treatment of the ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Distal gastrectomy with gastroduodenal anastomosis (Billroth I) | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Elevating the head of the bed when asleep | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) A gastric ulcer that does not respond to medical therapy requires surgical intervention. An appropri** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
