  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cut it out, clear the nodes, save the rest!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, distal gastrectomy with en bloc lymph node dissection, because this patient has localized, resectable antral gastric cancer without evidence of metastatic disease, making curative surgical resection the primary treatment. The tumor's location in the antrum allows for a subtotal resection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCurative intent surgery for gastric adenocarcinoma involves en bloc resection of the tumor with adequate margins (typically 5-6 cm proximal) and a D2 lymphadenectomy. For antral lesions, a distal subtotal gastrectomy is sufficient to achieve these goals, preserving more gastric function than a total gastrectomy while providing equivalent oncologic outcomes. This approach maximizes the chance of cure while minimizing surgical morbidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Chemotherapy only is not curative for localized gastric adenocarcinoma; surgical resection is essential for cure.\nOption B (Incorrect): Radiation therapy only is not curative for localized gastric adenocarcinoma.\nOption C (Incorrect): Combination chemotherapy and radiation therapy without resection is palliative or neoadjuvant, but not curative for resectable disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): Total gastrectomy is overly aggressive for an antral lesion without diffuse involvement and does not improve 5-year survival compared to distal gastrectomy for this specific location.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Type | Indication | Key Principle |\n|---|---|---|\n| Distal Gastrectomy (D2 LAD) | Localized antral/distal gastric cancer | Curative resection with adequate margins and regional lymphadenectomy |\n| Total Gastrectomy (D2 LAD) | Proximal gastric cancer, diffuse type, extensive disease | Curative resection for higher lesions or diffuse involvement |\n| Chemoradiation (Neoadjuvant/Adjuvant) | Locally advanced disease, high-risk resected disease | Downstaging, improved local control, improved survival |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For localized antral gastric cancer, distal gastrectomy with D2 lymphadenectomy is the curative standard.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would show an ulcerated mass in the antrum. Intraoperatively, after mobilization, the tumor would be palpable, and the extent of lymphadenopathy in the D1/D2 basins would be assessed for en bloc resection. CT would confirm no distant mets and assess local extent.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., Version 2.2023) recommend surgical resection with D1/D2 lymphadenectomy as the primary treatment for resectable gastric adenocarcinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chemotherapy only | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Radiation therapy only | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Combination chemotherapy and radiation therapy without resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Distal gastrectomy with en bloc removal of lymph nodes | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The treatment of an antral gastric cancer is distal subtotal gastrectomy with lymph node dissection ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
