  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the mucosa is clean, but the mass is mean, think GIST!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST). This diagnosis is strongly supported by the presentation of a large, palpable upper abdominal mass with intact gastric mucosa and normal biopsies, despite a UGI study showing a mass. The need for left transverse colon resection indicates significant local invasion, a characteristic feature of GISTs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGISTs originate from the interstitial cells of Cajal, located in the muscularis propria layer of the GI tract, explaining why the overlying gastric mucosa remains intact and biopsies of the mucosa are normal. These tumors can grow to a very large size (3 kg in this case) before becoming symptomatic. Their growth pattern often involves local invasion into adjacent organs, such as the transverse colon, necessitating en bloc resection. Historically, GISTs were misclassified as leiomyosarcomas due to their mesenchymal origin, but are now recognized by their specific immunohistochemical markers (e.g., CD117/KIT).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gastric cancer) (Incorrect): Gastric adenocarcinoma typically arises from the gastric mucosa, and biopsies would almost certainly show malignant cells if a mass is present. The intact mucosa and normal biopsies rule this out.\nOption C (Choledochoduodenal fistula) (Incorrect): This is an abnormal connection between the bile duct and duodenum, not a primary gastric mass. Symptoms would involve biliary issues, not a large palpable gastric tumor.\nOption D (Eosinophilic gastroenteritis) (Incorrect): This is an inflammatory condition characterized by eosinophilic infiltration of the GI tract. While it can cause thickening, it rarely presents as a large, discrete, palpable mass requiring extensive surgical resection like a 3kg tumor with colon involvement.\nOption E (Linitis plastica) (Incorrect): Linitis plastica is a diffuse infiltrative gastric carcinoma that causes a rigid, \"leather bottle\" stomach. While biopsies can be challenging, the endoscopy would typically show abnormal, rigid, non-distensible mucosa, not an intact mucosa with a discrete mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | GIST | Gastric Adenocarcinoma | Linitis Plastica | Eosinophilic Gastroenteritis |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Submucosal (muscularis propria) | Mucosal | Mucosal (diffuse infiltration) | Mucosal/Submucosal (inflammatory) |\n| **Endoscopy** | Intact mucosa, bulging mass | Ulceration, mass, friable mucosa | Rigid, non-distensible stomach, subtle mucosal changes | Edema, erythema, nodularity, sometimes strictures |\n| **Biopsy** | Normal gastric mucosa (if superficial) | Malignant cells | Often negative initially, requires deep biopsies | Eosinophilic infiltrate |\n| **Growth** | Expansile, local invasion | Mass, ulceration, metastasis | Diffuse, circumferential thickening | Infiltrative, inflammatory |\n| **Size** | Can be very large | Variable | Diffuse thickening | Variable, not typically a discrete large mass |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Large submucosal gastric mass with intact mucosa = GIST until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn UGI study, a GIST typically appears as a smooth, well-defined filling defect or extrinsic compression, often with an intact mucosal stripe. CT scan would show a large, heterogeneously enhancing mass originating from the stomach wall, potentially with areas of necrosis or hemorrhage, and clear evidence of local invasion into adjacent structures like the transverse colon. Intraoperatively, a GIST appears as a firm, often encapsulated or pseudoencapsulated mass arising from the gastric wall, distinct from the mucosa, with potential direct invasion into surrounding organs.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (including GIST) Version 1.2024. These guidelines recommend complete surgical resection as the primary treatment for localized GIST, with consideration for neoadjuvant/adjuvant imatinib based on risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastric cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Choledochoduodenal fistula | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Eosinophilic gastroenteritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Linitis plastica | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) GISTs were previously called leiomyosar-comas. They are rare (4% of all gastrointestinal tumors). Th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
