  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut what you can cure with chemo and rays!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Radiation and chemotherapy. This is because non-Hodgkin's lymphoma (NHL) of the stomach, particularly extranodal forms, is primarily treated with a combination of chemotherapy and radiation therapy, which has shown equivalent survival rates to surgery while avoiding its morbidity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastric lymphoma, the second most common gastric malignancy, has seen a significant evolution in its management. Historically, surgery was the mainstay, but contemporary evidence demonstrates that nonoperative approaches combining systemic chemotherapy with localized radiation therapy achieve comparable 5-year survival outcomes. This paradigm shift prioritizes organ preservation and reduced surgical morbidity, reserving surgery mainly for complications like perforation or intractable bleeding. Furthermore, specific subtypes like low-grade MALT lymphoma, often associated with H. pylori, can even be cured with antibiotic and PPI therapy in a significant percentage of cases.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Chemotherapy alone is often insufficient for localized gastric NHL, as radiation therapy significantly improves local control and survival when combined with chemotherapy.\nOption B (Incorrect): While immunotherapy is a crucial component of modern lymphoma treatment, it is typically used in combination with chemotherapy (e.g., R-CHOP) and not as a standalone primary therapy for localized gastric NHL.\nOption D (Incorrect): Surgery is no longer considered first-line therapy for primary gastric NHL due to similar survival rates with nonoperative management and its associated morbidity. It is reserved for complications.\nOption E (Incorrect): Surgery alone is an outdated and inadequate treatment for gastric NHL, as it does not address systemic disease potential and has been superseded by combined modality therapy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gastric Non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma (NHL) | Gastric MALT Lymphoma (low-grade) | Gastric Adenocarcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Treatment** | Chemotherapy + Radiation | H. pylori eradication (PPI + antibiotics) | Surgical resection (gastrectomy) |\n| **Role of Surgery** | For complications (perforation, bleeding) | Rarely, if H. pylori fails or high-grade transformation | Curative intent, staging |\n| **Prognosis** | Generally good with modern therapy | Excellent with H. pylori eradication | Varies greatly by stage, often poor |\n| **Etiology** | Diverse, often diffuse large B-cell | H. pylori infection | H. pylori, chronic gastritis, diet |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastric NHL: Chemo + Rads is the new standard, surgery for complications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal a mass, often with ulceration or diffuse infiltration, which can be biopsied. On CT, gastric lymphoma may appear as diffuse or focal wall thickening, sometimes with regional lymphadenopathy, but distinguishing it from adenocarcinoma radiographically can be challenging without biopsy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for B-Cell Lymphomas (e.g., 2023) recommend combined modality therapy (chemotherapy with or without radiation) for localized gastric diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chemotherapy alone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Immunotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radiation and chemotherapy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Surgery, radiation, and chemotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Surgery alone | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The stomach is the most common site of involvement in extranodal non-Hodgkin’s lym-phoma (NHL). Lymp** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
