  "answer": "A) Dysphagia in esophageal achalasia is described as paradoxical in that it is more pronounced for liquids than solids. There are numerous reports of an increased incidence of carcinoma in achalasia, ranging from 3% to 10%. In 1975, Belsey reported a 10% incidence in 81 patients in whom symptoms tended to occur at a younger age. Recurrent lung infec-tions from aspiration of esophageal contents are a troublesome complication. The treatment is surgical myotomy or endoscopic dilatation.",
