  "answer": "D) Oral fluids and solid foods can usually be started several days after the injury. Feeding at this stage is encouraged if the patient continues to show favorable improvement. If the caustic injury is superficial, stricture formation is unlikely to occur. Endoscopy to the proximal extend of the injury is recommended unless perforation is suspected. No attempt should be made to pass the endoscope beyond the proximal protion of the inflammatory segment. Emetics should not be administered because the esophagus will be reexposed to the agent when the patient vomits.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
