  "answer": "E) Patients with familial adenomatous poly-posis are at risk for developing carcinoma in adenomatous polyps arising in the stomach and duodenum. Ampullary and bile duct can-cers will result in jaundice.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 FAP: Don't forget the duodenum, it's a ticking time bomb!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Ampullary carcinoma. This patient's history of familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) places him at high risk for duodenal and ampullary cancers, which can manifest with obstructive jaundice and gastrointestinal bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFamilial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by a germline mutation in the APC gene, leading to hundreds to thousands of colorectal adenomas. Beyond the colon, FAP patients have a significantly increased risk of developing adenomas and subsequent carcinomas in the upper gastrointestinal tract, particularly in the duodenum and periampullary region. An ampullary carcinoma can obstruct the common bile duct and pancreatic duct, causing obstructive jaundice (elevated bilirubin, dark urine, pale stools) and can ulcerate, leading to guaiac positive stool. The 24-year disease-free interval post-colectomy highlights the need for continued surveillance of extracolonic manifestations.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Adenomatous gastric polyps. While FAP patients are at risk for gastric polyps, these are less commonly malignant and typically do not cause obstructive jaundice unless they are very large and located near the pylorus or ampulla, which is less direct than an ampullary tumor.\nOption B (Incorrect): Leiomyosarcoma. This is a rare malignant tumor of smooth muscle origin, not typically associated with FAP, and less likely to present as an ampullary mass causing obstructive jaundice.\nOption C (Incorrect): Lymphosarcoma. Lymphosarcoma (lymphoma) can occur in the GI tract but is not a primary extracolonic manifestation of FAP and is a less common cause of isolated obstructive jaundice from the ampulla.\nOption D (Incorrect): Linitis plastica. This is a diffuse infiltrative gastric adenocarcinoma, which can cause gastric outlet obstruction but does not typically cause obstructive jaundice from the ampulla and is not a specific FAP-associated extracolonic cancer in this context.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| FAP-Associated GI Cancers | Location | Key Symptoms | Surveillance Strategy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Colorectal Carcinoma | Colon/Rectum | Rectal bleeding, change in bowel habits | Prophylactic colectomy, regular endoscopy of remaining rectum/pouch |\n| Duodenal/Ampullary Carcinoma | Duodenum, Ampulla of Vater | Obstructive jaundice, GI bleeding, abdominal pain | Upper endoscopy with side-viewing duodenoscope (Spigelman staging) |\n| Gastric Carcinoma | Stomach | Dyspepsia, bleeding, weight loss | Upper endoscopy (less frequent than duodenal) |\n| Desmoid Tumors | Abdomen, mesentery, extremities | Palpable mass, pain, bowel obstruction | Clinical exam, imaging (CT/MRI) |\n| Pancreatic Carcinoma | Pancreas | Abdominal pain, weight loss, jaundice | Less common, no routine screening |\n| Thyroid Carcinoma (Papillary) | Thyroid | Thyroid nodule | Annual physical exam, ultrasound if indicated |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: FAP means lifelong surveillance for extracolonic cancers, especially duodenal/ampullary.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT/MRCP, an ampullary mass causing biliary and/or pancreatic duct dilation would be visible. Endoscopy with side-viewing duodenoscope would show a mass at the ampulla of Vater, allowing for biopsy. Intraoperatively, a firm mass at the ampulla would be palpable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colorectal Cancer Screening (2023): Recommend upper endoscopy with side-viewing duodenoscope for FAP patients starting at age 20-25, with surveillance intervals based on Spigelman stage, to detect duodenal and ampullary adenomas/carcinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adenomatous gastric polyps | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Leiomyosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lymphosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Linitis plastica | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Ampullary carcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Patients with familial adenomatous poly-posis are at risk for developing carcinoma in adenomatous po** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
