  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When blood hits the NGT, scope it fast, don't delay!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Upper endoscopy. This patient presents with signs of acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding (fresh blood and coffee grounds in the NGT) in the setting of critical illness (postoperative day 5, suspected anastomotic leak), making acute stress gastritis a strong possibility. Upper endoscopy is the gold standard for diagnosing and often treating upper GI bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUpper endoscopy allows for direct visualization of the gastric and duodenal mucosa, which is crucial for identifying the characteristic lesions of acute stress gastritis, ranging from petechiae and erosions to frank ulcers. It provides immediate diagnostic confirmation and can differentiate stress gastritis from other causes of upper GI bleeding like peptic ulcer disease or varices. Furthermore, endoscopy offers the capability for therapeutic intervention, such as epinephrine injection, cautery, or clipping, to achieve hemostasis if active bleeding is identified. Its safety profile, even in critically ill patients, makes it the preferred initial diagnostic and therapeutic modality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CAT scan) (Incorrect): A CT scan is primarily used to evaluate for structural abnormalities, free air, or fluid collections, and is not sensitive enough to detect superficial mucosal erosions or petechiae characteristic of stress gastritis.\nOption B (UGI series) (Incorrect): An upper gastrointestinal (UGI) series uses barium contrast and X-rays, which are poor at visualizing mucosal detail and cannot detect shallow erosions or petechiae. It also offers no therapeutic capabilities.\nOption C (Angiogram) (Incorrect): Angiography is typically reserved for brisk, active arterial bleeding when endoscopy has failed or is not feasible, and the bleeding rate is high enough (usually >0.5 mL/min) to be detected. Stress gastritis often presents with diffuse oozing or shallow lesions not amenable to angiographic detection or embolization.\nOption D (Capsule endoscopy) (Incorrect): Capsule endoscopy is primarily used for the diagnosis of obscure or occult gastrointestinal bleeding, particularly in the small bowel, when other methods have been unrevealing. It is not suitable for acute, active upper GI bleeding as it cannot be controlled, retrieved, or provide therapeutic intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Modality | Primary Use | Utility for Stress Gastritis | Limitations |\n|--------------------|-------------|------------------------------|--------------|\n| Upper Endoscopy    | Acute UGI Bleeding | Gold standard: direct visualization, biopsy, therapy | Invasive, requires sedation |\n| CT Angiography     | Brisk arterial bleeding | Low utility: poor for mucosal lesions, requires active bleeding | Radiation, contrast, no therapy |\n| UGI Series         | Structural abnormalities | Poor utility: limited mucosal detail, no therapy | Radiation, contrast, poor sensitivity |\n| Capsule Endoscopy  | Occult/obscure GI bleeding | No utility: not for acute bleeding, no therapy | Cannot be controlled, no therapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For acute upper GI bleeding, always think endoscopy first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopic findings for acute stress gastritis include diffuse erythema, petechiae, multiple shallow erosions, or discrete ulcers, typically located in the fundus and body of the stomach, and sometimes extending into the duodenum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Patients With Acute Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding (2021). Recommends early upper endoscopy (within 24 hours) for most patients with acute nonvariceal upper GI bleeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CAT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | UGI series | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Angiogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Capsule endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Upper endoscopy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Endoscopic findings range from petechiae to multiple ulcers in the body of the stomach and duodenum.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
