  "id": 130373,
  "question": "A73-year-old woman is admitted to the hospi-tal with a mild UGI hemorrhage that stopped spontaneously. She did not require transfusion. She had ingested large amounts of aspirin in the past 4 months to relieve the pain caused by severe rheumatoid arthritis. Endoscopy con-firms the presence of a duodenal ulcer. A biopsy is done. What is the next step in the management of a duodenal ulcer associated with a positive biopsy for H. pylori?",
  "options": {
    "A": "H blockers",
    "B": "Bipolar electrocautery of the ulcer",
    "C": "Triple therapy",
    "D": "Photocoagulation",
    "E": "Elective surgery"
  },
  "answer": "C) Since the patient is stable, she does not require any therapeutic endoscopic or surgical procedures. Triple therapy (a PPI and two antibiotics) should be initiated to eradicate the H. pylori organism. She should also be edu-cated about the association of aspirin and NSAIDs with peptic ulcer disease.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Eradicate H. pylori, don't just suppress the acid!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Triple therapy. This is the standard of care for a duodenal ulcer confirmed to be associated with H. pylori infection, especially in a stable patient without active bleeding, as it directly addresses and eradicates the underlying infectious cause.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nH. pylori is a major etiological factor in peptic ulcer disease, and its eradication is crucial for ulcer healing and preventing recurrence. Triple therapy, typically comprising a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) and two antibiotics (e.g., clarithromycin and amoxicillin or metronidazole), effectively targets the bacteria. This approach not only heals the current ulcer but also significantly reduces the risk of future ulcers and complications, which is particularly important given the patient's history of aspirin use.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): H blockers (H2-receptor antagonists) reduce acid secretion but do not eradicate H. pylori, leading to high ulcer recurrence rates.\nOption B (Incorrect): Bipolar electrocautery is an endoscopic hemostatic technique used for actively bleeding ulcers, which is not indicated in this stable patient with a spontaneously stopped hemorrhage.\nOption D (Incorrect): Photocoagulation is another endoscopic hemostatic technique for active bleeding, not appropriate for a stable, non-bleeding ulcer.\nOption E (Incorrect): Elective surgery (e.g., vagotomy, antrectomy) is reserved for complicated or refractory ulcers (e.g., perforation, obstruction, intractable bleeding) and is overly aggressive for an initial presentation of a stable, H. pylori-positive ulcer amenable to medical therapy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Initial Management | Key Principle |\n|---|---|---|\n| H. pylori Duodenal Ulcer (stable) | Triple Therapy (PPI + 2 antibiotics) | Eradicate H. pylori, heal ulcer |\n| NSAID-induced Ulcer (stable) | Discontinue NSAID, PPI | Remove offending agent, reduce acid |\n| Actively Bleeding Ulcer | Endoscopic hemostasis (e.g., cautery, clips) | Stop hemorrhage, stabilize patient |\n| Refractory/Complicated Ulcer | Consider surgery (e.g., perforation, obstruction) | Address complications, prevent recurrence |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: H. pylori + ulcer = triple therapy first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal a discrete mucosal defect (ulcer) in the duodenal bulb or post-bulbar region, often with a clean base or non-bleeding stigmata. Biopsy would confirm H. pylori presence via urease test or histology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Helicobacter pylori Infection (2017) recommends eradication therapy for H. pylori-associated peptic ulcer disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | H blockers | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bipolar electrocautery of the ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Triple therapy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Photocoagulation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Elective surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Since the patient is stable, she does not require any therapeutic endoscopic or surgical procedures.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
