  "answer": "E) Patients with impaired gastric emptying, such as those who have had previous gastric surgery or those with diabetes, can develop bezoars. Bezoars can be classified as two types— phytobezoars (undigested vegetable matter) and trichobezoars (hair). The diagnosis can be made by EGD or barium study. Nonoperative management is often successful. Patients are told to ingest meat tenderizer (which contains papain) and repeat endoscopy is performed for further fragmentation and removal of the bezoar. If the patient is obstructed and endoscopic therapy is unsuccessful, surgery is indicated. Patients who ingest their hair should be referred for psychiatric evaluation.",
