  "id": 130419,
  "question": "Ten years after diagnosis of total proctocolitis this patient undergoes colonscopy and biopsy reveals high-grade dysplasia in 2–10 speci-mens. What should the physician recommend?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Repeat colonoscopy in 1 year",
    "B": "Increase steroid dosage",
    "C": "Early repeat colonoscopy and biopsy area again",
    "D": "Total proctocolectomy",
    "E": "Resection of the involved segment"
  },
  "answer": "D) Risk of dysplasia and colorectal cancer is higher in ulcerative colitis than in the general poulation. The severity, duration, and anatomic extent of the inflammation are risk factors for the development of dysplasia and cancer. These cancers do not seem to follow the adenoma carcinoma sequence and can arise in flat mucosa making them difficult to detect even with regular colonoscopies. After 8–10 years of colitis survellance colonoscopy should be performed with multiple random biopsies. The finding of dysplasia is an indiction for immediate total protocolectomy. Centers have reported up to 42% of colons removed for dysplasia also had colon cancer.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 High-grade dysplasia in UC: Don't delay, resect the whole way!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Total proctocolectomy. High-grade dysplasia (HGD) in the setting of total proctocolitis is a strong indicator for prophylactic colectomy due to the significantly elevated risk of synchronous or metachronous colorectal cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUlcerative colitis (UC) is a chronic inflammatory condition that increases the risk of colorectal cancer (CRC). The risk is directly related to the duration, extent, and severity of the disease. High-grade dysplasia, especially when found in multiple biopsies or flat mucosa, is considered a pre-malignant lesion with a high likelihood of co-existing invasive carcinoma or progression to cancer. Unlike sporadic adenomas, UC-associated dysplasia often arises from flat mucosa and can be multifocal, making endoscopic surveillance alone insufficient and risky. Total proctocolectomy removes the entire at-risk colonic and rectal mucosa, thereby eliminating the risk of future CRC.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Repeat colonoscopy in 1 year is inappropriate for high-grade dysplasia, as it carries a high risk of progression to or presence of invasive cancer within that timeframe.\nOption B (Incorrect): Increase steroid dosage is a treatment for active inflammation, not for dysplasia or cancer prevention. Steroids do not impact the neoplastic process.\nOption C (Incorrect): Early repeat colonoscopy and biopsy area again delays definitive treatment. While sometimes considered for low-grade dysplasia or equivocal findings, high-grade dysplasia is a clear indication for surgical intervention.\nOption E (Incorrect): Resection of the involved segment is inadequate for total proctocolitis. The entire colon and rectum are at risk, and segmental resection would leave diseased mucosa behind, maintaining the cancer risk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Dysplasia Grade | Extent/Type | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Low-grade dysplasia (LGD) | Flat, endoscopically visible | Endoscopic resection if possible, then surveillance every 3-6 months. If persistent or multifocal, consider colectomy. |\n| Low-grade dysplasia (LGD) | Flat, invisible | Surveillance colonoscopy every 6-12 months. If persistent, consider colectomy. |\n| High-grade dysplasia (HGD) | Any | Total proctocolectomy (unless focal and completely resectable endoscopically, with careful follow-up). |\n| Indefinite for dysplasia | Any | Optimize medical therapy, repeat colonoscopy in 3-6 months. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: High-grade dysplasia in UC = total proctocolectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, high-grade dysplasia may appear as a flat, subtle mucosal change, a raised plaque, or a mass. Intraoperatively, the colon and rectum may show signs of chronic inflammation, strictures, or pseudopolyps, but the dysplasia itself is microscopic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) 2019 guidelines for the management of ulcerative colitis recommend total proctocolectomy for patients with confirmed high-grade dysplasia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Repeat colonoscopy in 1 year | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Increase steroid dosage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Early repeat colonoscopy and biopsy area again | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Total proctocolectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Resection of the involved segment | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Risk of dysplasia and colorectal cancer is higher in ulcerative colitis than in the general poulatio** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
