  "id": 130423,
  "question": "An elderly nursing home patient is brought to the hospital with recent onset of colicky abdom-inal pain, distension and obstipation on exami-nation, the abdomen is markedly distended and tympanitic. There is no marked tenderness. Plain abdominal x-ray shows a markedly distended loop located mainly in the right upper quadrant. The likely diagnosis is:",
  "options": {
    "A": "Small-bowel obstruction",
    "B": "Large-bowel obstruction",
    "C": "Gallstone ileus",
    "D": "Mesenteric vascular occlusion",
    "E": "Sigmoid volvulus"
  },
  "answer": "E) This patient has sigmoid volvulus. Plain abdominal x-ray shows a massively distended loop in the right upper quadrant, because the sigmoid colon, as it progressively distends, as a result of the twist of its mesentery, has no space, in the LLQ to occupy and flips over to the largest available area—namely the right upper quadrant. Given the clinical presentation and findings, the plain abdominal x-ray is diagnostic.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the sigmoid twists, it's a coffee bean in the RUQ!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Sigmoid volvulus. This patient's presentation of colicky abdominal pain, distension, obstipation, and a markedly distended, tympanitic abdomen with a classic X-ray finding points directly to sigmoid volvulus. The X-ray showing a massively distended loop in the right upper quadrant is pathognomonic for this condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSigmoid volvulus occurs when the sigmoid colon twists on its mesentery, leading to a closed-loop obstruction. As gas and fluid accumulate, the loop massively distends. Due to the limited space in the left lower quadrant, this distended sigmoid loop often migrates superiorly and to the right, occupying the right upper quadrant. This creates the characteristic 'coffee bean' or 'inverted U' sign on plain abdominal X-ray, which is highly diagnostic in the appropriate clinical context of an elderly, often debilitated patient with acute large bowel obstruction symptoms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Small-bowel obstruction) (Incorrect): SBO typically presents with dilated small bowel loops, air-fluid levels, and often a 'string of pearls' sign, not a single massively distended loop in the RUQ.\nOption B (Large-bowel obstruction) (Incorrect): While sigmoid volvulus is a type of LBO, this option is too general. The specific X-ray finding of a distended loop in the RUQ is highly suggestive of volvulus, differentiating it from other causes like tumors or strictures.\nOption C (Gallstone ileus) (Incorrect): Gallstone ileus is a form of SBO caused by a gallstone eroding into the bowel. X-ray findings include pneumobilia, dilated small bowel, and sometimes the gallstone itself, which are distinct from this presentation.\nOption D (Mesenteric vascular occlusion) (Incorrect): Mesenteric ischemia typically presents with severe abdominal pain out of proportion to physical exam findings, often without significant distension initially. X-rays may show 'thumbprinting' or pneumatosis in later stages, but not a single distended loop in the RUQ.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Clinical Features | Classic X-ray Findings |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sigmoid Volvulus | Elderly, nursing home, obstipation, distension, colicky pain | 'Coffee bean' sign, 'inverted U', massively distended loop in RUQ |\n| Cecal Volvulus | Younger patients, intermittent pain, less common | 'Kidney bean' shape, dilated cecum in LUQ or mid-abdomen |\n| Small Bowel Obstruction | Vomiting, abdominal pain, distension, obstipation | Dilated small bowel loops, air-fluid levels, 'string of pearls' sign |\n| Large Bowel Obstruction | Progressive distension, obstipation, less vomiting | Dilated colon proximal to obstruction, collapsed distal colon |\n| Gallstone Ileus | Elderly, SBO symptoms, history of cholecystitis | Pneumobilia, dilated small bowel, ectopic gallstone |\n| Mesenteric Ischemia | Severe pain out of proportion to exam, risk factors (AFib, atherosclerosis) | Often normal initially, later 'thumbprinting', pneumatosis intestinalis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A 'coffee bean' in the RUQ means sigmoid volvulus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, the classic 'coffee bean' or 'inverted U' sign represents the massively distended sigmoid colon, often extending into the right upper quadrant. CT scan would confirm the diagnosis by showing the 'whirl sign' (twisted mesentery and vessels) and the massively dilated sigmoid colon. Intraoperatively, a massively dilated, often dusky, sigmoid colon twisted around its mesentery would be evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for the management of large bowel obstruction (2018) recommend initial conservative management for uncomplicated sigmoid volvulus, followed by endoscopic detorsion, and elective sigmoidectomy to prevent recurrence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Small-bowel obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Large-bowel obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gallstone ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mesenteric vascular occlusion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sigmoid volvulus | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) This patient has sigmoid volvulus. Plain abdominal x-ray shows a massively distended loop in the rig** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
