  "id": 130434,
  "question": "At operation, 2.5 m of distal ileum is found to be gangrenous. There is, however, pulsation in the superior mesenteric artery and its main branches. Small-bowel gangrene in this patient is caused by which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Arterial thrombosis",
    "B": "Embolus",
    "C": "Nonocclusive ischemic disease",
    "D": "Von Willebrand’s disease",
    "E": "Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura"
  },
  "answer": "C) In a patient with small intestine infarction, the possibility of nonocclusive ischemic disease should be excluded by angiography. If there is no evidence of gangrene, then fluid resuscitation and intra-arterial superior mesenteric papaverine administration may be adequate, and surgical intervention may be avoided. Von Willebrand’s disease is characterized by a mild to moderate fall in factor VIII levels (pseudohemophilia) but with a much milder bleeding tendency than in true hemophilia. It affects males and females equally.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gut dies but the pulse thrives, think NOMI.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Nonocclusive ischemic disease. The presence of gangrenous bowel despite palpable pulsations in the superior mesenteric artery and its main branches strongly suggests a low-flow state or microvascular spasm rather than a large vessel occlusion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNonocclusive mesenteric ischemia (NOMI) typically occurs in critically ill patients with conditions causing systemic hypoperfusion, such as cardiogenic shock, sepsis, or severe dehydration. This leads to intense splanchnic vasoconstriction, reducing blood flow to the bowel wall at the microvascular level, even when the main mesenteric arteries are patent. This sustained vasoconstriction and hypoperfusion eventually result in transmural ischemia and gangrene, despite the absence of a macroscopic arterial or venous occlusion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Arterial thrombosis) (Incorrect): Arterial thrombosis would typically lead to absent or significantly diminished pulsations distal to the occlusion, which contradicts the clinical finding of palpable pulsations.\nOption B (Embolus) (Incorrect): Similar to thrombosis, an embolus in a major mesenteric artery would cause an occlusion, leading to absent pulsations and not fitting the described scenario.\nOption D (Von Willebrand’s disease) (Incorrect): Von Willebrand’s disease is a common inherited bleeding disorder, characterized by impaired platelet adhesion and coagulation, not a cause of bowel gangrene from ischemia.\nOption E (Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura) (Incorrect): Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) is an autoimmune disorder causing low platelet counts and increased bleeding risk, entirely unrelated to the pathophysiology of mesenteric ischemia and gangrene.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Arterial Occlusive Mesenteric Ischemia | Venous Occlusive Mesenteric Ischemia | Nonocclusive Mesenteric Ischemia (NOMI) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Cause** | Embolus, Thrombosis (atherosclerosis) | Hypercoagulable states, trauma, tumor | Systemic hypoperfusion, vasoconstriction |\n| **Vessel Patency** | Major artery occluded | Major vein occluded | Major arteries patent |\n| **Risk Factors** | AFib, MI, PVD, AAA | Malignancy, OCPs, portal HTN, sepsis | Shock, CHF, Sepsis, Vasopressors |\n| **Angiography** | Cut-off/filling defect | Venous thrombus | Diffuse vasoconstriction, \"string of beads\" |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gangrenous bowel with patent SMA suggests nonocclusive mesenteric ischemia until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn angiography, NOMI typically shows diffuse narrowing of the mesenteric arteries, often described as a \"string of beads\" appearance, with poor filling of peripheral branches. Intraoperatively, the bowel appears gangrenous, but palpation of the SMA and its main branches reveals strong pulsations, confirming their patency.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) Guidelines on the Management of Mesenteric Ischemia 2017. These guidelines recommend early diagnosis and treatment, including angiography for NOMI to confirm diagnosis and potentially administer vasodilators.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Arterial thrombosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Embolus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Nonocclusive ischemic disease | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Von Willebrand’s disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) In a patient with small intestine infarction, the possibility of nonocclusive ischemic disease shoul** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
