  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Plain film patterns: Know your bowel folds, save a life.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Ileal obstruction. This is because a plain film of the abdomen provides distinct clues for the location of bowel obstruction, with distal ileal obstruction typically presenting as a featureless bowel pattern.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe characteristic appearance of bowel loops on plain film is dictated by the mucosal folds present in different segments of the gastrointestinal tract. The jejunum, being more proximal small bowel, has prominent, closely spaced circular folds (valvulae conniventes) that extend across the entire lumen. The ileum, particularly the distal ileum, has fewer and less prominent valvulae conniventes, leading to a 'featureless' or 'smooth' appearance when distended. In contrast, the colon is characterized by haustra, which are sacculations that do not extend across the entire lumen and are more widely spaced, giving a different pattern on imaging.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Sigmoid volvulus) (Incorrect): This is a large bowel obstruction, which would typically show dilated colonic loops with haustral markings, often forming a 'coffee bean' sign.\nOption B (Cecal volvulus) (Incorrect): This is also a large bowel obstruction, presenting with a dilated cecum and colon, showing haustral markings, often displaced.\nOption C (Jejunal obstruction) (Incorrect): Proximal small bowel obstruction (jejunal) would typically show dilated loops with prominent valvulae conniventes, often described as a 'stack of coins' or 'keyboard' sign.\nOption E (Pyloric obstruction) (Incorrect): Pyloric obstruction is a gastric outlet obstruction, primarily affecting the stomach, which would show a dilated stomach and potentially minimal small bowel gas, not the small or large bowel patterns described.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Bowel Segment | Plain Film Finding in Obstruction |\n|---|---|\n| Jejunum | Valvulae conniventes ('stack of coins') |\n| Ileum (distal) | Featureless bowel loops |\n| Colon | Haustral markings |\n| Stomach (Pyloric) | Dilated stomach, minimal distal gas |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Valvulae = jejunum, Featureless = ileum, Haustra = colon on plain film.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a plain film, ileal obstruction would typically show multiple dilated loops of small bowel (greater than 3 cm in diameter) with air-fluid levels on erect views. The key distinguishing feature from jejunal obstruction would be the absence of prominent valvulae conniventes, giving the distended loops a smooth, 'featureless' appearance. Intraoperatively, one would find a transition point with dilated proximal ileum and collapsed distal ileum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Suspected Small Bowel Obstruction (2022). It recommends plain radiographs as an initial imaging study, but emphasizes CT abdomen/pelvis with IV contrast as the most appropriate imaging study for confirming diagnosis and determining etiology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sigmoid volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cecal volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Jejunal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ileal obstruction | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Pyloric obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Aplain film of the abdomen shows valvulae conniventes in jejunal (proximal) obstruction, a featurele** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
