  "answer": "A) Transit time in the ileum is slower than that in the jejunum. Resection of equal lengths of intestine results in greater deterioration after ileal resection as the site of slower (and therefore more complete) absorption is removed. Jejunal resection is followed by hypertrophy of the residual villi in the ileum and functional compensation to a degree greater than in the jejunum after ileal resection.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Slow and steady wins the race, but losing the slow part loses the game.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, highlighting that distal (ileal) resection is poorly tolerated because the ileum has a slower transit time compared to the jejunum. This slower transit is crucial for more complete nutrient absorption, making its loss more functionally significant.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe small intestine exhibits regional specialization. The jejunum is adapted for rapid, bulk absorption of most macronutrients due to its large surface area and faster transit. In contrast, the ileum's slower transit time is essential for the complete absorption of specific nutrients, such as vitamin B12 and bile salts, and for maximizing overall nutrient uptake. Resection of the ileum removes this critical segment of slower, more efficient absorption, leading to significant malabsorption, fluid and electrolyte imbalances, and often short bowel syndrome. While the jejunum can adapt to some extent, its compensatory capacity is less effective than the ileum's ability to adapt after jejunal resection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Transit time in the jejunum is faster than in the ileum, allowing for rapid bulk absorption but less complete nutrient extraction.\nOption C (Incorrect): The greater bulk of food (carbohydrates, proteins, and fats) is primarily absorbed in the jejunum, not the ileum.\nOption D (Incorrect): While some water is absorbed in the ileum, the majority of water absorption occurs in the colon. The poor tolerance of ileal resection is more critically linked to specific nutrient and bile salt malabsorption.\nOption E (Incorrect): Mineral absorption is distributed throughout the small intestine, with specific sites for different minerals (e.g., iron in the duodenum). Not all minerals are preferentially absorbed in the ileum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Jejunum | Ileum |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------ | :---------------------------------------- |\n| **Transit Time** | Faster | Slower |\n| **Primary Function**| Bulk nutrient absorption (carbs, fats, proteins) | Specific nutrient absorption (B12, bile salts), water, fine-tuning |\n| **Adaptation Post-Resection** | Ileum can adapt well, significant compensation | Jejunum adapts less effectively, greater functional deficit |\n| **Impact of Resection** | Better tolerated | Poorly tolerated |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ileal resection is worse than jejunal due to slower transit and specific absorption loss.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after significant ileal resection, one might observe dilated proximal small bowel loops due to increased intraluminal pressure and compensatory hypertrophy. Post-operatively, imaging might show signs of malabsorption like steatorrhea or vitamin deficiencies.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nESPEN guideline on clinical nutrition in intestinal failure: an update 2023. This guideline provides comprehensive recommendations for the management of patients with short bowel syndrome, often a consequence of extensive ileal resections.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Transit time in the ileum is slower than that in the jejunum. | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Transit time in the jejunum is slower than that in the ileum. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The greater bulk of food is absorbed in the ileum. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Water absorption is mainly in the ileum. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | All minerals are absorbed preferentially in the ileum. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Transit time in the ileum is slower than that in the jejunum. Resection of equal lengths of intestin** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
