  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When air meets bile and bowel stops, think gallstone ileus!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Gallstone ileus. This diagnosis perfectly explains the patient's symptoms of vomiting and intermittent colicky abdominal pain, indicative of bowel obstruction, combined with the pathognomonic finding of pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree) on X-ray.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus occurs when a large gallstone erodes through the gallbladder wall into an adjacent loop of bowel, typically the duodenum, forming a cholecystoenteric fistula. The stone then travels distally, causing intermittent mechanical small bowel obstruction, often at the ileocecal valve, leading to the 'tumbling' obstruction described. The presence of air in the biliary tree (pneumobilia) is a direct result of this fistula, allowing gas from the bowel to enter the biliary system, completing Rigler's triad.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Abdominal adhesions are a common cause of small bowel obstruction but do not cause air in the biliary tree.\nOption C (Incorrect): Carcinoma of the right colon can cause bowel obstruction, but it would not lead to pneumobilia.\nOption D (Incorrect): Abdominal lymphosarcoma is a rare cause of bowel obstruction and does not explain the presence of air in the biliary tree.\nOption E (Incorrect): A previous choledochoduodenostomy would explain air in the biliary tree by creating a communication between the bile duct and duodenum, but it would not typically cause small bowel obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Symptoms | Imaging Findings | Pathophysiology |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gallstone Ileus | Vomiting, colicky pain, SBO | Pneumobilia, dilated bowel, ectopic gallstone | Cholecystoenteric fistula, stone impaction |\n| Adhesional SBO | Vomiting, colicky pain, SBO | Dilated bowel, transition point, no pneumobilia | Fibrous bands from prior surgery/inflammation |\n| Colon Carcinoma | Change in bowel habits, weight loss, SBO | Apple-core lesion, dilated bowel, no pneumobilia | Tumor mass obstructing lumen |\n| Choledochoduodenostomy | Asymptomatic or related to underlying biliary disease | Pneumobilia (expected finding), no SBO | Surgical anastomosis between CBD and duodenum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rigler's triad (pneumobilia, SBO, ectopic gallstone) equals gallstone ileus until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain X-rays, look for dilated loops of small bowel, air-fluid levels, and pneumobilia. A CT scan is diagnostic, showing the cholecystoenteric fistula, the impacted gallstone, and dilated proximal bowel. Intraoperatively, a large gallstone will be found obstructing the small bowel, often in the ileum, with a fistula tract to the gallbladder.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 SAGES Guidelines for the Management of Small Bowel Obstruction. These guidelines recommend CT imaging for diagnosis and differentiation of SBO etiologies, including gallstone ileus, to guide appropriate management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abdominal adhesions | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gallstone ileus | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Carcinoma of the right colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Abdominal lymphosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Previous choledochoduodenostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Gallstone ileus results in “tumbling” intestinal obstruction due to the intermittent nature of the c** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
