  "question": "A 48-year-old man is admitted to hospital because of a 3-day history of mild abdominal pain, repeated vomiting, and marked distension. Immediately after the pain commenced, he had one small-bowel movement but no further passage of stool or flatus. An abdominal flat plate revealed marked distension of loops of bowel confined to the small bowel. A plain abdominal film shows loops of bowel that all extensively show valvulae conniventes. What is the most likely site of obstruction (Fig. 6–3)?",
