  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 See a CBD stone, fix a CBD stone, prevent a future moan!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. An intraoperative cholangiogram revealing a 0.8-cm filling defect in the distal common bile duct (CBD) is highly suggestive of a choledocholithiasis, which necessitates intervention to prevent complications such as cholangitis or pancreatitis. Therefore, CBD exploration is indicated.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraoperative cholangiography (IOC) is a critical diagnostic tool during cholecystectomy, allowing for direct visualization of the biliary tree and identification of choledocholithiasis. A filling defect, as described, is pathognomonic for a stone. Addressing a confirmed CBD stone at the time of cholecystectomy is crucial to prevent future complications and avoid a second procedure. The surgeon has the option to perform this exploration either laparoscopically, often via transcystic duct exploration or choledochotomy, or convert to an open procedure if laparoscopic removal is not feasible, ensuring definitive management of the stone.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Normal LFTs do not rule out choledocholithiasis, especially in asymptomatic or early stages. Leaving a confirmed CBD stone untreated is inappropriate and carries significant risk.\nOption B (Incorrect): While ultrasound can detect CBD dilation or stones, a normal postoperative ultrasound does not negate the intraoperative finding of a stone. Observation of a confirmed stone is not appropriate management.\nOption D (Incorrect): Completing the cholecystectomy without addressing a confirmed CBD stone is negligent. The stone poses a risk of obstruction, cholangitis, or pancreatitis.\nOption E (Incorrect): A HIDA scan evaluates cystic duct patency and gallbladder function, not the presence of CBD stones. It would not be helpful in this scenario where a CBD stone has already been identified.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Finding on IOC | Interpretation | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Filling defect in CBD | Choledocholithiasis | CBD exploration (laparoscopic or open) |\n| Free flow of contrast into duodenum | Normal CBD | Complete cholecystectomy |\n| No flow into duodenum, dilated CBD | CBD obstruction (stone, stricture) | CBD exploration, further investigation |\n| Contrast extravasation | Bile duct injury | Repair of injury |\n| Filling defect in cystic duct | Cystic duct stone | Complete cholecystectomy, remove stone if accessible |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A confirmed CBD stone on IOC demands immediate exploration, not observation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an intraoperative cholangiogram, a filling defect appears as a lucent (non-opacified) area within the contrast-filled common bile duct, often with a meniscus sign, indicating a stone obstructing contrast flow.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Bile Duct Stones (2017) recommends that patients with confirmed choledocholithiasis should undergo stone extraction, either preoperatively, intraoperatively, or postoperatively.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Complete the laparoscopic cholecystectomy and check liver function tests (L | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Complete the laparoscopic cholecystectomy and repeat an ultrasound postoper | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Perform a CBD exploration either laparoscopically or open along with a chol | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Complete the laparoscopic cholecystectomy, no further treatment is necessar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Complete the laparoscopic cholecystectomy and plan for a postoperative hydr | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The intraoperative cholangiogram is suggestive of a CBD stone. Normal LFTs do not rule out choledoch** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n"