  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the bile ducts breathe, a gallstone's on the loose!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer, A, accurately identifies gallstone ileus as the diagnosis given the classic presentation of small bowel obstruction in an elderly patient with pneumobilia. This combination of findings, known as Rigler's triad (small bowel obstruction, pneumobilia, and an ectopic gallstone), is pathognomonic for a cholecystoenteric fistula and subsequent gallstone impaction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus is a rare but critical complication of chronic cholecystitis, where a large gallstone erodes through the gallbladder wall into an adjacent loop of bowel, typically the duodenum, forming a cholecystoenteric fistula. The stone then migrates distally, eventually becoming impacted in the small bowel, most commonly the terminal ileum due to its narrower lumen and less active peristalsis. The presence of air in the biliary tree (pneumobilia) on imaging is a direct result of this fistula, allowing intestinal gas to enter the biliary system, confirming the diagnosis in conjunction with small bowel obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): An enterotomy should be performed *proximal* to the site of obstruction to facilitate stone removal and prevent further distal impaction or injury to the bowel. Removing it distal would be more difficult and potentially lead to more complications.\nOption C (Incorrect): Gallstone ileus is predominantly a disease of the elderly, typically affecting patients over 65 years of age, often with a history of gallstone disease, due to the chronic inflammatory process required for fistula formation.\nOption D (Incorrect): While cholecystectomy is often deferred during the initial emergency surgery for stone removal due to the patient's acute condition and inflammation, it is not absolutely contraindicated. A delayed, elective cholecystectomy and fistula repair may be considered in stable patients to prevent recurrence or other complications, though many patients do not require it.\nOption E (Incorrect): While SBO can occur anywhere, in gallstone ileus, the obstruction most commonly occurs in the terminal ileum (60-70% of cases) because it is the narrowest part of the small bowel and has less vigorous peristalsis compared to the jejunum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gallstone Ileus | Adhesional SBO | Malignant SBO |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Gallstone migration through cholecystoenteric fistula | Prior abdominal surgery | Primary or metastatic cancer |\n| **Patient Age** | Elderly (typically >65) | Any age, often history of surgery | Often older, history of cancer |\n| **Imaging Clues** | Pneumobilia, SBO, ectopic gallstone (Rigler's triad) | Transition point, no pneumobilia | Mass, lymphadenopathy, peritoneal carcinomatosis |\n| **Treatment** | Enterotomy & stone removal; +/- delayed cholecystectomy | Laparoscopic or open adhesiolysis | Resection, bypass, stenting, palliative care |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Elderly + SBO + pneumobilia = Gallstone Ileus until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal films or CT, Rigler's triad (pneumobilia, small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone) is diagnostic. Intraoperatively, one would find dilated small bowel proximal to an impacted gallstone, often in the terminal ileum, and a cholecystoenteric fistula, typically between the gallbladder and duodenum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Society of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons (SAGES) 2017 Guidelines for the Management of Small Bowel Obstruction. These guidelines recommend surgical intervention for complete SBO not resolving with conservative management, with specific considerations for the underlying etiology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Air in the biliary tree associated with small-bowel obstruction suggests a  | ✅ Correct |\n| B | An enterotomy should be distal to the site of obstruction and the stone sho | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gallstone ileus is more common in the young adults. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cholecystectomy is contraindicated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Small-bowel obstruction usually occurs in the distal jejunum. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Gallstone ileus usually results from formation of a cholecystoenteric fistula and is seen more often** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
