  "answer": "E) Staging of Hodgkin’s disease is often done nonoperatively. Staging laparotomy consists of wedge biopsy of the liver, splenectomy, examination and biopsy of peraortic lymph nodes, as well as biopsy of mesenteric and hepatoduodenal nodes. Stage I Hodgkin’s lymphoma is limited to one anatomic area, while Stage II involves 2 or more areas of the same side of the diaphram. Stage III disease involves both sides of the diaphram limited to lymph nodes, Waldyer’s ring or the spleen. Stage IV disease involves organs other than lymph nodes, Waldyer’s ring, or the spleen. Splenectomy may improve thrombocytopenia and allow chemotherapy to be administered.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spleen out for platelets, not just for show!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E. This question tests knowledge of Hodgkin's lymphoma staging and management principles. Splenectomy, while historically part of staging, now has specific therapeutic indications, such as managing severe thrombocytopenia to facilitate chemotherapy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenectomy for thrombocytopenia in Hodgkin's lymphoma is indicated when the spleen is contributing to platelet destruction, often due to hypersplenism or immune-mediated mechanisms, leading to a critically low platelet count. By removing the spleen, platelet counts can rise, allowing patients to safely receive myelosuppressive chemotherapy, which is crucial for disease control. This intervention shifts from a diagnostic staging procedure to a supportive therapeutic measure, enabling the primary treatment strategy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Splenectomy is no longer always required for accurate staging; modern imaging (PET/CT) has largely replaced staging laparotomy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Staging laparotomy historically involved splenectomy, not just a biopsy of the spleen, along with liver biopsies and lymph node sampling.\nOption C (Incorrect): Stage II disease involves two or more lymph node regions on the *same* side of the diaphragm, not both sides.\nOption D (Incorrect): If the spleen is involved, the patient has Stage III disease, not Stage IV. Stage IV involves diffuse extralymphatic organ involvement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ann Arbor Stage | Description |\n|---|---|\n| Stage I | Involvement of a single lymph node region or localized involvement of a single extralymphatic organ or site (IE). |\n| Stage II | Involvement of two or more lymph node regions on the same side of the diaphragm, or localized involvement of a single extralymphatic organ or site and its regional lymph nodes on the same side of the diaphragm (IIE). |\n| Stage III | Involvement of lymph node regions on both sides of the diaphragm, or localized involvement of a single extralymphatic organ or site and its regional lymph nodes on both sides of the diaphragm, or spleen involvement (IIIS). |\n| Stage IV | Diffuse or disseminated involvement of one or more extralymphatic organs, with or without associated lymph node involvement. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Splenectomy for Hodgkin's is therapeutic for cytopenias, not routine staging.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn PET/CT, Hodgkin's lymphoma typically presents as hypermetabolic lymphadenopathy, often in the cervical, supraclavicular, mediastinal, or retroperitoneal regions. Intraoperatively, involved lymph nodes may appear enlarged and firm, and the spleen, if involved, can be enlarged with nodular lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hodgkin Lymphoma (most recent version). These guidelines recommend PET/CT for staging and emphasize chemotherapy as the primary treatment, with splenectomy reserved for specific indications like refractory cytopenias.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Splenectomy is always required for accurate staging. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Staging laparotomy involves liver biopsy, biopsy of the spleen, and periaor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Stage II disease involves disease on both sides of the diaphragm. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | If the spleen is involved, the patient has stage IV disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Splenectomy is sometimes indicated for thrombocytopenia. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Staging of Hodgkin’s disease is often done nonoperatively. Staging laparotomy consists of wedge biop** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
