  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gut pours, and potassium drops, think VIPoma's watery flops!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Watery, diarrhea, hypokalemia, and achlorhydria (WDHA) syndrome, also known as VIPoma. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the patient's presentation of profuse watery diarrhea, weakness, weight loss, and severe hypokalemia, which are classic features of VIPoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVIPoma, caused by a vasoactive intestinal polypeptide (VIP)-secreting tumor, leads to massive secretory diarrhea, often exceeding 5 liters daily, rich in potassium, resembling \"watery tea.\" This persistent diarrhea results in profound hypokalemia and metabolic acidosis, explaining the patient's weakness and low serum potassium. The diarrhea is refractory to conventional antidiarrheal agents and continues even with fasting, distinguishing it from other causes of secretory diarrhea. Surgical excision of the pancreatic tumor is the definitive treatment, with octreotide used to manage symptoms preoperatively or in metastatic disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Somatostatinoma typically presents with a triad of diabetes mellitus, steatorrhea, and cholelithiasis due to somatostatin's inhibitory effects on various hormones and GI functions. Profuse watery diarrhea and hypokalemia are not its primary features.\nOption C (Incorrect): Glucagonoma is characterized by migratory necrolytic erythema, diabetes, and weight loss. While diarrhea can occur in about 15% of patients, it is not the predominant symptom, nor is severe hypokalemia a hallmark.\nOption D (Incorrect): Insulinoma causes symptoms of hypoglycemia (e.g., neuroglycopenic symptoms like confusion, weakness, and adrenergic symptoms like palpitations, sweating) due to excessive insulin secretion. It does not cause profuse watery diarrhea or hypokalemia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1 (MEN-1) is a genetic syndrome predisposing to tumors of the parathyroid, pituitary, and pancreas. While a VIPoma can occur as part of MEN-1, MEN-1 itself is a genetic predisposition syndrome, not the specific tumor syndrome causing the patient's symptoms. The question asks for the \"most likely diagnosis\" of the syndrome presented.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Key Symptoms | Hormone | Associated Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| VIPoma (WDHA) | Profuse watery diarrhea, hypokalemia, weakness, weight loss | VIP | Secretory diarrhea (5L+/day), metabolic acidosis, refractory to antidiarrheals |\n| Glucagonoma | Migratory necrolytic erythema, diabetes, weight loss | Glucagon | Diarrhea in 15%, glossitis, cheilosis |\n| Somatostatinoma | Diabetes mellitus, steatorrhea, cholelithiasis | Somatostatin | Inhibits multiple hormones, rare |\n| Insulinoma | Hypoglycemia (neuroglycopenic, adrenergic) | Insulin | Whipple's triad (hypoglycemia, symptoms, relief with glucose) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Profuse watery diarrhea + hypokalemia = VIPoma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (CT/MRI) would typically reveal a pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify and excise the pancreatic mass, often located in the body or tail.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe North American Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (NANETS) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pancreatic Neuroendocrine Tumors (2017) recommend surgical resection for localized VIPomas and medical management with somatostatin analogs (e.g., octreotide) for symptom control in metastatic disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Watery, diarrhea, hypokalemia, and achlorhydria (WDHA) syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Somatostatinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Glucagonoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Insulinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1(MEN-1) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) WDHAor vasoactive intestinal polypeptide (VIPoma) is characterized by voluminous diarrhea, 5 Lor mor** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
