  "question": "A 45-year-old man presents with an upper GI bleed. An upper endoscopy reveals multiple duodenal ulcers and an enlarged stomach. Select the most likely diagnosis.",
  "options": {
    "A": "WDHA syndrome",
    "B": "Glucagonoma",
    "C": "Zollinger-Ellison syndrome",
    "D": "Insulinoma",
    "E": "Somatostatinoma"
  },
  "answer": "C) Gastrinoma, or Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, should be suspected in patients with peptic ulcer disease refractory to medical treatment, or in patients with multiple ulcers or ulcers in uncommon locations. Gastrin secretion by the tumor, most commonly found in the pancreas, results in hypersecretion of gastric acid. Common patient complaints are epigastric pain, melena, hematemesis, diarrhea, and weight loss. ZES may occur as part of the MEN-1 syndrome; this patient presents with only atypical peptic ulcer disease. The treatment of choice involves the identification and resection of the gastrinoma. Preoperative treatment may include treatment of the ulcers with omeprazole.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When ulcers multiply and the stomach grows, think gastrinoma's hyperacidic woes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Zollinger-Ellison syndrome (ZES). This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the presence of multiple duodenal ulcers and an enlarged stomach in a patient presenting with an upper GI bleed, which are classic manifestations of gastrin hypersecretion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nZollinger-Ellison syndrome is caused by a gastrin-secreting tumor (gastrinoma), most commonly located in the pancreas or duodenum. The excessive gastrin leads to hypersecretion of gastric acid, which overwhelms the duodenal mucosal defenses, resulting in multiple, often refractory, peptic ulcers. The chronic stimulation of gastric parietal cells by gastrin also causes hypertrophy of the gastric mucosa, leading to an \"enlarged stomach\" appearance on endoscopy or imaging. This hyperacidity can also cause diarrhea and malabsorption. ZES can occur sporadically or as part of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 1 (MEN-1) syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (WDHA syndrome) (Incorrect): WDHA syndrome (Watery Diarrhea, Hypokalemia, Achlorhydria) is caused by a VIPoma, which secretes vasoactive intestinal peptide, leading to severe secretory diarrhea, not peptic ulcers or GI bleeding.\nOption B (Glucagonoma) (Incorrect): Glucagonomas secrete glucagon, causing symptoms like diabetes mellitus, necrolytic migratory erythema, weight loss, and stomatitis, not duodenal ulcers or GI bleeding.\nOption D (Insulinoma) (Incorrect): Insulinomas secrete insulin, leading to hypoglycemia with neuroglycopenic and adrenergic symptoms, not gastrointestinal ulceration or bleeding.\nOption E (Somatostatinoma) (Incorrect): Somatostatinomas secrete somatostatin, causing a classic triad of diabetes mellitus, steatorrhea (due to malabsorption), and cholelithiasis, not peptic ulcer disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Hormone | Key Symptoms |\n|---|---|---|\n| Zollinger-Ellison (Gastrinoma) | Gastrin | Multiple/refractory peptic ulcers, GI bleed, diarrhea, enlarged gastric folds |\n| WDHA (VIPoma) | VIP | Watery diarrhea, hypokalemia, achlorhydria |\n| Glucagonoma | Glucagon | Diabetes, necrolytic migratory erythema, weight loss |\n| Insulinoma | Insulin | Hypoglycemia (neuroglycopenic/adrenergic) |\n| Somatostatinoma | Somatostatin | Diabetes, steatorrhea, cholelithiasis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think ZES for multiple, refractory ulcers or ulcers in unusual locations.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would show multiple ulcers, often in the duodenum, and prominent, enlarged gastric folds. Imaging (CT/MRI/EUS) aims to localize the gastrinoma, which can be small and difficult to find, often in the gastrinoma triangle. Intraoperatively, careful palpation of the pancreas and duodenum is crucial.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Neuroendocrine Tumors, 2023. Recommends biochemical confirmation of ZES, followed by imaging for tumor localization and surgical resection if feasible.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | WDHA syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Glucagonoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Zollinger-Ellison syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Insulinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Somatostatinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Gastrinoma, or Zollinger-Ellison syndrome, should be suspected in patients with peptic ulcer disease** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
