  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spherocytes are spherical, but splenectomy makes life less circular.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation of anemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly points to a hemolytic anemia. The key differentiating factors are the autosomal dominant inheritance pattern and the statement that splenectomy is the *only* treatment, which are classic hallmarks of Hereditary Spherocytosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHereditary spherocytosis is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by defects in red blood cell membrane proteins (e.g., spectrin, ankyrin, band 3, protein 4.2). These defects lead to the formation of rigid, spherical red blood cells (spherocytes) that are prematurely trapped and destroyed in the spleen. Splenectomy removes the primary site of red cell destruction, thereby alleviating the symptoms of anemia and jaundice, though the underlying red cell defect persists. This intervention significantly improves the patient's quality of life and reduces transfusion dependence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Thalassemia) (Incorrect): Thalassemia is a defect in hemoglobin synthesis, not a red cell membrane defect, and while it causes hemolytic anemia and splenomegaly, it is typically autosomal recessive (major forms) and splenectomy is not the sole treatment.\nOption C (Sickle cell disease) (Incorrect): Sickle cell disease is an autosomal recessive disorder of hemoglobin structure, not autosomal dominant. Splenectomy is not the primary or only treatment and is reserved for specific complications like hypersplenism or acute sequestration.\nOption D (Idiopathic autoimmune hemolytic anemia) (Incorrect): This is an acquired immune-mediated condition, not an autosomal dominant genetic disorder. Treatment typically involves corticosteroids or other immunosuppressants before considering splenectomy.\nOption E (Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TPP)) (Incorrect): TTP is a microangiopathic hemolytic anemia characterized by thrombocytopenia and organ damage. It is not an autosomal dominant disorder, and plasma exchange, not splenectomy, is the primary treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hereditary Spherocytosis | Thalassemia | Sickle Cell Disease |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Inheritance | Autosomal Dominant | Autosomal Recessive (major) | Autosomal Recessive |\n| Defect | Red cell membrane proteins | Hemoglobin synthesis (alpha/beta chains) | Hemoglobin structure (HbS) |\n| RBC Morphology | Spherocytes | Microcytic, hypochromic | Sickle cells |\n| Primary Treatment | Splenectomy | Transfusions, chelation | Hydroxyurea, transfusions |\n| Splenectomy Role | Curative for hemolysis | Reduces transfusion burden | For complications (sequestration, hypersplenism) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anemia + Jaundice + Splenomegaly + AD + Splenectomy = Hereditary Spherocytosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (ultrasound/CT) would show splenomegaly. Intraoperatively, a significantly enlarged, congested spleen would be observed. Meticulous search for and removal of accessory spleens (splenunculi) is crucial to prevent recurrence of symptoms.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2020 guidelines for the management of hereditary spherocytosis recommend splenectomy for severe cases, typically after age 5-6, to avoid complications and allow for immune system development.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thalassemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hereditary spherocytosis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Sickle cell disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Idiopathic autoimmune hemolytic anemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TPP) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Hereditary spherocytosis is the most common symptomatic familial hemolytic anemia, and is transmitte** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
