  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anechoic on US? Think simple cyst, not complex disease!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Nonparasitic cyst. The presence of an anechoic 3-cm mass on ultrasound, especially when found incidentally in a patient presenting with unrelated symptoms (cholelithiasis), strongly suggests a benign, fluid-filled lesion like a nonparasitic cyst.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNonparasitic liver cysts are typically congenital, solitary, and more common in the right lobe. They contain clear, watery fluid and are characteristically anechoic (black, fluid-filled) on ultrasound due to their simple fluid content and lack of internal structures. Most are asymptomatic and discovered incidentally, as in this case where the patient's primary complaint is cholelithiasis. Their benign nature and distinct anechoic appearance on imaging differentiate them from other solid or complex cystic liver lesions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Hydatid cysts, while also cystic, typically show internal echoes, septations, or daughter cysts on ultrasound, distinguishing them from simple nonparasitic cysts. They are also parasitic in origin.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hamartomas are solid benign tumors, not anechoic cysts. Their sonographic appearance would be different, usually heterogeneous or solid.\nOption D (Incorrect): Adenomas are solid benign liver tumors, often associated with oral contraceptive use, and would appear as a solid mass, not anechoic, on ultrasound.\nOption E (Incorrect): Focal nodular hyperplasia (FNH) is a solid benign liver lesion, often characterized by a central scar, and is typically hypodense or iso-dense on imaging, not anechoic.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Nonparasitic Cyst       | Hydatid Cyst            | Hemangioma              | Focal Nodular Hyperplasia |\n|---------------------|-------------------------|-------------------------|-------------------------|---------------------------|\n| **Etiology**        | Congenital              | Parasitic (Echinococcus)| Congenital vascular malformation | Benign hyperplasia, often with central scar |\n| **Ultrasound**      | Anechoic, clear fluid   | Internal echoes, septations, daughter cysts | Variable echogenic pattern, often hyperechoic | Often hypodense/iso-dense, central scar |\n| **Fluid Content**   | Clear, watery           | Colorless, under high pressure | N/A (solid)             | N/A (solid)               |\n| **Symptoms**        | Usually asymptomatic, incidental | Can cause RUQ pain, fever, anaphylaxis if ruptured | Usually asymptomatic, incidental | Usually asymptomatic, incidental |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Incidental anechoic liver lesions are typically benign nonparasitic cysts.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a nonparasitic cyst appears as a well-defined, anechoic (black) lesion with posterior acoustic enhancement, indicating its fluid-filled nature. Intraoperatively, it would appear as a smooth-walled, thin-capsuled, fluid-filled sac on the liver surface.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance 2021: Evaluation of Incidental Liver Lesions. Recommends that simple cysts with classic benign imaging features do not require further follow-up.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Nonparasitic cyst | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Hydatid cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hamartoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Focal nodular hyperplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Benign liver cysts can be single or multiple. Solitary nonparasitic cysts usually contain clear, wat** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
