  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Enucleate the small, preserve the sweet.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is enucleation because most insulinomas are small, solitary, and benign, making simple tumor removal adequate while preserving pancreatic function. The 2-cm size and clear localization in the tail of the pancreas support this less invasive approach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEnucleation is the preferred surgical approach for small (<2 cm), benign, and well-localized insulinomas, especially when located in the body or tail of the pancreas. This technique allows for the precise removal of the tumor while preserving the surrounding healthy pancreatic parenchyma, thereby minimizing the risk of exocrine and endocrine insufficiency. The high success rate and low morbidity associated with enucleation make it ideal for these specific tumor characteristics.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Somatostatin receptor scintigraphy (SRS) is not always useful for insulinomas as they may not express somatostatin receptors, making it an unreliable localization or confirmation tool.\nOption B (Incorrect): Total pancreatectomy is an overly aggressive procedure almost never indicated for insulinomas, as it leads to severe diabetes and exocrine insufficiency.\nOption C (Incorrect): Distal pancreatectomy is a more extensive resection than necessary for a small, benign, and well-localized tumor, leading to greater loss of pancreatic function.\nOption D (Incorrect): Whipple pancreaticoduodenectomy is indicated for tumors in the head of the pancreas, not the tail, and is far too radical for a benign 2-cm insulinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Approach | Indication | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Enucleation | Small (<2cm), solitary, benign insulinoma (body/tail) | Preserves pancreatic function, minimal invasiveness |\n| Distal Pancreatectomy | Larger (>2cm), malignant, or multiple insulinomas (body/tail) | More extensive resection for higher risk tumors |\n| Whipple Pancreaticoduodenectomy | Malignant insulinoma in pancreatic head | Radical resection for tumors in critical location |\n| Total Pancreatectomy | Extremely rare, diffuse disease, or failed prior resections | Last resort due to severe endocrine/exocrine insufficiency |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small, solitary insulinomas in the body/tail are best enucleated to preserve pancreatic function.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn EUS, an insulinoma typically appears as a well-defined, hypoechoic lesion within the pancreatic parenchyma. Intraoperatively, they are often palpable as firm nodules and may be identified by intraoperative ultrasound or by changes in blood glucose during manipulation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Neuroendocrine Tumors, Pancreatic Neuroendocrine Tumors (2023) recommends enucleation for small, well-localized, non-invasive insulinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Somatostatin receptor scintigraphy (SRS) to confirm the insulinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Exploratory laparotomy and total pancreatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Distal pancreatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Whipple pancreaticoduodenectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Enucleation of the tumor | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Most insulinomas are small (<2 cm), solitary, and benign. Therefore, simple enucleation is ade-quate** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
