  "answer": "D) Lactescent serum is sometimes seen soon after an acute attack of pancreatitis. Lipase level should be elevated to show pancreatitis as the cause of the abdominal pain. Hypertrigly-ceridemia artificially lowers serum amylase levels. If the blood specimen appears milky, the serum should be diluted; after dilution, serum amylase levels may become elevated. Other uncommon causes of pancreatitis include steroids, thiazide diuretics, lasix, sul-fonamides, protein deficiency, hypercalcemia, familial, traumatic, idiopathic, and anatomic anomalies such as stricture, or pancreas divi-sum of the pancreatic duct.",
