  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the bile ducts get tough, check the gut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with jaundice and radiologically confirmed sclerosing cholangitis, coupled with a long history of chronic diarrhea requiring steroids. This clinical picture strongly suggests an underlying inflammatory bowel disease, and Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) has a well-established and strong association with Ulcerative Colitis (UC).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) is a chronic, progressive cholestatic liver disease characterized by inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts, leading to strictures. It is strongly associated with inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), particularly ulcerative colitis, which is found in 60-80% of PSC patients. The shared autoimmune mechanisms and inflammatory pathways are thought to contribute to this strong link. The patient's history of chronic diarrhea and steroid use further supports an IBD diagnosis, making Ulcerative Colitis the most likely co-existing condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pernicious anemia) (Incorrect): While an autoimmune condition, pernicious anemia has no direct or significant association with sclerosing cholangitis or chronic diarrhea.\nOption C (Celiac disease) (Incorrect): Celiac disease causes chronic diarrhea due to malabsorption but is not directly linked to primary sclerosing cholangitis.\nOption D (Liver cirrhosis) (Incorrect): Liver cirrhosis is an end-stage consequence of untreated or progressive sclerosing cholangitis, not the underlying condition causing the cholangitis itself. The question asks what she is *likely to suffer from*, implying a primary or co-existing disease.\nOption E (Crohn’s disease) (Incorrect): While Crohn's disease is an inflammatory bowel disease, Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis is much more strongly associated with Ulcerative Colitis than with Crohn's disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) | Ulcerative Colitis (UC) | Crohn's Disease (CD) |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Organ Affected** | Bile ducts (intra/extrahepatic) | Colon and rectum (continuous) | Any part of GI tract (mouth to anus, skip lesions) |\n| **Association** | Strong with UC (60-80%), less with CD | Strong with PSC | Less strong with PSC than UC |\n| **Symptoms** | Jaundice, pruritus, fatigue, RUQ pain | Bloody diarrhea, tenesmus, abdominal pain | Abdominal pain, diarrhea (non-bloody), weight loss, fistulas |\n| **Pathology** | Fibrosis, strictures, \"onion skin\" periductal fibrosis | Mucosal inflammation, crypt abscesses | Transmural inflammation, granulomas |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PSC + chronic diarrhea = think Ulcerative Colitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRCP or ERCP, PSC typically shows multifocal stricturing and dilatations of the intrahepatic and/or extrahepatic bile ducts, giving a characteristic \"beaded\" appearance.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance on Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (2023). It recommends screening for IBD in all PSC patients and vice versa.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pernicious anemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ulcerative colitis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Celiac disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Liver cirrhosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Crohn’s disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Sclerosing cholangitis is rare and occurs mainly in the third and fourth decades of life. Unlike mos** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
