  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, HIDA flow will show you the way!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, HIDA scan. A HIDA scan is the initial, least invasive test with the best yield to assess the functional patency of a choledochoduodenostomy. It directly evaluates the flow of bile into the duodenum, which is crucial for determining if the anastomosis is open.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe HIDA (hepatobiliary iminodiacetic acid) scan utilizes a radiolabeled isotope that is taken up by hepatocytes and excreted into the biliary system, mimicking bile flow. For a patent choledochoduodenostomy, the isotope should be visualized flowing from the common bile duct directly into the duodenum. This functional assessment is superior to purely anatomical imaging for evaluating the patency of a biliary-enteric anastomosis, as it directly demonstrates the presence or absence of bile flow across the surgical connection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): ERCP is an invasive procedure with risks like pancreatitis and perforation. While it can assess patency, it is not the initial, least invasive test, and may be technically challenging with altered anatomy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiogram (PTC) is also an invasive procedure, typically reserved for cases where ERCP is unsuccessful or contraindicated, or for direct drainage, not as an initial diagnostic test for patency.\nOption D (Incorrect): A CT scan of the abdomen provides excellent anatomical detail but is less effective at directly assessing the functional patency of a small biliary-enteric anastomosis. It might show ductal dilation but not necessarily flow.\nOption E (Incorrect): Ultrasound of the abdomen is a good initial screening tool for biliary pathology (e.g., ductal dilation, stones) but cannot reliably assess the functional patency of a choledochoduodenostomy directly.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Invasiveness | Primary Use | Patency Assessment |\n| :------- | :----------- | :---------- | :----------------- |\n| HIDA scan | Non-invasive | Functional assessment of bile flow, cystic duct patency, biliary-enteric anastomosis patency | Excellent (functional) |\n| ERCP | Invasive | Diagnostic and therapeutic for biliary and pancreatic duct pathology (stones, strictures) | Good (direct visualization, but invasive) |\n| CT scan | Non-invasive | Anatomical imaging of abdomen, ductal dilation, masses | Poor (anatomical, not functional flow) |\n| Ultrasound | Non-invasive | Initial screening for biliary dilation, stones, cholecystitis | Poor (anatomical, not functional flow) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: HIDA for functional patency of biliary-enteric anastomoses.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a HIDA scan, a patent choledochoduodenostomy would show prompt visualization of the radiotracer entering the duodenum from the common bile duct. If occluded, the tracer would accumulate in the dilated biliary tree without entering the small bowel.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Right Upper Quadrant Pain (2021) supports non-invasive imaging first for biliary concerns.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | ERCP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiogram (PTC) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | HIDA scan | ✅ Correct |\n| D | CT scan of the abdomen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Ultrasound of the abdomen | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) A HIDA scan will show excretion of the radiolabeled isotope into the biliary tree, but there will be** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
