  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Splenectomy success isn't forever; accessory spleens can be sneaky.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's recurrence of thrombocytopenia two years after a successful splenectomy strongly suggests the presence of a retained accessory spleen (splenunculus). This accessory spleen has likely hypertrophied and resumed its function of sequestering platelets, leading to the return of symptoms. Identifying this tissue is crucial for definitive treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadioactive technetium (99mTc)-labeled heat-damaged red blood cells are the gold standard for localizing splenic tissue. This imaging modality works because the reticuloendothelial cells within splenic tissue preferentially take up the damaged red blood cells. An accessory spleen, or splenunculus, is a congenital remnant of splenic tissue that can become functionally active, leading to recurrent immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) after a primary splenectomy. Localizing it allows for targeted surgical removal.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Radioactive I135 is primarily used for thyroid imaging, not for localizing splenic tissue. The correct isotope for splenic scintigraphy is 99mTc.\nOption C (Incorrect): Exploratory laparotomy is an invasive procedure and should not be the initial diagnostic step. Imaging studies are required first to localize any potential accessory splenic tissue.\nOption D (Incorrect): Platelet transfusion provides only temporary relief and does not address the underlying cause of recurrent thrombocytopenia, which in this case is likely a functional splenunculus.\nOption E (Incorrect): A red blood cell (RBC) fragility test is used to diagnose hereditary spherocytosis, a condition involving hemolytic anemia, and is irrelevant to the diagnosis or management of thrombocytopenia or ITP.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Indication | Key Feature |\n| :--------------- | :--------- | :---------- |\n| 99mTc-heat-damaged RBCs | Accessory spleen, splenic tissue | Specific uptake by splenic reticuloendothelial cells |\n| 99mTc-sulfur colloid | Liver/spleen imaging, general RES function | Less specific for ectopic splenic tissue than damaged RBCs |\n| CT/MRI abdomen | General abdominal anatomy, masses | Can identify accessory spleens but less specific for functional tissue |\n| I135 scan | Thyroid imaging | Used for thyroid function and cancer detection, not spleen |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Recurrent ITP post-splenectomy? Always suspect a splenunculus; scan with 99mTc.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a 99mTc-heat-damaged RBC scan, a splenunculus would appear as a focal area of increased radiotracer uptake outside the normal splenic bed, indicating functional splenic tissue. Intraoperatively, it would present as a small, reddish-purple nodule of splenic tissue, often found in the omentum, mesentery, or near the pancreatic tail.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2018 guidelines for Immune Thrombocytopenia (ITP) recommend imaging for accessory spleens in patients with recurrent ITP after splenectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radioactive technetium (99mTc) scan to see if a splenunculus is present | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Radioactive (I135) to see if a splenunculus is present | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Exploratory laparotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Platelet transfusion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Red blood cell (RBC) fragility test | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Radioactive technetium (99mTc) scan to see if a retained accessory spleen (splenunculus) is present,** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
