  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 TTP: When platelets clot where they shouldn't, organs pay the rent.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is elevated urea and creatinine levels, which directly indicates renal involvement, a hallmark feature of Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (TTP). TTP is characterized by microvascular thrombosis leading to organ damage, with the kidneys being a frequently affected site.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTTP is a life-threatening disorder characterized by widespread formation of platelet-rich thrombi in the microvasculature throughout the body. This leads to a classic pentad of symptoms: microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (MAHA), thrombocytopenia, fever, neurological manifestations, and renal dysfunction. The microthrombi occlude small blood vessels, causing ischemia and infarction in various organs. In the kidneys, these thrombi obstruct glomerular capillaries and renal arterioles, impairing filtration and leading to acute kidney injury, which is reflected by elevated serum urea and creatinine levels.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): TTP is characterized by diffuse hyalinization and occlusion of arterioles and capillaries due to microthrombi, not normal arterioles.\nOption B (Incorrect): The occlusion of microvessels by thrombi in TTP frequently leads to tissue ischemia and infarction, including in the spleen, making the absence of infarction incorrect.\nOption C (Incorrect): TTP is primarily associated with thrombocytopenia and hemolytic anemia. Leukopenia is not a typical feature; rather, a mild leukocytosis can sometimes be seen.\nOption E (Incorrect): Microangiopathic hemolytic anemia in TTP involves increased destruction of red blood cells. The bone marrow attempts to compensate for this loss by increasing red blood cell production, which would lead to an *elevation* of reticulocytes, not suppression.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | TTP | HUS | ITP |\n| :------------------ | :--------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------- |\n| Primary Defect | ADAMTS13 deficiency | Shiga toxin (E. coli O157:H7) | Autoantibodies against platelets |\n| Key Clinical Triad | MAHA, Thrombocytopenia, Renal failure | MAHA, Thrombocytopenia, Renal failure | Isolated Thrombocytopenia |\n| Neurological Sx | Common | Less common (more renal) | Rare |\n| Renal Involvement | Common, often severe | Prominent, often severe | Rare |\n| Treatment | Plasmapheresis, steroids, caplacizumab | Supportive, plasmapheresis (atypical HUS) | Steroids, IVIG, splenectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: TTP's pentad: Fever, MAHA, Thrombocytopenia, Renal failure, Neuro symptoms.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nRenal biopsy in TTP would reveal microthrombi within glomerular capillaries and arterioles, with evidence of ischemic injury and hyalinization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2020 guidelines for TTP. They recommend prompt diagnosis and initiation of plasmapheresis and immunosuppression.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Normal arterioles on biopsy of the spleen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Absence of infarction on biopsy of the spleen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Leukopenia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Elevated urea and creatinine levels | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Suppression of reticulocytes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Features of TTP include fever, thrombocy-topenic purpura, hemolytic anemia, neurolog-ical manifestat** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
