  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't miss the PSA for the high-risk man; it's a prostate-specific plan!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Prostate-specific antigen (PSA). This test is the primary blood marker used for prostate cancer screening, especially relevant for an African American male over 50 with urinary symptoms, who is considered high-risk.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPSA is a glycoprotein produced by the prostate gland. While elevated levels can indicate prostate cancer, they can also be due to benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), prostatitis, or recent prostate manipulation. However, it remains the most effective initial blood test for screening. African American men and those with a family history of prostate cancer are at higher risk and typically begin screening earlier, making PSA an essential part of their workup.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) is primarily used as a tumor marker for colorectal cancer, not prostate cancer.\nOption B (Incorrect): Prostatic acid phosphatase (PAP) was historically used for prostate cancer, but PSA has largely replaced it due to its superior sensitivity and specificity for screening.\nOption C (Incorrect): Alkaline phosphatase is a marker for bone metastasis or liver disease, not for primary prostate cancer screening.\nOption E (Incorrect): Lactic dehydrogenase (LDH) is a general marker of tissue damage or tumor burden and is not specific for prostate cancer screening.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Marker | Primary Use/Associated Condition | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| PSA | Prostate cancer screening, monitoring | Elevated in BPH, prostatitis; not cancer-specific |\n| CEA | Colorectal cancer, gastric, pancreatic | Non-specific, used for monitoring recurrence |\n| AFP | Hepatocellular carcinoma, germ cell tumors | Also elevated in pregnancy |\n| CA 19-9 | Pancreatic cancer | Can be elevated in other GI cancers, cholangitis |\n| CA-125 | Ovarian cancer | Can be elevated in endometriosis, fibroids |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PSA is the go-to blood test for prostate cancer screening, especially in high-risk groups.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nTransrectal ultrasound (TRUS) with biopsy is used to confirm prostate cancer. Multiparametric MRI can help stage the disease and guide targeted biopsies.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Cancer Society (ACS) and American Urological Association (AUA) guidelines recommend shared decision-making for PSA screening, typically starting at age 50 for average risk, and earlier (40-45) for high-risk individuals like African American men.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Prostatic acid phosphatase | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Alkaline phosphatase | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Prostate-specific antigen (PSA) | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Lactic dehydrogenase (LDH) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) According to American Cancer Society, all men over the age of 50 years should undergo annual PSA mea** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
