  "answer": "D) At any time during prostate cancer screening, if either the PSA or the DRE is abnormal, recommendation is referral to a urologist to perform TRUS guided biopsy of prostate.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just feel it, prove it: Biopsy the bump!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe presence of an irregular mass on digital rectal examination (DRE) is a significant finding highly suggestive of prostate cancer. The immediate and most appropriate next step for definitive diagnosis is a biopsy of the suspicious area to obtain tissue for histopathological examination.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn abnormal DRE, such as an irregular mass or nodule, is a strong indicator for prostate cancer and necessitates further investigation, even with normal blood tests. While PSA levels are important, a palpable abnormality on DRE often takes precedence in the diagnostic pathway. A transrectal ultrasound (TRUS)-guided biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosing prostate cancer, allowing for targeted sampling of suspicious areas identified by DRE or imaging, or systematic sampling of the gland. This procedure provides the definitive histological diagnosis required for treatment planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A CT scan of the pelvis is primarily used for staging established prostate cancer, not for initial diagnosis of a palpable mass. It would not provide a tissue diagnosis.\nOption B (Incorrect): MRI of the prostate is increasingly used for targeted biopsies and local staging, but it is not the initial diagnostic step after an abnormal DRE; a biopsy is required for definitive diagnosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): A colonoscopy is irrelevant to the diagnosis of a prostate mass. While a biopsy is needed, performing it under general anesthetic as the *initial* step is not standard; TRUS-guided biopsy is typically done under local anesthesia.\nOption E (Incorrect): A bone scan is used for detecting metastatic disease, specifically bone metastases, and is indicated for staging *after* a diagnosis of prostate cancer has been made, not as an initial diagnostic step for a palpable mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Tool | Purpose | Key Indication |\n|---|---|---|\n| Digital Rectal Exam (DRE) | Physical assessment of prostate | Palpable nodules, asymmetry, induration |\n| Prostate-Specific Antigen (PSA) | Blood test for prostate health | Elevated levels can indicate cancer, BPH, prostatitis |\n| Transrectal Ultrasound (TRUS) | Imaging for prostate visualization | Guides biopsy, assesses gland volume |\n| Prostate Biopsy | Definitive tissue diagnosis | Abnormal DRE or elevated/rising PSA |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Abnormal DRE or PSA warrants urology referral for prostate biopsy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring a TRUS-guided biopsy, the ultrasound probe visualizes the prostate gland, allowing the urologist to target the irregular mass identified on DRE and systematically sample other areas, typically obtaining 10-12 core biopsies.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines 2023 for Early Detection of Prostate Cancer. These guidelines recommend that for men with an abnormal DRE or elevated PSA, shared decision-making regarding prostate biopsy should occur.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Computed tomography (CT) scan of the pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Magnetic resonance image (MRI) of the prostate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Colonoscopy and biopsy of the prostate under general anesthetic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Biopsy of the nodule | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Bone scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) At any time during prostate cancer screening, if either the PSA or the DRE is abnormal, recommendati** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
