  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't treat what you haven't staged!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is correct. After a positive TRUS biopsy confirms prostate adenocarcinoma, the immediate next step is to determine the extent of the disease (staging) before deciding on definitive treatment. This involves evaluating for metastatic spread, particularly to common sites like bone and lymph nodes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProstate cancer commonly metastasizes to regional lymph nodes and bone. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is crucial for assessing pelvic lymphadenopathy and can also identify other genitourinary abnormalities. A bone scan is used to detect bone metastases, but its utility is guided by PSA levels, typically recommended for PSA > 20 ng/mL, or in cases of high-grade disease or clinical symptoms, as noted in the explanation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Chemotherapy is reserved for advanced, metastatic, or castration-resistant prostate cancer, not for initial staging after diagnosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Repeating PSA and biopsy is not indicated after a positive biopsy. The diagnosis is already established; the next step is staging.\nOption D (Incorrect): Evaluation by a radiation oncologist is part of treatment planning, which occurs after the disease has been staged.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hormonal ablation is a form of treatment for prostate cancer, not a staging procedure. It's considered after staging and discussion of treatment options.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stage/Action | Description | Key Modalities |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Diagnosis** | Suspicion based on elevated PSA/DRE | TRUS biopsy |\n| **Staging** | Determine extent of disease | CT Abdomen/Pelvis, Bone Scan (PSA-dependent), MRI Prostate |\n| **Treatment Planning** | Based on stage, grade, patient factors | Active Surveillance, Surgery, Radiation, Hormonal Therapy, Chemo |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Positive prostate biopsy? Stage it first, then treat.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, enlarged or irregular pelvic lymph nodes suggest metastasis. On bone scan, 'hot spots' (increased radiotracer uptake) indicate osteoblastic metastases, common in prostate cancer.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Prostate Cancer, 2024. Recommends imaging for staging (CT/MRI and bone scan) based on risk stratification (PSA, Gleason score, clinical stage), particularly for intermediate/high-risk disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Refer to oncologist for chemotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Metastatic evaluation including CT and bone scans | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Repeat PSA and biospy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Evaluation by radiation oncologist | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Start hormonal ablation treatment | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Typical workup after a positive TRUS biopsy would be evaluating the common metastatic sites (pelvic ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
