  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Painless lump in a young man's testicle? Think cancer, act fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, stating that testicular cancer presents as a painless mass in the scrotum in more than 70% of patients. This is the classic and most common presentation, making it a critical diagnostic clue for this malignancy, despite the patient's complaint of heaviness.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTesticular cancer is the most common solid malignancy in men aged 15-35 years. While the question describes a patient with groin heaviness after lifting, the most typical presentation is a painless, firm, non-transilluminating mass in the testis. Any scrotal mass should be considered malignant until proven otherwise, especially in this age group. Early detection is crucial due to its high cure rate when localized.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Testicular cancer is the most common solid tumor in men aged 15-35, not over 50. Testicular lymphoma is more common in men over 50.\nOption B (Incorrect): Testicular cancer and its treatment (chemotherapy, radiation, surgery) are associated with a higher incidence of infertility, both pre-existing and treatment-induced.\nOption D (Incorrect): Testicular cancer accounts for only 1-2% of all malignant tumors in men, not 10%.\nOption E (Incorrect): Testicular cancer frequently metastasizes, primarily via lymphatic spread to retroperitoneal lymph nodes, and hematogenously to lungs, liver, and brain.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Testicular Cancer | Testicular Lymphoma | Epididymitis/Orchitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Typical Age** | 15-35 years | >50 years | Any age |\n| **Presentation** | Painless, firm scrotal mass | Painless or painful mass | Painful, swollen, tender |\n| **Transillumination** | No | No | May or may not |\n| **Associated Factors** | Cryptorchidism, infertility | Immunosuppression | UTI, STIs |\n| **Metastasis** | Common (lymphatic, hematogenous) | Common (systemic) | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Any painless testicular mass in a young man is cancer until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn scrotal ultrasound, testicular cancer typically appears as a hypoechoic, heterogeneous, often hypervascular intratesticular mass. Intraoperatively, an inguinal orchiectomy is performed, and the testis is delivered into the field to assess the mass.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Testicular Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend radical inguinal orchiectomy for suspected testicular cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is the most common solid tumor in men over 50 years of age. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is not associated with a higher incidence of infertility. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It presents as a painless mass in the scrotum in more than 70% of patients. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | It accounts for 10% of malignant tumors in men. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It rarely metastasizes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Testicular cancer accounts for 1–2% of all malignant tumors in men. There are two categories of test** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
