  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, cut it out – especially if it's a solid testicular mass!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cancer of the testis. A solid, non-tender mass within the testis, especially in a young man presenting with infertility, is highly suspicious for testicular malignancy until proven otherwise.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTesticular cancer is the most common solid malignancy in men aged 15-35 years. It typically presents as a painless, solid mass within the testicular parenchyma, though a dull ache or heaviness can occur. Infertility can be an associated symptom, either due to the tumor itself or underlying testicular dysfunction. The two main categories are germ cell tumors (seminoma, nonseminoma) and non-germ cell tumors (Leydig cell, Sertoli cell), all of which present as solid masses requiring prompt evaluation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Torsion of the testis presents with acute, severe scrotal pain and tenderness, often with a high-riding testis, and does not typically involve a solid intratesticular mass.\nOption B (Incorrect): A cyst of the epididymis is typically a cystic, fluid-filled lesion located in the epididymis, separate from the testis, and is usually benign.\nOption C (Incorrect): A lipoma of the cord is a benign fatty tumor located within the spermatic cord, superior to the testis, and would not present as a solid intratesticular mass.\nOption E (Incorrect): Epididymo-orchitis is an inflammatory condition causing acute pain, swelling, and tenderness of the epididymis and/or testis, often with fever, and is not characterized by a distinct solid tumor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Testicular Cancer         | Testicular Torsion        | Epididymo-orchitis        | Epididymal Cyst           |\n|---------------------|---------------------------|---------------------------|---------------------------|---------------------------|\n| **Mass**            | Solid, intratesticular    | No distinct mass          | Diffuse swelling/tenderness | Cystic, epididymal        |\n| **Pain**            | Usually painless (can be dull ache) | Acute, severe             | Acute, painful, tender    | Usually painless          |\n| **Location**        | Within testis             | Testis/cord               | Epididymis/testis         | Epididymis                |\n| **Consistency**     | Firm/hard                 | Normal/swollen            | Inflamed, tender          | Soft, fluctuant           |\n| **Associated Sx**   | Infertility, hydrocele    | Nausea, vomiting          | Fever, dysuria            | None                      |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Any solid intratesticular mass is testicular cancer until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn scrotal ultrasound, testicular cancer typically appears as a hypoechoic, heterogeneous, solid intratesticular mass with increased vascularity on color Doppler.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Testicular Cancer (e.g., Version 1.2023). They recommend radical inguinal orchiectomy for suspicious solid testicular masses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Torsion of the testis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cyst of the epididymis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lipoma of the cord | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cancer of the testis | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Epididymo-orchitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Nonhematogenous testicular tumors are divided into two categories—germ cell tumors (seminoma, nonsem** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
