  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For invasive vulvar SCC, go big or go home (to the OR!).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, radical vulvectomy and bilateral groin dissection. This approach is indicated for invasive squamous cell carcinoma of the vulva, particularly when involving the labia majora, due to the high risk of lymphatic spread. This aggressive surgical management significantly improves survival rates by addressing both the primary tumor and potential regional nodal metastases.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadical vulvectomy involves the complete removal of the vulva, ensuring wide tumor-free margins. Bilateral groin dissection targets both superficial and deep inguinal lymph nodes, which are the primary drainage sites for the vulva. This comprehensive nodal clearance is crucial because vulvar SCC, especially from the labia, can spread bilaterally. The removal of these nodes, even if clinically negative, is paramount for accurate staging and improved oncologic outcomes, leading to cure rates exceeding 70% when nodes are not involved.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Wide local excision alone is typically reserved for very early, superficial, or small lesions, not for invasive SCC of the labia majora which carries a significant risk of nodal involvement.\nOption B (Incorrect): Radiotherapy alone is generally not the primary treatment for invasive vulvar SCC; the provided answer key explicitly states it has not offered additional benefit in this context.\nOption C (Incorrect): Preoperative radiotherapy followed by wide local excision is insufficient. Radiotherapy alone is not curative, and wide local excision is inadequate for invasive disease requiring nodal assessment.\nOption D (Incorrect): Wide excision and unilateral groin dissection is insufficient. While wide excision is better than local, it may not be radical enough, and unilateral groin dissection is inadequate for labial lesions which can have bilateral lymphatic drainage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Treatment Strategy |\n|---|---|\n| Early, superficial vulvar SCC | Wide local excision |\n| Invasive vulvar SCC (e.g., labia majora) | Radical vulvectomy + Bilateral groin dissection |\n| Penile SCC (analogy) | Partial/Total penectomy + Bilateral groin dissection |\n| Vulvar Paget's disease | Wide local excision (often repeated) |\n| Vulvar melanoma | Wide local excision + Sentinel lymph node biopsy/Groin dissection |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Invasive vulvar SCC = Radical vulvectomy + bilateral groin dissection.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after radical vulvectomy, the surgeon will meticulously dissect the inguinal and femoral lymph nodes, identifying and removing both superficial and deep groups. On imaging (e.g., CT/MRI), enlarged or suspicious inguinal lymph nodes would raise concern for metastatic disease, guiding the extent of dissection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Vulvar Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend radical vulvectomy with bilateral inguinofemoral lymphadenectomy for invasive squamous cell carcinoma of the vulva.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wide local excision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Preoperative radiotherapy followed by wide local excision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Wide excision and unilateral groin dissection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Radical vulvectomy and bilateral groin dissection | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Similar to penile cancer, radical vulvectomy and bilateral groin dissection have improved survival i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
