  "question": "A24-year-old man had been treated for gonorrhea 2 months previously. He developed an ulcerative lesion in the glands of the penis that is noted to be condylomata lata. The etiology of condylomata lata is which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Mixture of organisms",
    "B": "Haemophilus ducreyi",
    "C": "Herpesvirus hominis, type II",
    "D": "Treponema pallidum",
    "E": "Neisseria gonorrhoeae"
  },
  "answer": "D) Condylomata lata are a manifestation of secondary syphilis. The treatment is intramuscular injection of penicillin. They are distinguished from condylomata acuminata; in that the latter are velvety and filiform in appearance and are result of infection with human papilloma virus (HPV).",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Broad, flat, moist? Think syphilis, not just warts!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Treponema pallidum. Condylomata lata are a classic manifestation of secondary syphilis, caused by the spirochete Treponema pallidum, making this the definitive etiology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCondylomata lata are moist, broad-based, wart-like lesions that typically appear in moist intertriginous areas such as the anogenital region, axillae, or under breasts. Histologically, they show epidermal hyperplasia with acanthosis and a dense inflammatory infiltrate rich in plasma cells, often with spirochetes visible on silver stain. They are highly infectious and represent a systemic dissemination of Treponema pallidum during the secondary stage of syphilis, following the primary chancre. It is crucial to distinguish them from condylomata acuminata (genital warts), which are caused by Human Papillomavirus (HPV) and are typically filiform or cauliflower-like.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Mixture of organisms) (Incorrect): Condylomata lata have a specific, singular etiology, not a mixed infection.\nOption B (Haemophilus ducreyi) (Incorrect): This bacterium causes chancroid, which presents as painful, soft chancres with ragged borders, distinct from condylomata lata.\nOption C (Herpesvirus hominis, type II) (Incorrect): Herpes simplex virus type 2 causes genital herpes, characterized by painful vesicles that ulcerate, not broad, flat lesions like condylomata lata.\nOption E (Neisseria gonorrhoeae) (Incorrect): Neisseria gonorrhoeae causes gonorrhea, primarily presenting as urethritis, cervicitis, or pharyngitis, and does not cause condylomata lata.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Condylomata Lata | Condylomata Acuminata | Chancroid | Genital Herpes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Treponema pallidum | Human Papillomavirus (HPV) | Haemophilus ducreyi | Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV) |\n| **Disease Stage** | Secondary Syphilis | HPV Infection | Chancroid | HSV Infection |\n| **Appearance** | Broad, flat, moist, velvety plaques | Filiform, cauliflower-like, verrucous | Painful, soft ulcer with ragged borders | Painful vesicles that ulcerate |\n| **Infectivity** | Highly infectious | Highly infectious | Highly infectious | Highly infectious |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Condylomata lata = Syphilis. Condylomata acuminata = HPV.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn gross inspection, condylomata lata appear as flat-topped, moist, grayish-white or pinkish lesions, often coalescing, typically found in warm, moist areas like the perineum or groin.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC 2021 STI Treatment Guidelines. These guidelines recommend penicillin G benzathine for the treatment of syphilis, including secondary syphilis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mixture of organisms | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Haemophilus ducreyi | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Herpesvirus hominis, type II | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Treponema pallidum | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Neisseria gonorrhoeae | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Condylomata lata are a manifestation of secondary syphilis. The treatment is intramuscular injection** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
