  "id": 130608,
  "question": "A 24-year-old woman has been unsuccessful becoming pregnant. She is admitted with abdominal pain; her blood pressure is 90/60 mm Hg, her pulse rate is 102 beats per minute (bpm), and her hematocrit (HCT) is 28%. Features of ectopic pregnancy include which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Elevated blood pressure on assuming an erect position",
    "B": "Pulsus paradoxus",
    "C": "Tenderness below the right subcostal margin (Murphy’s sign)",
    "D": "Pain referred to the supraclavicular region",
    "E": "Ecchymosis around the umbilicus"
  },
  "answer": "D) Free bleeding in the peritoneal cavity results in pain referred to the right supraclavicular region due to diaphragmatic irritation. Patients who present with abdominal pain and (usually) a history of missed menstruation should undergo a pregnancy test after hospital admission.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Shoulder pain in a hypotensive woman? Think ruptured ectopic, stat!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. This patient presents with classic signs of hypovolemic shock (hypotension, tachycardia, low HCT) and abdominal pain, highly suggestive of a ruptured ectopic pregnancy with significant hemoperitoneum. The referred pain to the supraclavicular region is a hallmark sign of diaphragmatic irritation due to free intraperitoneal blood.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFree blood in the peritoneal cavity, particularly when it irritates the diaphragm, stimulates the phrenic nerve. The phrenic nerve (C3-C5) shares spinal cord segments with the supraclavicular nerves, leading to referred pain in the ipsilateral shoulder or supraclavicular region, known as Kehr's sign. This is a critical diagnostic clue for conditions causing diaphragmatic irritation, such as ruptured ectopic pregnancy, splenic rupture, or subphrenic abscess. The patient's hemodynamic instability underscores the urgency of recognizing this sign.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Elevated blood pressure on assuming an erect position is orthostatic hypertension, which is not expected in a patient with hypovolemic shock. Orthostatic hypotension (a drop in BP) would be more likely.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pulsus paradoxus is an exaggerated drop in systolic blood pressure during inspiration, typically associated with cardiac tamponade, severe asthma, or constrictive pericarditis, not ruptured ectopic pregnancy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Tenderness below the right subcostal margin (Murphy’s sign) is a classic sign of acute cholecystitis, indicating gallbladder inflammation, which is unrelated to a ruptured ectopic pregnancy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Ecchymosis around the umbilicus (Cullen’s sign) indicates retroperitoneal hemorrhage or severe intra-abdominal bleeding, often seen in pancreatitis or ruptured ectopic, but it is a less common and usually a later, more severe sign than diaphragmatic irritation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sign / Symptom          | Description                                                              | Associated Condition(s)                                   |\n|-------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------|\n| Kehr's Sign             | Referred pain to the left shoulder/supraclavicular region                | Splenic rupture, ruptured ectopic pregnancy, diaphragmatic irritation |\n| Cullen's Sign           | Periumbilical ecchymosis                                                 | Pancreatitis, ruptured ectopic pregnancy, retroperitoneal hemorrhage |\n| Grey Turner's Sign      | Flank ecchymosis                                                         | Pancreatitis, retroperitoneal hemorrhage                  |\n| Murphy's Sign           | Inspiratory arrest on palpation of right upper quadrant                  | Acute cholecystitis                                       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Shoulder pain + hypovolemia = intraperitoneal bleed until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn transvaginal ultrasound, one would typically see free fluid (blood) in the cul-de-sac or Morrison's pouch, and potentially an adnexal mass or gestational sac outside the uterus. Intraoperatively, a ruptured fallopian tube with active bleeding and hemoperitoneum would be evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 193 (2018) on Ectopic Pregnancy recommends prompt diagnosis and management, including surgical intervention for hemodynamically unstable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Elevated blood pressure on assuming an erect position | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pulsus paradoxus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tenderness below the right subcostal margin (Murphy’s sign) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pain referred to the supraclavicular region | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Ecchymosis around the umbilicus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Free bleeding in the peritoneal cavity results in pain referred to the right supraclavicular region ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
