  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cisplatin: The platinum standard for cancer, but mind the nerves and kidneys!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Peripheral neuropathy. Cisplatin is a platinum-based chemotherapy agent widely used in oncology, and its dose-limiting toxicities, including peripheral neuropathy, are critical to recognize and manage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCisplatin-induced peripheral neuropathy (CIPN) is a cumulative, dose-dependent toxicity primarily affecting sensory neurons, leading to a 'stocking-glove' distribution of symptoms. The mechanism involves damage to the dorsal root ganglia and peripheral nerves, interfering with axonal transport and causing demyelination. This neurotoxicity can be debilitating and often irreversible, significantly impacting a patient's quality of life. Other hallmark toxicities of cisplatin include nephrotoxicity (which can be mitigated by aggressive hydration) and ototoxicity (hearing loss, tinnitus).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Multiple lipoma are benign fatty tumors and have no known association with cisplatin treatment.\nOption B (Incorrect): Ankylosing spondylitis is a chronic inflammatory autoimmune disease primarily affecting the spine, unrelated to cisplatin side effects.\nOption C (Incorrect): Megaloblastic anemia is typically caused by vitamin B12 or folate deficiency. While cisplatin can cause anemia, it is usually normocytic and not megaloblastic.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pulmonary fibrosis is a well-known side effect of other chemotherapy agents like bleomycin or busulfan, but not typically associated with cisplatin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Chemotherapy Agent | Key Side Effect(s) |\n|--------------------|--------------------|\n| Cisplatin          | Peripheral neuropathy, Nephrotoxicity, Ototoxicity, Severe Nausea/Vomiting |\n| Bleomycin          | Pulmonary Fibrosis |\n| Doxorubicin        | Cardiotoxicity (Dilated Cardiomyopathy) |\n| Vincristine        | Peripheral Neuropathy (often motor), Constipation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cisplatin's 'P' is for Platinum, Peripheral neuropathy, and Pee (nephrotoxicity).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, severe cisplatin-induced nephrotoxicity might manifest as hydronephrosis or renal parenchymal changes on CT/ultrasound if not adequately managed. Nerve conduction studies could objectively demonstrate peripheral neuropathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Survivorship (2023) recommends screening and management strategies for chemotherapy-induced peripheral neuropathy, including those caused by platinum agents.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Multiple lipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ankylosing spondylitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Megaloblastic anemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pulmonary fibrosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Peripheral neuropathy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Peripheral neuropathy, ototoxicity, and nephrotoxicity may be encountered following cisplatinum trea** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
