  "id": 130622,
  "question": "A64-year-old man underwent transplantation, which was complicated by graft-versus-host reaction. He had undergone a transplantation of which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Kidney",
    "B": "Skin",
    "C": "Bone marrow",
    "D": "Cornea",
    "E": "Liver"
  },
  "answer": "C) Normal bone marrow cells are destroyed readily by drugs and ionizing irradiation; the red blood cell (RBC) stem cell in particular is sensitive to damage. The marrow is not destroyed by the host if transplanted into an immunosuppressed host. The transplanted bone marrow develops mature stem cells, which have immunologic competence that now reject those of the host (graft-versus-host reaction). Diarrhea, dermatitis, weight loss, and infection occur.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the graft fights back, it's bone marrow's unique attack!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Bone marrow. Graft-versus-host reaction (GVHR) or disease (GVHD) is a unique complication of allogeneic hematopoietic stem cell (bone marrow) transplantation, where immunocompetent donor T-cells recognize the recipient's tissues as foreign and mount an immune attack.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn allogeneic bone marrow transplantation, the donor's immune system, specifically mature T-lymphocytes within the graft, is transferred to an immunosuppressed recipient. These donor T-cells perceive the recipient's tissues as foreign due to differences in major histocompatibility complex (MHC) antigens. This leads to a systemic immune response where the donor cells attack various host organs, including the skin, liver, and gastrointestinal tract, causing the characteristic symptoms of GVHD. This mechanism is distinct from transplant rejection, where the recipient's immune system attacks the transplanted organ.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Kidney) (Incorrect): Kidney transplantation is a solid organ transplant. The primary immune complication is host-versus-graft rejection, where the recipient's immune system attacks the transplanted kidney, not the other way around.\nOption B (Skin) (Incorrect): Skin transplantation (allograft) primarily involves host-versus-graft rejection. Autografts (from the same individual) do not elicit an immune response. GVHD is not a typical complication.\nOption D (Cornea) (Incorrect): The cornea is an immunologically privileged site. While rejection can occur, it is host-versus-graft rejection, and GVHD is not a primary concern.\nOption E (Liver) (Incorrect): Liver transplantation is a solid organ transplant. Like kidney, the main immune complication is host-versus-graft rejection, although the liver is considered somewhat immunologically privileged.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Transplant Type | Primary Immune Complication | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bone Marrow (Allogeneic) | Graft-versus-Host Disease (GVHD) | Donor T-cells attack host tissues |\n| Kidney (Allogeneic) | Host-versus-Graft Rejection | Host immune system attacks donor organ |\n| Liver (Allogeneic) | Host-versus-Graft Rejection | Host immune system attacks donor organ |\n| Cornea (Allogeneic) | Host-versus-Graft Rejection | Host immune system attacks donor tissue (less common due to privilege) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: GVHD = Donor attacks Host. Rejection = Host attacks Donor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor GI GVHD, endoscopy may reveal mucosal edema, erythema, ulceration, or sloughing. CT imaging might show bowel wall thickening and ascites. Liver GVHD can manifest as hepatomegaly or bile duct abnormalities on ultrasound/CT.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Society for Transplantation and Cellular Therapy (ASTCT) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Graft-versus-Host Disease (2020) recommend systemic corticosteroids as first-line therapy for acute GVHD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Kidney | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Skin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bone marrow | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Cornea | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Liver | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Normal bone marrow cells are destroyed readily by drugs and ionizing irradiation; the red blood cell** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
