  "id": 130626,
  "question": "As a result of a motor vehicle crash, a 42-year-old female has a pelvic fracture, confirmed on x-ray of the pelvis. What does she require?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Surgical repair under local anesthesia",
    "B": "Open lavage and, if positive, immediate laparotomy",
    "C": "Immobilization of the pelvis in a plaster cast",
    "D": "Analgesics and observation",
    "E": "Skeletal traction"
  },
  "answer": "B) The patient that has a hemoperitoneum following a pelvic fracture need to be explored immediately. Surgical repair under local anesthesia is not feasible nor is immobilization and a plaster cast. Anelgesics and observation might be possble if the patient were a child and a CAT scan revealed a clinical and a liver injury. Local traction would not be effective in stopping the bleeding.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pelvic fracture + blood = look inside!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"Open lavage and, if positive, immediate laparotomy.\" This patient, a 42-year-old female with a pelvic fracture from a motor vehicle crash, requires immediate investigation for intra-abdominal hemorrhage, which, if present, necessitates surgical exploration to control bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPelvic fractures are often associated with significant hemorrhage, which can be retroperitoneal or, less commonly but critically, intraperitoneal. In a trauma setting, a pelvic fracture should prompt a search for other injuries, especially if the patient is hemodynamically unstable. Diagnostic Peritoneal Lavage (DPL) or a Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (FAST) exam is used to rapidly detect hemoperitoneum. A positive DPL (gross blood or high red blood cell count) or significant free fluid on FAST in a patient with a pelvic fracture and suspected intra-abdominal injury mandates immediate laparotomy to identify and control the source of bleeding, which could be from solid organ injury or mesenteric tears.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Surgical repair under local anesthesia) (Incorrect): Pelvic fractures are complex injuries requiring general anesthesia for surgical stabilization, if indicated, and local anesthesia is wholly inadequate for managing associated hemorrhage or fracture repair.\nOption C (Immobilization of the pelvis in a plaster cast) (Incorrect): A plaster cast is not a standard or effective method for acute pelvic fracture management, especially when internal bleeding is a concern. External fixation or pelvic binders are used for stabilization.\nOption D (Analgesics and observation) (Incorrect): This approach is insufficient and dangerous for a patient with a pelvic fracture and potential intra-abdominal hemorrhage. It delays definitive diagnosis and treatment of life-threatening bleeding.\nOption E (Skeletal traction) (Incorrect): While skeletal traction can be used for specific types of pelvic or lower extremity fractures, it does not address or control internal bleeding, which is the primary concern in this scenario.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Pelvic Fracture Scenario | Initial Management | Definitive Management | Key Concern |\n| :----------------------- | :----------------- | :-------------------- | :---------- |\n| Hemodynamically Stable, no intra-abdominal injury | Pelvic binder, analgesia | Non-operative or surgical fixation (if unstable) | Pain, long-term stability |\n| Hemodynamically Unstable, retroperitoneal bleeding | Pelvic binder, resuscitation, angiography/embolization | Angiography/embolization, external fixation | Hemorrhage control |\n| Hemodynamically Unstable, positive FAST/DPL | Pelvic binder, resuscitation | Immediate laparotomy | Intra-abdominal hemorrhage |\n| Open Pelvic Fracture | Pelvic binder, resuscitation, broad-spectrum antibiotics | Debridement, diversion, external fixation | Infection, hemorrhage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pelvic fracture + instability = rule out intra-abdominal bleed.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn FAST exam, free fluid (anechoic or hypoechoic collection) would be seen in Morison's pouch, splenorenal recess, or cul-de-sac. A positive DPL would yield gross blood. Intraoperatively, laparotomy would reveal the source of bleeding, such as a splenic laceration, liver injury, or mesenteric tear, which would then be addressed surgically.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons Committee on Trauma (ACS COT) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 11th Edition (2022) recommends a systematic approach to trauma patients, including rapid assessment for life-threatening injuries like hemorrhage associated with pelvic fractures, often utilizing FAST or DPL.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Surgical repair under local anesthesia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Open lavage and, if positive, immediate laparotomy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Immobilization of the pelvis in a plaster cast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Analgesics and observation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Skeletal traction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The patient that has a hemoperitoneum following a pelvic fracture need to be explored immediately. S** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
