  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Calf pain + ecchymosis + exertion = muscle tear, not a clot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, a tear of the plantaris muscle. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the clinical presentation of an 18-year-old man experiencing acute, painful, swollen leg with calf tenderness and ecchymosis following strenuous physical exertion like marathon training.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMuscle tears, particularly of the plantaris or gastrocnemius (often termed 'tennis leg'), commonly occur due to sudden eccentric loading or forceful contraction during activities such as running or jumping. The presence of ecchymosis is a key indicator, signifying hemorrhage from torn muscle fibers and associated blood vessels, which is characteristic of a significant muscle strain or tear. The localized calf tenderness further points to the site of muscle injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cellulitis): Incorrect. Cellulitis typically presents with erythema, warmth, and often fever, usually without acute ecchymosis directly resulting from exertion. While a hematoma can become infected, the initial presentation here strongly suggests trauma.\nOption B (DVT): Incorrect. While Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT) causes pain and swelling, ecchymosis is less common, and the acute onset during exertion makes a muscle tear a more likely diagnosis. DVT risk factors are also not mentioned.\nOption C (Superficial thrombophlebitis): Incorrect. This condition involves inflammation of a superficial vein, presenting as a palpable, tender cord along the vein's course, not diffuse calf tenderness with ecchymosis.\nOption E (Medical lemniscus tear): Incorrect. The medial lemniscus is a sensory pathway in the brainstem. The question likely intended 'medial meniscus tear' of the knee. Even then, a meniscus tear presents with knee joint line tenderness, mechanical symptoms, and often a positive McMurray sign, not calf pain and ecchymosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Symptoms | Cause/Mechanism | Differentiating Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Plantaris/Gastrocnemius Tear | Acute calf pain, swelling, ecchymosis, 'pop' sensation | Sudden eccentric load, forceful contraction during exertion | History of exertion, localized calf tenderness, ecchymosis |\n| DVT | Calf pain, swelling, warmth, erythema | Venous stasis, hypercoagulability, endothelial injury | Wells score, absence of acute trauma/ecchymosis |\n| Cellulitis | Erythema, warmth, tenderness, fever, ill-defined borders | Bacterial infection of skin/subcutaneous tissue | Systemic symptoms, skin integrity breach, lack of acute trauma |\n| Medial Meniscus Tear | Knee joint line pain, locking, clicking, giving way, effusion | Twisting injury to the knee | Pain localized to knee joint, positive McMurray, no calf ecchymosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute calf pain with ecchymosis after exertion = muscle tear until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or MRI, a plantaris or gastrocnemius tear would show disruption of muscle fibers, a fluid collection (hematoma), and edema within the affected muscle belly.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Medical Society for Sports Medicine (AMSSM) Position Statement: Muscle Injuries in Athletes (2019) recommends RICE (Rest, Ice, Compression, Elevation) and early mobilization for acute muscle strains.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cellulitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | DVT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Superficial thrombophlebitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Tear of the plantaris muscle | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Medical lemniscus tear | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Plantaris or gastrocnernius tear may occur during physical exertion involving running or walking, ca** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
