  "answer": "D) PTA is technically successful in approximately 90% of iliac lesions with good patency rates. It is more successful for single short stenoses rather than multiple long stenosis or occlusions. The advantages of PTA is that it is less invasive than surgery, has a lower initial cost, has a shorter hospital stay, and lower morbidity, enables an earlier return to full activity, and the procedure can be repeated without an increase in morbidity or a decrease in clinical result. It is particularly useful for patients who are at high operative risks. The ideal procedure would be and angioplasty and stent placement.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When iliacs get tight, stent 'em right!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, PTA and stent placement. For a short-segment, 90% common iliac artery stenosis causing claudication, endovascular intervention is the treatment of choice due to its high success rate and minimally invasive nature.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPercutaneous transluminal angioplasty (PTA) with stent placement is highly effective for short, focal iliac stenoses, boasting a technical success rate of approximately 90% and good patency. Its advantages over open surgical bypass include being less invasive, lower initial cost, shorter hospital stay, reduced morbidity, and quicker return to activity. The procedure is also repeatable without increasing morbidity, making it ideal for patients who might be at higher operative risk for open surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Aortofemoral bypass is a major open surgical procedure reserved for extensive aortoiliac occlusive disease, not a short, focal iliac stenosis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Left-to-right femorofemoral bypass is typically used for unilateral iliac artery occlusion when the contralateral iliac artery is patent, but it is more invasive than PTA for a short stenosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Iliofemoral bypass is an open surgical bypass, which is more invasive than PTA and stent placement for a short, focal lesion.\nOption E (Incorrect): Axillofemoral bypass is an extra-anatomic bypass used for extensive aortoiliac disease, often in high-risk patients unable to tolerate an abdominal incision, and is far too invasive for a short iliac stenosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Treatment of Choice | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Short, focal iliac stenosis | PTA and Stent | Minimally invasive, high success, good patency |\n| Long iliac stenosis or occlusion | Endovascular (complex) or Iliofemoral bypass | More extensive disease requires more robust intervention |\n| Extensive aortoiliac occlusive disease | Aortofemoral bypass | Gold standard for multi-segment disease |\n| Unilateral iliac occlusion (contralateral patent) | Femorofemoral bypass | Revascularizes affected limb using healthy contralateral inflow |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Short iliac stenosis = PTA and stent first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn angiography, a short, tight narrowing (90% stenosis) of the common iliac artery would be clearly visible. During PTA, a guidewire is advanced through the stenosis, followed by a balloon catheter to dilate the vessel, and then a stent is deployed to maintain patency, all visualized fluoroscopically.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Patients With Peripheral Artery Disease. This guideline recommends endovascular therapy (PTA with or without stenting) as the first-line treatment for symptomatic iliac artery lesions, especially for short stenoses (Class I, Level of Evidence A).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aortofemoral bypass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Left-to-right fermorofemoral bypass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Iliofemoral bypass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | PTA and stent placement | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Axillofemoral bypass | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) PTA is technically successful in approximately 90% of iliac lesions with good patency rates. It is m** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
