  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Arms worse than legs? Think central cord!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Central Cord Syndrome. This pattern of motor findings, characterized by greater weakness in the upper extremities than the lower extremities, and often greater distal weakness than proximal, is pathognomonic for a central spinal cord injury, typically in the cervical region.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCentral cord syndrome arises from the somatotopic organization of motor fibers within the corticospinal tracts of the cervical spinal cord. Fibers controlling the upper extremities and more proximal muscles are located more centrally, making them more susceptible to damage from a central injury, such as hyperextension trauma. In contrast, fibers for the lower extremities are more peripheral. Sensory fibers are also more peripherally located, which explains why sensory deficits are often variable, inconsistent, or less severe than motor deficits in this syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Cervical radiculopathy involves compression of a specific nerve root, leading to motor and sensory deficits in a dermatomal/myotomal distribution, not a global upper-greater-than-lower pattern.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cauda equina syndrome affects the lumbar and sacral nerve roots below the conus medullaris, causing lower extremity weakness, saddle anesthesia, and bowel/bladder dysfunction, which is distinct from a cervical cord injury.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lhermitte sign is an electrical sensation down the spine and limbs upon neck flexion, indicating spinal cord dysfunction, but it is a symptom, not a pattern of motor findings or a syndrome itself.\nOption E (Incorrect): Posterior cord syndrome primarily affects the dorsal columns, leading to loss of proprioception and vibratory sensation, with motor weakness being less prominent or absent.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Motor Deficit | Sensory Deficit | Key Feature/Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Central Cord | UE > LE weakness, distal > proximal | Variable, often sacral sparing | Central gray matter/corticospinal tracts (cervical) |\n| Anterior Cord | Bilateral paralysis below lesion | Loss of pain/temp below lesion | Anterior spinal artery occlusion (anterior 2/3 of cord) |\n| Posterior Cord | Minimal motor | Loss of proprioception/vibration below lesion | Dorsal columns |\n| Brown-Séquard | Ipsilateral motor paralysis, ipsilateral proprioception loss | Contralateral pain/temp loss | Hemisection of spinal cord |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Central cord syndrome = 'walking wounded' with weak arms.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a central cord injury typically shows T2 hyperintensity (edema) or hemorrhage within the central gray matter of the cervical spinal cord, often associated with spinal canal stenosis from disc herniation or osteophytes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Neurological Surgeons (AANS) / Congress of Neurological Surgeons (CNS) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Cervical Spine and Spinal Cord Injuries (2019). These guidelines recommend early surgical decompression for patients with acute central cord syndrome and persistent neurological deficits.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Central cord syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Cervical radiculopathy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cauda equina syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lhermitte sign | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Posterior cord syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The central spinal cord syndrome describes the following pattern of weakness: (a) weakness in upper ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
