  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the legs feel like ants and the triceps are weak, think cervical spine.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis is cervical myelopathy. The patient's presentation with upper motor neuron signs (hyperreflexia, increased tone, Babinski's reflex) in both upper (triceps weakness) and lower extremities, along with a sensory level, strongly indicates a spinal cord lesion above the thoracic level.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCervical myelopathy results from chronic compression of the cervical spinal cord, often due to spondylosis or disc herniation. This compression affects the long tracts, specifically the corticospinal tracts for motor function and spinothalamic tracts for sensation, leading to upper motor neuron signs below the level of compression. The presence of triceps weakness (C6-C8 innervation) in conjunction with lower extremity symptoms localizes the lesion to the cervical spine, as the motor pathways for the lower extremities pass through this region.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A thoracic spinal cord compression would not typically cause triceps weakness, as the motor innervation for the triceps originates from the cervical spine (C6-C8). While a sensory level at the nipples (T4) could be consistent, the triceps weakness points to a higher lesion.\nOption B (Incorrect): A thoracic radiculopathy involves nerve roots, presenting with lower motor neuron signs (e.g., flaccid paralysis, hyporeflexia) and dermatomal sensory loss, which contradicts the patient's upper motor neuron findings.\nOption D (Incorrect): A cerebellar tumor would primarily cause ataxia, dysmetria, nystagmus, and other cerebellar signs, not the spasticity, hyperreflexia, and distinct sensory level seen in this patient.\nOption E (Incorrect): An intracranial aneurysm, unless ruptured and causing widespread brain injury, would not typically present with diffuse upper motor neuron signs in all four limbs and a distinct sensory level without cranial nerve involvement or facial symptoms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Upper Motor Neuron Lesion (e.g., Myelopathy) | Lower Motor Neuron Lesion (e.g., Radiculopathy) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Muscle Tone | Increased (Spasticity) | Decreased (Flaccidity) |\n| Deep Tendon Reflexes | Hyperactive | Hypoactive/Absent |\n| Babinski's Sign | Present | Absent |\n| Muscle Atrophy | Mild (disuse) | Severe (denervation) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Triceps weakness + lower extremity UMN signs = cervical myelopathy until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMRI of the cervicothoracic spine would reveal spinal cord compression, often by osteophytes or disc herniation, leading to T2 signal changes (myelomalacia) within the cord at the C6-C7 level.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAOSpine International Guidelines for the Management of Degenerative Cervical Myelopathy (2017). Recommends surgical intervention for most patients with moderate to severe DCM.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A thoracic spinal cord compression | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A thoracic radiculopathy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | A cervical myelopathy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Cerebellar tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Intracranial aneurysm | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) On subsequent MRI of the cervicothoracic spine, this patient is found to have severe spondylosis at ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
