  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Colles' fracture: Dorsal displacement, dinner fork, old lady's wrist.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, stating that the distal radial metaphysis is displaced dorsally. This is the defining characteristic of a Colles' fracture, which is an extra-articular fracture of the distal radius.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA Colles' fracture typically results from a fall on an outstretched hand (FOOSH) with the wrist in extension. This mechanism causes the distal fragment of the radius to be displaced dorsally and often radially, leading to the classic 'dinner fork' deformity. The fracture line is usually transverse, located approximately 2.5 cm proximal to the radiocarpal joint, involving the distal radial metaphysis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A Colles' fracture results from a fall on the flexor (palmar) surface of the wrist, not the dorsum. A fall on the dorsum of the wrist with the wrist in flexion typically causes a Smith's fracture.\nOption B (Incorrect): Most Colles' fractures, especially stable ones, are managed with closed reduction and immobilization. Open reduction and internal fixation (ORIF) is reserved for unstable, irreducible, or significantly displaced fractures.\nOption C (Incorrect): Colles' fractures are most commonly seen in older women, particularly post-menopausal women due to osteoporosis, not younger men.\nOption E (Incorrect): While an associated ulnar styloid fracture is common, the ulnar *shaft* is not typically fractured in a Colles' fracture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Colles' Fracture | Smith's Fracture |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mechanism | Fall on outstretched hand (FOOSH) with wrist in extension | Fall on flexed wrist or direct blow to dorsum |\n| Displacement | Dorsal displacement of distal fragment | Volar (palmar) displacement of distal fragment |\n| Deformity | 'Dinner fork' deformity | 'Garden spade' deformity |\n| Common Population | Older women (osteoporosis) | Younger individuals, less common than Colles' |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Colles' = dorsal displacement, Smith's = volar displacement.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a lateral X-ray, the distal radial fragment will be clearly displaced dorsally and often radially, with dorsal angulation. Radial length may be shortened, and radial inclination decreased. An associated ulnar styloid fracture is frequently observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Distal Radius Fractures (2017). Recommends nonoperative treatment for stable, minimally displaced fractures and operative treatment for unstable or significantly displaced fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The fall occurs on the dorsum of the wrist. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Open reduction is most commonly indicated. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Younger men are generally affected. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The distal radial metaphysis is displaced dorsally. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | The ulnar shaft is fractured proximally. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The distal radial metaphysis is displaced dorsally. This fracture was described by Colles over 150 y** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
