  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A tight cast can drop a foot, always check the fibular head!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the Deep fibula (peroneal) nerve. Foot drop, characterized by the inability to dorsiflex the ankle and extend the toes, is a classic sign of injury to the deep fibula nerve, often due to compression from a tight cast or direct trauma to the fibular head.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe common fibula (peroneal) nerve, a branch of the sciatic nerve, is particularly vulnerable to compression as it courses superficially around the neck of the fibula. It then divides into the superficial and deep fibula nerves. The deep fibula nerve specifically innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg, including the tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus, extensor hallucis longus, and fibularis tertius. These muscles are responsible for ankle dorsiflexion and toe extension. Damage to this nerve directly impairs these functions, leading to the characteristic foot drop observed in the patient.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The posterior tibial nerve innervates the posterior compartment muscles, which are responsible for plantarflexion and toe flexion, not dorsiflexion.\nOption B (Incorrect): The saphenous nerve is a purely sensory nerve, providing sensation to the medial aspect of the leg and foot, with no motor function.\nOption C (Incorrect): The femoral nerve innervates the anterior thigh muscles (quadriceps) for knee extension and hip flexion, not the muscles of the lower leg responsible for ankle movement.\nOption E (Incorrect): The nerve to the soleus muscle is a branch of the tibial nerve and supplies the soleus, which is a powerful plantarflexor, not a dorsiflexor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Compartment | Primary Motor Function | Clinical Sign of Injury |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Deep Fibula (Peroneal) | Anterior Leg | Ankle Dorsiflexion, Toe Extension | Foot Drop |\n| Superficial Fibula (Peroneal) | Lateral Leg | Ankle Eversion | Impaired Eversion, Sensory Loss Lateral Leg |\n| Tibial | Posterior Leg | Ankle Plantarflexion, Toe Flexion | Calcaneal Gait, Impaired Plantarflexion |\n| Femoral | Anterior Thigh | Knee Extension, Hip Flexion | Quadriceps Weakness, Difficulty Climbing Stairs |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Foot drop = common fibula (peroneal) nerve injury until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, nerve edema or discontinuity might be seen at the fibular head. Intraoperatively, the common fibula nerve would be explored at the fibular neck for signs of compression or transection, and neurolysis or decompression may be performed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Tibial Shaft Fractures (2019) recommends careful neurovascular assessment and monitoring for nerve injury, especially with cast application.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Posterior tibial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Saphenous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Femoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Deep fibula (peroneal) nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Nerve to the soleus muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The common fibula (peroneal) nerve divides into the superficial fibula (peroneal) nerve, which suppl** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
