  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When gastric varices are isolated, think spleen, not liver!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Splenectomy. This procedure is indicated for gastric varices that arise from splenic vein thrombosis, a condition often associated with pancreatitis or malignancy, leading to isolated gastric varices.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenic vein thrombosis (SVT) causes increased pressure specifically in the short gastric veins, which drain into the splenic vein. This localized elevation in pressure leads to the formation of gastric varices, typically in the fundus, without generalized portal hypertension. Unlike varices caused by cirrhosis, these 'isolated' gastric varices are effectively treated by splenectomy. Removing the spleen eliminates the high-pressure splenic circulation, thereby decompressing the short gastric veins and resolving the varices, preventing further bleeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Total gastrectomy) (Incorrect): This is an overly aggressive and inappropriate procedure for gastric varices, as it does not address the underlying portal hypertension or splenic vein pathology.\nOption C (Portal vein ligation) (Incorrect): Ligation of the portal vein would exacerbate portal hypertension, leading to catastrophic consequences and is never indicated for variceal bleeding.\nOption D (Hepatic vein ligation) (Incorrect): Ligation of the hepatic veins would cause severe liver congestion and failure, and is irrelevant to the management of gastric varices.\nOption E (Placement of an emergency portacaval shunt) (Incorrect): While shunts are used for portal hypertension, an emergency portacaval shunt is a major procedure for generalized portal hypertension, not isolated gastric varices from splenic vein thrombosis. Furthermore, emergency shunts are rarely performed today, with TIPS or endoscopic therapies preferred.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Generalized Gastric Varices (e.g., cirrhosis) | Isolated Gastric Varices (e.g., SVT) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Portal hypertension (cirrhosis, portal vein thrombosis) | Splenic vein thrombosis (pancreatitis, malignancy) |\n| Location | Often fundus, but can be widespread | Typically fundus (gastric fundal varices) |\n| Treatment | TIPS, BRTO, endoscopic therapy (glue injection), shunt surgery | Splenectomy |\n| Liver Function | Often impaired | Usually normal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Isolated gastric varices? Think splenic vein thrombosis, treat with splenectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, splenic vein thrombosis would be evident, often with collateral vessels and dilated gastric varices. Intraoperatively, a large, congested spleen and prominent, dilated short gastric veins draining into the splenic hilum would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBaveno VII Consensus Report (2021): While primarily focused on cirrhotic portal hypertension, it emphasizes the importance of identifying and treating non-cirrhotic causes of portal hypertension and varices, implicitly supporting specific interventions like splenectomy for splenic vein thrombosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Splenectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Portal vein ligation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hepatic vein ligation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Placement of an emergency portacaval shunt | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The most common causes of gastric varices in patients with splenic vein thrombosis occur following p** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
