  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it bleeds from the nipple, papilloma's the culprit, but cancer's the fear!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Intraductal papilloma. This is the most common benign cause of bloody nipple discharge, accounting for approximately 45% of cases, making it the most likely diagnosis in this clinical scenario.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraductal papillomas are benign epithelial proliferations within the lactiferous ducts, typically near the nipple. Their friable nature and location within the duct system lead to bleeding, which manifests as a spontaneous, often unilateral, bloody nipple discharge. While malignancy must always be excluded, papillomas are statistically the most frequent etiology for this specific symptom.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fibrocystic breast disease is characterized by breast pain, tenderness, and lumpiness, but it is not typically associated with bloody nipple discharge.\nOption C (Incorrect): A pituitary tumor (prolactinoma) can cause nipple discharge, but it is usually bilateral, milky, or clear, due to elevated prolactin levels, not bloody.\nOption D (Incorrect): Invasive ductal carcinoma is a serious concern and must be ruled out, but it accounts for a smaller percentage (around 10%) of bloody nipple discharge cases compared to intraductal papilloma, making it less likely as the most common cause.\nOption E (Incorrect): Lobular carcinoma is a type of breast cancer, but it is less commonly associated with nipple discharge, especially bloody discharge, and is not the most likely cause.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Discharge | Common Characteristics | Most Likely Causes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bloody | Unilateral, spontaneous | Intraductal papilloma, Ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS), Invasive ductal carcinoma |\n| Milky/Clear | Bilateral, spontaneous | Prolactinoma, Medications, Pregnancy/Lactation |\n| Purulent | Unilateral, associated with inflammation | Abscess, Mastitis |\n| Serous/Serosanguinous | Unilateral, spontaneous | Intraductal papilloma, DCIS, Fibrocystic changes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bloody nipple discharge = think papilloma first, but always rule out cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, papillomas may be occult or appear as a small mass or calcifications. Ultrasound may show an intraductal mass or ductal ectasia. Ductography (galactography) is often diagnostic, revealing a filling defect within a dilated duct. In the OR, microdochectomy or duct excision would reveal the papilloma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023). These guidelines emphasize thorough evaluation of nipple discharge, including imaging and biopsy, to differentiate benign from malignant causes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fibrocystic breast disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Intraductal papilloma | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Pituitary tumor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Invasive ductal carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Lobular carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Secretions drain from the nipple by multiple openings. The most common cause of a bloody nipple disc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
