  "answer": "B) Glioblastoma multiforme is a highly malig-nant neoplasm, arising from glial cells or their precursors within the CNS. It is the most common of all primary malignancies of the CNS and its peak incidence is within the fifth to sev-enth decade of life. Alow-grade astrocytoma is a tumor derived from glial cells of astrocytes. Fig. 11–4, shows a large cystic giant astrocytoma on T2 weighted MRI where fluid is shown as a white area with midline shift (not glioblastoma multiforme presented in this question).",
