  "question": "A4-year-old boy is brought to the emergency depart-ment with the complaint of approximately 2 weeks of headache and vomiting. He was seen in the emer-gency department 1 week earlier with the same com-plaints. At that time, his parents were told that the probable cause was a gastrointestinal virus, and the boy was sent home. His symptoms have not improved. On general examination, the child appears somewhat dehydrated and has a dry mouth and sunken eyes. His examination findings are also remarkable for the presence of bilateral papilledema and marked nystagmus. An MRI with intravenous contrast is obtained that reveals the presence of a 2-cm mass in the posterior fossa. The mass is entirely within the fourth ventricle and appears to be arising from the vermis of the cerebellum. It enhances uni-formly with contrast. The lateral and third ventricles are moderately dilated with hydrocephalus. What is the most likely diagnosis?",
