  "question": "Following a sudden impact in an accident, the 34-year-old race car driver becomes uncon-scious and is admitted to the hospital. A CT scan is performed, and a right space-occupying lesion is noted (Fig. 11–1). What is the most likely diagnosis?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Corpus callosum injury",
    "B": "Pituitary apoplexia",
    "C": "Acute subdural hematoma",
    "D": "Acute epidural hematoma",
    "E": "Chronic subdural hematoma"
  },
  "answer": "C) Acute subdural hematomas (Fig. 11–1) occur most commonly when violent accelera-tions or deceleration injuries of the head cause tearing of the bridging veins within the sub-dural potential space. They generally imply a much more severe injury to the brain itself than in the case of their epidural counterpart. For this reason, they are associated with cerebral contusions in over 30% of cases.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bridging veins tear, brain's in fear; subdural's here, prognosis unclear!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Acute subdural hematoma. This diagnosis aligns with the clinical presentation of a sudden impact causing unconsciousness and a space-occupying lesion, as acute subdural hematomas are a common and severe consequence of traumatic acceleration-deceleration injuries.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute subdural hematomas (ASH) result from the tearing of bridging veins that traverse the subdural space, connecting the cerebral cortex to the dural venous sinuses. These injuries are typically caused by high-energy trauma, leading to rapid accumulation of blood. ASH often signifies a more severe underlying brain injury, such as cerebral contusions or diffuse axonal injury, compared to epidural hematomas, contributing to a higher morbidity and mortality rate. The rapid onset of symptoms and the presence of a space-occupying lesion on CT are classic indicators.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Corpus callosum injury is a form of diffuse axonal injury (DAI), which is a microscopic injury and not typically seen as a focal 'space-occupying lesion' on initial CT scans in the way a hematoma is.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pituitary apoplexia is a spontaneous hemorrhage or infarction of the pituitary gland, unrelated to acute trauma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Acute epidural hematoma is also traumatic but typically results from arterial tears (e.g., middle meningeal artery) and often presents with a 'lucid interval.' While a space-occupying lesion, the clinical context and the implication of a more severe underlying brain injury often point to subdural.\nOption E (Incorrect): Chronic subdural hematoma develops slowly over weeks to months, often in elderly or alcoholic patients, and would not present acutely following a sudden impact.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Subdural Hematoma | Acute Epidural Hematoma | Chronic Subdural Hematoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Mechanism** | Tearing of bridging veins | Tearing of meningeal arteries (e.g., middle) | Tearing of bridging veins (slow leak) |\n| **Trauma** | High-velocity acceleration/deceleration | Direct impact, often focal | Minor trauma, often in elderly/atrophic brain |\n| **CT Appearance** | Crescent-shaped, conforms to brain surface | Lenticular (biconvex), does not cross sutures | Hypodense/isodense, crescent-shaped |\n| **Lucid Interval** | Rare | Common (in 20-50%) | Absent |\n| **Prognosis** | Often poor, associated with severe brain injury | Better if treated promptly, less underlying brain injury | Variable, can be insidious |\n| **Location** | Between dura and arachnoid | Between dura and skull | Between dura and arachnoid |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Crescent-shaped hematoma = Subdural. Lenticular = Epidural.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an acute subdural hematoma appears as a hyperdense (bright white) crescent-shaped collection of blood that conforms to the contour of the brain surface and can cross suture lines, but typically does not cross the falx or tentorium.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBrain Trauma Foundation (BTF) Guidelines for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury (4th Edition, 2016). These guidelines provide evidence-based recommendations for the diagnosis and management of intracranial hematomas, including acute subdural hematomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Corpus callosum injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pituitary apoplexia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Acute subdural hematoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Acute epidural hematoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Chronic subdural hematoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Acute subdural hematomas (Fig. 11–1) occur most commonly when violent accelera-tions or deceleration** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
