  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Meningiomas are brain's good guys; they rarely bleed, and when they do, it's not SAH!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D, Hemorrhagic meningioma, is the least likely cause of subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH) in this patient. Meningiomas rarely bleed, and when they do, the hemorrhage is typically intratumoral or intraparenchymal, not into the subarachnoid space.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSpontaneous SAH is most commonly caused by ruptured berry aneurysms, often located on the Circle of Willis, directly within the subarachnoid space. Arteriovenous malformations (AVMs) are another frequent cause, typically bleeding intraparenchymally but often superficially enough to present with associated SAH. In a a patient with sickle cell disease, sickle cell angiopathy is a recognized cause of SAH from subpial vessels. Meningiomas, however, are typically benign tumors that are not prone to hemorrhage, and their rare bleeding events are usually confined within the tumor or brain parenchyma, making them an unlikely source of isolated SAH.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Aneurysmal bleed is the most common cause of spontaneous SAH, making it a highly likely etiology.\nOption B (Incorrect): Sickle cell angiopathy is a known cause of SAH, especially relevant in a patient with a history of sickle cell disease.\nOption C (Incorrect): Arteriovenous malformation (AVM) is a common cause of SAH, often presenting with superficial bleeding that extends into the subarachnoid space.\nOption E (Incorrect): Blood dyscrasias can predispose to bleeding anywhere in the body, including the subarachnoid space, making it a plausible cause of SAH.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of SAH | Typical Bleeding Pattern | Relevance to SAH |\n| :----------- | :----------------------- | :--------------- |\n| Aneurysm     | Subarachnoid             | Most common cause |\n| AVM          | Intraparenchymal, often with SAH | Common cause |\n| Sickle Cell Angiopathy | Subarachnoid (subpial vessels) | Relevant in SCD patients |\n| Meningioma   | Intratumoral/Intraparenchymal | Extremely rare cause of SAH |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When SAH is confirmed, think aneurysm or AVM first, not tumor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT scan in SAH typically shows high-attenuation blood within the basal cisterns, Sylvian fissures, and cerebral sulci. The absence of intraparenchymal abnormality on CT helps narrow the differential, making causes like pure intraparenchymal hemorrhage less likely, but doesn't rule out AVMs that bleed superficially.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAHA/ASA Guidelines for the Management of Patients With Aneurysmal Subarachnoid Hemorrhage (2012): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis and management of SAH, emphasizing early imaging and identification of the source.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aneurysmal bleed | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sickle cell angiopathy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Arteriovenous malformation (AVM) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hemorrhagic meningioma | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Blood dyscrasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The most common cause of the spontaneous SAH is berry aneurysm and AVM. Aneurysms are often located ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
