  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the bleed looks bigger than its age, think tumor.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Hemorrhagic neoplasm. This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the subacute presentation (3-month headache, cognitive decline, sudden hemiparesis) and, critically, the CT finding of a 3-cm irregular hemorrhage surrounded by marked edema and mass effect disproportionate to the size of the hemorrhage. This disproportionate edema points to a pre-existing lesion that has recently bled.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemorrhagic neoplasms, such as glioblastomas or metastatic tumors, often present with a subacute history of neurological symptoms and can bleed spontaneously. The key differentiating factor on imaging is the presence of significant vasogenic edema and mass effect that appears out of proportion to the acute hemorrhage itself. This edema is often chronic, developing around the tumor prior to the bleed, or rapidly exacerbated by the hemorrhage within a pre-existing pathological tissue. In contrast, primary intracerebral hemorrhages (e.g., hypertensive or amyloid) typically cause edema that develops over several hours to days and is generally more proportional to the hematoma volume.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Amyloid angiopathy) (Incorrect): While common in the elderly and a cause of lobar hemorrhage, it typically presents with acute hemorrhage and the edema is usually proportional to the bleed, not disproportionately marked as seen here.\nOption B (Hypertensive hemorrhage) (Incorrect): This usually presents acutely, often in deep brain structures (basal ganglia, pons, cerebellum), and the edema develops over hours and is generally proportional to the hematoma size. The subacute history and disproportionate edema make this less likely.\nOption D (Arterial-venous malformation) (Incorrect): AVMs can cause acute hemorrhage, but typically do not present with a 3-month history of headache and disproportionate edema/mass effect unless there's a chronic, underlying lesion with recent bleed, which is less characteristic than a neoplasm in this context.\nOption E (Coagulopathy) (Incorrect): Coagulopathies cause acute hemorrhage, often multifocal, but do not typically present with a 3-month history of headache or disproportionate edema and mass effect around a single lesion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Hemorrhagic Neoplasm                               | Hypertensive Hemorrhage                               | Amyloid Angiopathy                                  |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Presentation**    | Subacute (headache, progressive deficits), then acute bleed | Acute onset, often severe headache, focal deficits    | Acute onset, often lobar hemorrhage, focal deficits |\n| **Location**        | Any, often lobar (frontal-temporal in this case)   | Deep structures (basal ganglia, thalamus, pons, cerebellum) | Lobar (cortical-subcortical)                        |\n| **Edema/Mass Effect** | Marked, disproportionate to hemorrhage size        | Proportional to hemorrhage size, develops over hours  | Proportional to hemorrhage size, develops over hours |\n| **Underlying Cause**| Tumor (primary or metastatic)                      | Chronic hypertension                                  | Cerebral amyloid deposition                         |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Disproportionate edema with ICH = suspect underlying lesion, especially neoplasm.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a hemorrhagic neoplasm will show an irregular intraparenchymal hematoma often with surrounding low-density vasogenic edema that extends far beyond the hematoma itself, indicating a chronic process or significant mass effect. The hemorrhage may appear heterogeneous due to different ages of bleeding. Intraoperatively, one might encounter friable, vascular tumor tissue mixed with clotted blood.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Heart Association/American Stroke Association (AHA/ASA) Guidelines for the Management of Spontaneous Intracerebral Hemorrhage (2022). These guidelines discuss the differential diagnosis of ICH and the importance of identifying underlying structural lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Amyloid angiopathy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypertensive hemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hemorrhagic neoplasm | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Arterial-venous malformation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Coagulopathy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) History of recent onset of headache in adult should always raise the suspicion of neoplasm. Amyloid ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
