  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, ultrasound it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. This patient's presentation of projectile vomiting in a 7-week-old girl, despite stable weight and avid sucking, is highly suspicious for hypertrophic pyloric stenosis, necessitating an abdominal ultrasound for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypertrophic pyloric stenosis (HPS) is a a common cause of gastric outlet obstruction in infants, typically presenting with non-bilious projectile vomiting. While classically described in 4-week-old male infants with a palpable 'olive' mass, this case highlights that HPS can occur in females and at slightly older ages, and the mass is often not palpable due to its location or overlying structures. Ultrasound is the gold standard for diagnosis, providing objective measurements of pyloric wall thickness (>3 mm) and channel length (>16 mm), which are crucial for confirming the diagnosis and guiding management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Immediate surgical pyloromyotomy is premature. The diagnosis must first be confirmed by imaging, and any electrolyte abnormalities or dehydration must be corrected before surgery to ensure patient safety.\nOption B (Incorrect): Laboratory testing, specifically electrolyte assessment, is critical. Prolonged vomiting can lead to hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis and dehydration, which must be corrected prior to anesthesia and surgery.\nOption D (Incorrect): Trying a new formula is inappropriate for a suspected surgical condition like pyloric stenosis. This would delay definitive diagnosis and treatment, potentially worsening the infant's condition.\nOption E (Incorrect): The absence of a palpable 'olive' does not rule out pyloric stenosis. The hypertrophied pylorus is only palpable in about 50% of cases, often obscured by the liver or a distended stomach, making imaging essential for diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pyloric Stenosis | GERD | Malrotation with Volvulus |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Vomiting** | Projectile, non-bilious | Regurgitation, non-projectile, non-bilious | Bilious, sudden onset, often projectile |\n| **Timing** | 3-6 weeks, progressive | Infancy, often after feeds | Any age, often first month |\n| **Feeding** | Avid feeder, hungry after vomiting | May refuse feeds, irritable | May refuse feeds, signs of distress |\n| **Abdomen** | Soft, visible peristalsis, +/- olive | Soft, non-tender | Distended, tender, signs of peritonitis |\n| **Diagnosis** | Ultrasound (wall >3mm, length >16mm) | Clinical, pH probe, UGI series | Upper GI series (ligament of Treitz) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Projectile vomiting in an infant = rule out pyloric stenosis with ultrasound, even without a palpable olive.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn abdominal ultrasound, hypertrophic pyloric stenosis is characterized by a thickened pyloric muscle wall (>3 mm), an elongated pyloric channel (>16 mm), and an overall pyloric diameter (>14 mm). The pylorus appears as a 'target sign' in transverse view and a 'cervix sign' in longitudinal view.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Report 'Diagnosis and Management of Pyloric Stenosis' (2017) recommends abdominal ultrasound as the primary diagnostic modality and emphasizes electrolyte correction prior to surgical pyloromyotomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Should lead to immediate surgical pyloromyotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Should not require any laboratory testing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Should prompt an order for an abdominal ultrasound | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Should not be entertained until she has been tried on a new formula | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Would be unlikely in the absence of an “olive” | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Although pyloric stenosis is typically seen in 4-week-old male infants, it can certainly be seen in ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
