  "answer": "D) The spleen is the most common solid organ injured by blunt trauma. Though gastric rupture could cause the clinical presentation described, it is very rare. Rib fracture in the midtorso alone generally does not cause the referred shoulder pain, because blood does not collect under the left diaphragm, as seen in splenic injuries.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the left shoulder aches after a left-sided hit, think spleen, not just a sprain!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is splenic injury. This is the most likely diagnosis given the mechanism of blunt trauma to the left midtorso, presenting with left lower chest/upper abdominal pain, and crucially, referred left shoulder pain (Kehr's sign), which is highly suggestive of diaphragmatic irritation from splenic hemorrhage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe spleen is the most frequently injured solid organ in blunt abdominal trauma due to its friability and relatively unprotected location in the left upper quadrant. The referred left shoulder pain, known as Kehr's sign, is a classic indicator of diaphragmatic irritation, typically caused by blood accumulating under the left hemidiaphragm from a splenic rupture. This pain is mediated by the phrenic nerve, which shares nerve roots (C3-C5) with the supraclavicular nerves supplying the shoulder.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Rib fractures can cause localized pain but do not typically cause referred left shoulder pain unless there's an underlying organ injury causing diaphragmatic irritation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Liver injury is the most common solid organ injury in blunt trauma, but it is located in the right upper quadrant and would typically cause right-sided pain, not left shoulder pain.\nOption C (Incorrect): Ruptured diaphragm is possible with significant blunt trauma but is less common than splenic injury. While it can cause shoulder pain, it's usually due to associated hemorrhage or organ herniation, not the diaphragm rupture itself causing the classic Kehr's sign.\nOption E (Incorrect): Ruptured stomach is exceedingly rare in blunt abdominal trauma due to its protected location and elasticity, making it a highly unlikely primary diagnosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organ Injured | Typical Location of Pain | Classic Associated Sign | Imaging Finding |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Spleen | Left upper quadrant, left flank, left shoulder | Kehr's sign (left shoulder pain) | Perisplenic fluid, splenic laceration/hematoma |\n| Liver | Right upper quadrant, right flank, right shoulder | Right shoulder pain (less common than Kehr's) | Perihepatic fluid, hepatic laceration/hematoma |\n| Kidney | Flank, back | Hematuria | Perinephric fluid, renal laceration/hematoma |\n| Pancreas | Epigastric, back | Elevated amylase/lipase | Peripancreatic fluid, pancreatic transection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Left shoulder pain after left upper quadrant trauma = splenic injury until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, a splenic injury would typically appear as a perisplenic hematoma, intraparenchymal lacerations, subcapsular hematoma, or active extravasation of contrast. Free fluid (blood) in the abdomen, particularly around the spleen, would also be evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 11th Edition (2022). ATLS emphasizes rapid assessment and management of blunt abdominal trauma, including focused assessment with sonography for trauma (FAST) and CT imaging for hemodynamically stable patients to identify solid organ injuries like splenic rupture.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rib fractures | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Liver injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ruptured diaphragm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Splenic injury | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Ruptured stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The spleen is the most common solid organ injured by blunt trauma. Though gastric rupture could caus** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
