  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Save the spleen, stop the bleed, stay out of the OR.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Despite a Grade III splenic injury with an arterial blush, the patient remains hemodynamically stable. In this scenario, the priority is splenic preservation, and angioembolization is the most appropriate intervention to control active bleeding while avoiding operative intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenic preservation is crucial in pediatric trauma to prevent the long-term risks of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI). An arterial \"blush\" on CT signifies active extravasation of contrast, indicating ongoing hemorrhage. In a hemodynamically stable patient, selective angioembolization of the bleeding vessel allows for definitive control of hemorrhage without sacrificing the spleen. This approach minimizes morbidity, preserves vital immune function, and is a cornerstone of modern non-operative management for splenic trauma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Immediate exploration is reserved for hemodynamically unstable patients or those with other clear surgical indications (e.g., peritonitis, hollow viscus injury). This patient is stable.\nOption C (Incorrect): Aggressive fluid resuscitation is for hemodynamic instability, which this patient does not have. A liver-spleen scan is not the appropriate next step for an active blush.\nOption D (Incorrect): Monitoring only is insufficient given the presence of an arterial \"blush,\" which indicates active bleeding and requires intervention to prevent potential instability.\nOption E (Incorrect): Elective splenectomy is not indicated in this trauma setting. Pneumovax is given if splenectomy is performed or significant splenic tissue is lost, not as a primary treatment for a stable splenic injury.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Management | Rationale |\n| :---------------- | :--------- | :-------- |\n| Hemodynamically Unstable | Immediate Laparotomy/Splenectomy | Life-threatening hemorrhage requires surgical control. |\n| Stable with Arterial Blush | Angioembolization | Control active bleeding, preserve spleen, avoid surgery. |\n| Stable without Blush (High Grade) | Non-operative Management (NOM) with close monitoring | Most high-grade injuries can heal without surgery in stable patients. |\n| Stable with Low Grade Injury | Non-operative Management (NOM) with close monitoring | Standard of care for most blunt splenic injuries. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stable splenic blush = angioembolization, preserve the spleen.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a contrast-enhanced CT scan, an arterial \"blush\" appears as a focal, high-attenuation collection of contrast material within the splenic parenchyma during the arterial phase, which may persist or enlarge on delayed images, indicating active extravasation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) guidelines for splenic injury management (e.g., AAST Organ Injury Scale and associated management protocols) recommend non-operative management, including angioembolization, for hemodynamically stable patients with splenic injuries, even high-grade ones or those with active extravasation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Continuous hemodynamic monitoring, celiac angiogram, and angio embolisation | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Immediate exploration in the operation room | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | If hemodynamic instability develops, aggressive fluid resuscitation includi | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Monitoring only | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Pneumovax and elective splenectomy in 6 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) While all blunt abdominal trauma patients developing hemodynamic instability should go to the operat** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
