  "id": 130816,
  "question": "A20-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a stab wound to the neck above the angle of the mandible. The patient’s blood pressure is 110/80 mm Hg, pulse rate is 100 bpm, and respiration rate is 24 breaths per minute. Between initial presentation and insertion of intravenous lines, the hematoma in the upper neck enlarges significantly. What should be the next step in the patient’s management?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Barium swallow",
    "B": "Flexible endoscopy",
    "C": "Operative exploration",
    "D": "Doppler ultrasound",
    "E": "Angiography"
  },
  "answer": "C) In considering management of neck wounds, three zones are described. Zone III refers to the area above and posterior to the angle of the mandible (see Fig. 12–4). Angiographic definition of the site and extent of arterial injury is important because of the difficulty in exposure of internal carotid injuries near the base of the skull. Such injuries may require the use of extracranial–intracranial arterial bypass.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the neck swells, the OR calls!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is operative exploration. An enlarging hematoma in the neck is a hard sign of active hemorrhage and impending airway compromise, demanding immediate surgical intervention regardless of the specific neck zone.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn enlarging hematoma signifies active, uncontrolled bleeding, which is a life-threatening condition. While Zone III injuries (above the angle of the mandible) are notoriously difficult to expose surgically and often benefit from preoperative angiography in stable patients, the presence of a rapidly expanding hematoma overrides any diagnostic delay. This clinical finding indicates the need for immediate surgical control of the bleeding vessel and potential airway protection, as delaying for imaging could lead to exsanguination or airway obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Barium swallow): Incorrect. This study is used to evaluate esophageal injury, which is not the primary concern with an enlarging hematoma indicating active vascular bleeding.\nOption B (Flexible endoscopy): Incorrect. This is used to evaluate pharyngeal or laryngeal injury, not the immediate priority for an enlarging hematoma.\nOption D (Doppler ultrasound): Incorrect. While useful for initial screening, it is not definitive for major arterial injury in the neck, especially in Zone III, and would delay definitive management in the face of active bleeding.\nOption E (Angiography): Incorrect. Although angiography is often indicated for stable Zone III injuries to define vascular damage, an *enlarging hematoma* is a \"hard sign\" of active bleeding that mandates immediate operative exploration, not a diagnostic delay.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Neck Zone | Location | Common Injuries | Management Approach (Stable Patient) |\n| :-------- | :------- | :-------------- | :----------------------------------- |\n| Zone I    | Clavicles to cricoid | Great vessels, lung apex, trachea, esophagus | Angiography, bronchoscopy, esophagoscopy |\n| Zone II   | Cricoid to angle of mandible | Carotid/vertebral arteries, jugular veins, trachea, esophagus, larynx, pharynx | Selective non-operative with imaging (CT Angio, endoscopy) |\n| Zone III  | Above angle of mandible to skull base | Carotid/vertebral arteries, cranial nerves, salivary glands | Angiography, selective operative exploration (difficult access) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Enlarging neck hematoma = immediate OR.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, after incision, one would encounter a large, pulsatile hematoma obscuring vital structures, requiring careful dissection and proximal/distal control of the injured vessel (e.g., internal carotid artery) near the skull base.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons Committee on Trauma (ACS COT) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018) recommends immediate operative exploration for hard signs of vascular injury in penetrating neck trauma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Barium swallow | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Flexible endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Operative exploration | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Doppler ultrasound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Angiography | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) In considering management of neck wounds, three zones are described. Zone III refers to the area abo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
