  "id": 130820,
  "question": "A26-year-old man is brought to the emergency department with a stab wound to the right side of the back just medial to the posterioraxillary line. His blood pressure is 120/80 mm Hg, pulse rate is 98 bpm, and respiration rate is 22 breaths per minute. Physical examination reveals no abdominal tenderness, guarding, or neurologic changes. Local exploration of the stab wound is performed using local anesthesia. The track to the wound ends in the paraspinal muscles. What would be the next step in management?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Admit the patient for 24 hours of observation.",
    "B": "Perform peritoneal lavage.",
    "C": "Perform CT scan with rectal and intravenous contrast.",
    "D": "Discharge to outpatient clinic for follow-up monitoring.",
    "E": "Perform ultrasound."
  },
  "answer": "D) Apatient with definitive negative findings on wound exploration can be discharged from the hospital for outpatient follow-up care. It is sometimes difficult to determine the depth of a stab wound to the back because of the thickness of the paraspinal muscles. Some authors have found that nearly 20% of patients with such injuries have negative findings on exploration. Such patients can be discharged. Deeper stab wounds to the back may injure peritoneal structures without penetration of the peritoneal cavity. Thus, peritoneal lavage is less useful than a CT scan with intravenous, oral, and (particularly) rectal contrast to rule out retroperitoneal colon injuries.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Superficial stab, no deep dive, patient can thrive!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT because the local wound exploration definitively ruled out deep penetration beyond the paraspinal muscles. This finding indicates no injury to vital thoracic or abdominal structures, making further intervention or observation unnecessary.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLocal wound exploration is a crucial diagnostic tool for penetrating trauma, especially in areas with thick muscle layers like the back. When the wound track is definitively found to end superficially within the paraspinal muscles, it provides high confidence that the pleura, peritoneum, or retroperitoneal organs have not been violated. This allows for safe discharge, preventing unnecessary hospital admissions, costly investigations, and potential iatrogenic complications, while ensuring appropriate patient care based on objective findings.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Admitting for 24 hours of observation is unnecessary when local wound exploration definitively rules out deep penetration. Observation is for equivocal findings or when depth cannot be fully assessed.\nOption B (Incorrect): Peritoneal lavage is primarily for detecting peritoneal penetration and intra-abdominal hemorrhage. Given the wound ends in the paraspinal muscles, peritoneal penetration is highly unlikely, and lavage is less sensitive for retroperitoneal injuries.\nOption C (Incorrect): A CT scan with contrast is indicated for deeper stab wounds to the back where retroperitoneal injury is suspected or when wound exploration is inconclusive. It is an over-investigation for a definitively superficial wound.\nOption E (Incorrect): Ultrasound has limited utility in evaluating the depth of stab wounds through muscle and is not the primary diagnostic tool for assessing retroperitoneal organ injury in this context.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Scenario | Management | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Superficial stab wound (negative wound exploration) | Discharge with outpatient follow-up | No deep penetration, low risk of complications. |\n| Deep stab wound (potential peritoneal penetration) | Diagnostic peritoneal lavage (DPL) or laparoscopy | Rule out intra-abdominal injury. |\n| Deep stab wound to flank/back (potential retroperitoneal injury) | CT scan with triple contrast | Evaluate for retroperitoneal organ injury (e.g., colon, kidney). |\n| Hemodynamically unstable patient with penetrating trauma | Immediate surgical exploration | Control hemorrhage, repair injuries. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Negative wound exploration for back stab wounds means discharge.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn local wound exploration, the track would be visualized ending blindly within the muscle fascia, without breaching the deeper fascial layers or entering the thoracic/abdominal cavity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018) recommends local wound exploration for selected penetrating torso injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Admit the patient for 24 hours of observation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Perform peritoneal lavage. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Perform CT scan with rectal and intravenous contrast. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Discharge to outpatient clinic for follow-up monitoring. | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Perform ultrasound. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Apatient with definitive negative findings on wound exploration can be discharged from the hospital ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
