  "id": 130828,
  "question": "A 25-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a gunshot wound to the abdomen. On exploratory laparotomy, he is found to have multiple small-bowel enterotomies, transverse colon enterotomy, and a partial injury just to the left of the midline of the pancreas. The pancreatic duct appears intact. What is the appropriate management of the pancreatic injury?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Closed-suction drainage and lavage",
    "B": "Drain with sump drains",
    "C": "Distal pancreatectomy",
    "D": "Operative pancreatogram followed by distal pancreatectomy if ductal injury is noted",
    "E": "Transection of injured area of pancreas with Roux-en-Y (jejunal) anastomosis to the transected tail of the pancreas"
  },
  "answer": "A) Routinely performing distal pancreatectomy for all penetrating injuries to the body or tail of the pancreas significantly prolongs the operative time and contributes to additional hemorrhage and possible hypothermia. Approximately 25% of patients undergoing distal pancreatectomy develop an intra-abdominal abscess. Distal pancreatectomy is the procedure of choice if there is an obvious disruption of the pancreatic duct in the body or tail. Closed-suction drainage is preferred to suction drainage because of the lower incidence of abscess formation with closed-suction drainage. If there is an injury to the duodenum, a pancreaticogram can be performed through the injury site; however, a normal duodenum should not be opened to secure an intra-operative pancreaticogram.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the pancreatic duct is intact, drain it, don't dissect it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, closed-suction drainage. This approach is appropriate because the patient has a partial pancreatic injury with an intact pancreatic duct, which is the critical factor guiding conservative management. Unnecessary pancreatic resection carries significant morbidity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic injuries are graded, and an intact duct in a partial injury (likely AAST Grade I or II) allows for non-resectional management. The primary goal is to control potential leaks and prevent complications like pseudocyst or fistula formation, which closed-suction drainage effectively addresses. This conservative approach avoids the significant morbidity associated with pancreatectomy, such as hemorrhage, prolonged operative time, and a higher risk of intra-abdominal abscess, especially when the duct is not disrupted. Closed-suction drainage is preferred over sump drains due to a lower incidence of abscess formation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Sump drains are generally less effective and associated with a higher risk of infection and abscess formation compared to closed-suction drains for pancreatic injuries.\nOption C (Incorrect): Distal pancreatectomy is an aggressive procedure reserved for significant ductal disruption in the body or tail, which is not present here as the duct is intact.\nOption D (Incorrect): An operative pancreatogram is not indicated when the duct appears intact, and performing a distal pancreatectomy without confirmed ductal injury is inappropriate and overly aggressive.\nOption E (Incorrect): Transection with Roux-en-Y anastomosis is a complex reconstructive procedure for severe ductal injuries, typically involving complete transection or major disruption, which is not the case here.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Minor Pancreatic Injury (Intact Duct) | Major Pancreatic Injury (Duct Disruption, Body/Tail) | Major Pancreatic Injury (Duct Disruption, Head) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Duct Integrity** | Intact | Disrupted | Disrupted |\n| **Management** | Closed-suction drainage | Distal pancreatectomy | Pylorus-preserving pancreaticoduodenectomy (Whipple) or complex repair/drainage |\n| **Goal** | Prevent fistula/abscess, preserve parenchyma | Resect damaged tissue, prevent leak | Complex reconstruction, preserve function |\n| **Complications** | Fistula, pseudocyst | Abscess, fistula, endocrine/exocrine insufficiency | High morbidity/mortality, fistula, insufficiency |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intact pancreatic duct + partial injury = drain, not resect.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a partial pancreatic injury with an intact duct would appear as a contusion, laceration, or hematoma of the pancreatic parenchyma without obvious transection or leakage of pancreatic fluid from the main duct. Careful inspection and gentle palpation confirm ductal integrity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Organ Injury Scale for the Pancreas (Revised 2018). It recommends drainage for Grade I and II injuries (contusion, superficial laceration without duct injury).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Closed-suction drainage and lavage | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Drain with sump drains | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Distal pancreatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Operative pancreatogram followed by distal pancreatectomy if ductal injury  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Transection of injured area of pancreas with Roux-en-Y (jejunal) anastomosi | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Routinely performing distal pancreatectomy for all penetrating injuries to the body or tail of the p** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
