  "id": 130829,
  "question": "A 29-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department with a gunshot wound to the abdomen. Her blood pressure is 80/60 mm Hg, pulse rate is 118 bpm, and respiration rate is 24 breaths per minute. She is brought immediately to the OR, where a large amount of blood and clots are found within the abdomen. After initial packing of the abdomen and stabilization of the patient, a retroperitoneal hematoma is found just above the renal veins. Proximal and distal control of the inferior vena cava is obtained and the blood pressure comes up to 100/60 mm Hg. Which is the most appropriate management?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Vascular repair of the injury",
    "B": "Packing of the area with a definitive plan to return to the OR in 48 hours",
    "C": "Ligation of the inferior vena cava",
    "D": "Use of intracava shunt to allow venous return while repairing the injury",
    "E": "Use of Gore-Tex interposition graft to restore continuity"
  },
  "answer": "A) Although injuries in the inferior vena cava can be ligated if the repair is unduly time consuming for the patient with continued hypotension, every attempt must be made to repair a suprarenal vena cava injury. Packing of the injury should be performed only if acidemia and/or hypothermia develop, because packing of the vena cava is not likely to be effective for a very long period. If an interposition graft is necessary, vein graft should be obtained from the infrarenal cava or iliac veins. A synthetic graft is likely to thrombose. An intracaval shunt generally requires a thoracotomy to gain proximal control and is reserved for retrohepatic injuries to the vena cava.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Suprarenal IVC: Repair it or regret it.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is vascular repair of the injury. Despite the initial instability, the patient has been stabilized, and every effort should be made to repair a suprarenal inferior vena cava (IVC) injury due to the high morbidity and mortality associated with ligation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSuprarenal IVC injuries are particularly lethal, and primary repair or repair with an autologous graft is the gold standard. Ligation of the IVC above the renal veins carries a very high mortality rate due to acute renal failure and massive lower extremity edema. With the patient stabilized and proximal/distal control achieved, direct repair is feasible and offers the best long-term outcome, preserving venous return and renal function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Packing is a temporary measure for damage control in unstable patients or to control diffuse bleeding, not a definitive plan for a major vascular injury like the IVC, especially when the patient is stabilized. Packing the IVC is unlikely to be effective long-term.\nOption C (Incorrect): Ligation of the suprarenal IVC is associated with extremely high mortality and morbidity (renal failure, lower extremity ischemia) and should only be considered as a last resort in an exsanguinating patient where repair is impossible or too time-consuming.\nOption D (Incorrect): An intracaval shunt is primarily used for retrohepatic IVC injuries, often requiring thoracotomy for proximal control, which is not indicated for a suprarenal injury above the renal veins.\nOption E (Incorrect): Synthetic grafts like Gore-Tex have a high thrombosis rate in the low-pressure venous system and are generally avoided for IVC reconstruction. Autologous vein grafts (e.g., from infrarenal cava or iliac veins) are preferred if primary repair is not possible.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Strategy | Indication | Pros | Cons |\n| :------------------ | :--------- | :--- | :--- |\n| Primary Repair | Most IVC injuries, especially suprarenal, when feasible | Best long-term patency, preserves venous return | Can be technically challenging, requires patient stability |\n| IVC Ligation | Last resort for exsanguinating patient, irreparable injury, infrarenal | Rapid hemorrhage control | High mortality (suprarenal), renal failure, lower extremity edema |\n| Autologous Vein Graft | When primary repair not possible, suprarenal/retrohepatic | Better patency than synthetic, avoids ligation sequelae | Requires donor site, technically demanding |\n| Intracaval Shunt | Retrohepatic IVC injuries, temporary bypass | Allows liver mobilization/repair, maintains venous return | Requires thoracotomy for control, temporary |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always repair suprarenal IVC injuries if patient stable enough.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a large retroperitoneal hematoma above the renal veins would be encountered. After opening the retroperitoneum, the IVC injury would be visible, often with active bleeding or a contained hematoma. Proximal and distal control would involve clamping the IVC above and below the injury, potentially including the renal veins if the injury extends.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEastern Association for the Surgery of Trauma (EAST) Practice Management Guidelines for the Management of Inferior Vena Cava Injuries (2011). Recommends primary repair when feasible for IVC injuries, with ligation reserved for unstable patients or irreparable injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Vascular repair of the injury | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Packing of the area with a definitive plan to return to the OR in 48 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ligation of the inferior vena cava | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Use of intracava shunt to allow venous return while repairing the injury | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Use of Gore-Tex interposition graft to restore continuity | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Although injuries in the inferior vena cava can be ligated if the repair is unduly time consuming fo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
