  "answer": "D) Restriction of motion (“locking”), effusion (“swelling”), and medial joint-line tenderness are the hallmarks of meniscal tears. Stability-to-stress testing eliminates collateral ligament rupture, and the ability to elevate the straight leg eliminates patella dislocation and quadriceps tendon ruptures. In addition, patella dislocation would also be characterized by gross patella deformity laterally.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the knee locks and aches, think meniscus, not just ligaments!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Medial meniscus. The patient's presentation of a twisting injury, knee swelling, restricted range of motion with inability to fully extend or bend (suggesting locking), and tenderness over the medial joint line are classic signs of a meniscal tear. The stability to varus/valgus stress rules out collateral ligament injuries.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeniscal tears often result from twisting injuries to a flexed knee, common in sports like skiing. The menisci act as shock absorbers and stabilizers. A tear can cause mechanical symptoms like \"locking\" (inability to fully extend due to a displaced fragment), \"catching,\" and effusion (swelling) due to synovial irritation. Medial joint line tenderness is a highly specific sign for a medial meniscal tear. The intact stability to stress testing is crucial, as it differentiates meniscal injuries from ligamentous ruptures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Anterior cruciate ligament) (Incorrect): ACL tears typically present with instability (giving way), a \"pop\" sensation, and a positive Lachman or anterior drawer test, which are not described here. The knee is stable to stress.\nOption B (Tuberosity) (Incorrect): Tibial tuberosity avulsion fractures are more common in adolescents and would be visible on X-ray, which was normal. This doesn't explain the locking or medial joint line tenderness.\nOption C (Transverse genicular ligament) (Incorrect): The transverse genicular ligament connects the anterior horns of the menisci. Isolated injury is rare and would not typically cause the described locking, significant effusion, or medial joint line tenderness as the primary presentation.\nOption E (Posterior cruciate ligament) (Incorrect): PCL tears present with posterior instability, often from a direct blow to the anterior tibia or hyperflexion. The knee is stable to stress testing, ruling this out.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Meniscal Tear | ACL Tear | Collateral Ligament Tear (MCL/LCL) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mechanism | Twisting, squatting, direct impact | Twisting, hyperextension, direct blow | Valgus (MCL), Varus (LCL) stress |\n| Key Symptoms | Locking, catching, joint line tenderness, effusion | \"Pop,\" instability, effusion, giving way | Pain with stress, localized tenderness, instability |\n| Stability to Stress | Stable (unless combined injury) | Unstable (Lachman, anterior drawer positive) | Unstable (valgus/varus stress positive) |\n| Imaging | MRI (best), X-ray normal | MRI (best), X-ray normal | MRI (best), X-ray normal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Locking, swelling, and joint line tenderness after a twist = meniscal tear until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMRI would show a high signal intensity extending to the meniscal surface. Arthroscopy would reveal the tear morphology (e.g., bucket-handle, radial, flap) and location.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Management of Meniscal Tears (2014, updated 2019). It recommends MRI for diagnosis and arthroscopic repair/meniscectomy based on tear characteristics and patient factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anterior cruciate ligament | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tuberosity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Transverse genicular ligament | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Medial meniscus | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Posterior cruciate ligament | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Restriction of motion (“locking”), effusion (“swelling”), and medial joint-line tenderness are the h** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
