  "answer": "D) Nonoperative management of splenic trauma is usually successful in grade I lacera-tions and would be the standard of care in a hemodyamically stable patient. This boy responded well to a modest fluid bolus but if he becomes unstable on the way to CAT scan it would be hazardous to allow him to go into full-blown shock while in the scanner. Likewise, he should be explored (or embolized, depending on the resources available) for other signs of active bleeding including requiring >20 mL/kg PRBC to maintain his vital signs or seeing active extravasation on contrast on the CAT scan. Seeing fluid around the spleen on the FAST exam simply supports the clinical diagnosis of ruptured spleen but not an indi-cation for intervention in the absence of hemo-dynamic instability.",
