  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stable spleen, happy teen; unstable spleen, intervention keen!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Nonoperative management of splenic trauma is justified when the patient is hemodynamically stable, even if imaging shows free fluid, as long as there are no other signs of ongoing significant hemorrhage requiring intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNonoperative management (NOM) is the standard of care for most pediatric splenic injuries, provided the patient remains hemodynamically stable. Hemodynamic stability is the cornerstone of NOM, defined by normal vital signs for age, adequate urine output, and no signs of ongoing shock. A positive FAST exam (free fluid around the spleen) simply confirms the presence of intra-abdominal hemorrhage but does not, by itself, mandate operative intervention if the patient is stable. The initial fluid bolus successfully stabilized this patient, making NOM a viable option if other contraindications are absent.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Active extravasation of IV contrast on CT indicates ongoing hemorrhage, which is a contraindication to nonoperative management and typically requires intervention (embolization or surgery).\nOption B (Incorrect): Becoming restless, tachycardic, and hypotensive signifies hemodynamic instability and impending shock, necessitating immediate operative intervention, not nonoperative management.\nOption C (Incorrect): Requiring 2 units of packed red blood cells (PRBCs) for a 41 kg child (approximately >20 mL/kg) within 3 hours indicates significant ongoing blood loss, which is a contraindication to nonoperative management and suggests the need for intervention.\nOption E (Incorrect): The question states the fluid bolus *did* increase his blood pressure. If it failed to increase his blood pressure, he would be considered a non-responder, indicating ongoing hemorrhage and a need for operative intervention, not justification for nonoperative management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Finding/Status | Hemodynamic Stability | Management Strategy |\n|---|---|---|\n| Free fluid on FAST | Stable | Nonoperative Management (NOM) |\n| Active extravasation on CT | Stable/Unstable | Intervention (Embolization/Surgery) |\n| Persistent instability/Shock | Unstable | Operative Management |\n| Transfusion >20 mL/kg PRBCs | Stable/Unstable | Intervention (Embolization/Surgery) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hemodynamic stability is paramount for nonoperative management of splenic trauma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, look for splenic lacerations, perisplenic hematoma, and active contrast extravasation (blush) which signifies ongoing arterial bleeding. Free fluid in the abdomen (hemoperitoneum) is common.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018) recommends nonoperative management for hemodynamically stable patients with solid organ injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | You find a grade I splenic laceration on the CAT scan with some active extr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | If he becomes restless, recurrently tachycardic, and hypotensive while on t | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | He requires 2 U of packed red blood cells (PRBCs) to maintain his vital sig | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | FAST exam before the CAT scan demonstrates free fluid around the spleen | ✅ Correct |\n| E | It fails to increase his blood pressure | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Nonoperative management of splenic trauma is usually successful in grade I lacera-tions and would be** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
