  "answer": "B) The test of choice is ultrasound. It is quick, noninvasive, and accurate for the diagnosis of gallstones and acute cholecystitis. When pres-ent, signs of acute cholecystitis such as peric-holecystitic fluid and a thickened gallbladder wall can easily be seen on ultrasound. CAT scan often does not show gallstones if the den-sity of the stones is similar to that of bile. HIDA scan is usually reserved for patients in whom ultrasound is negative but suspicion of gall-bladder disease is high. MRI is expensive and not studied for the diagnosis of stones. ERCPis usally done to rule out common duct stones.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When RUQ pain strikes, ultrasound is your first sight!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Ultrasound. For a patient presenting with classic symptoms of biliary colic or acute cholecystitis (RUQ pain, vomiting, multiparous female, normal LFTs), ultrasound is the initial diagnostic test of choice due to its safety, availability, and accuracy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound is highly effective for visualizing gallstones, gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, and eliciting a sonographic Murphy's sign, all indicative of acute cholecystitis. It is non-invasive, does not involve radiation, and can be performed rapidly at the bedside, making it ideal for emergent evaluation of RUQ pain. Its ability to directly visualize the gallbladder and its contents makes it superior to other modalities for initial diagnosis of cholelithiasis and cholecystitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Computerized axial tomography (CAT) scan) (Incorrect): While useful for abdominal pain, CT is less sensitive than ultrasound for detecting gallstones, especially non-calcified ones, and exposes the patient to radiation.\nOption C (Hydroxy iminodiacetic acid (HIDA) scan) (Incorrect): HIDA scan assesses gallbladder function and cystic duct patency; it is typically reserved for cases where ultrasound is equivocal or negative but clinical suspicion for acute cholecystitis remains high.\nOption D (MRI) (Incorrect): MRI is excellent for soft tissue contrast but is more expensive, time-consuming, and generally not the first-line imaging for suspected gallstones or acute cholecystitis.\nOption E (Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)) (Incorrect): ERCP is an invasive procedure primarily used for therapeutic intervention or diagnosis of common bile duct stones, not for initial diagnosis of gallbladder pathology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Primary Use | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ultrasound | Initial diagnosis of cholelithiasis, acute cholecystitis | Quick, non-invasive, no radiation, high sensitivity for stones/cholecystitis | Operator dependent, limited by bowel gas/obesity |\n| HIDA scan | Acute cholecystitis (when US equivocal), acalculous cholecystitis | Functional assessment of cystic duct patency | Radiation exposure, less anatomical detail |\n| CT scan | Complications of cholecystitis, alternative diagnoses | Good for surrounding structures, abscesses, pancreatitis | Radiation exposure, less sensitive for stones than US |\n| ERCP | Common bile duct stones (diagnosis & therapy) | Therapeutic capabilities, direct visualization of ducts | Invasive, risk of pancreatitis, perforation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ultrasound is the first-line imaging for RUQ pain and suspected gallbladder disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, acute cholecystitis is characterized by gallstones, gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a positive sonographic Murphy's sign.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend ultrasound as the primary imaging modality for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Computerized axial tomography (CAT) scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ultrasound | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Hydroxy iminodiacetic acid (HIDA) scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The test of choice is ultrasound. It is quick, noninvasive, and accurate for the diagnosis of gallst** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
