  "answer": "C) Asubtotal gastrectomy with negative mar-gins is appropriate treatment for gastric carci-noma. Vagotomy adds nothing as patients with gastric cancer are invariably achlorhydric. A Whipple procedure is done for panccreatic car-cinoma. Total gastrectomy is rarely indicated for a distal gastric carcinoma.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For distal gastric cancer, less is more (if oncologically sound).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is subtotal gastrectomy because it provides adequate oncologic resection with negative margins for a distal gastric adenocarcinoma without evidence of metastatic disease, while preserving some gastric function. This approach balances curative intent with minimizing surgical morbidity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSubtotal gastrectomy involves resection of the distal two-thirds to three-quarters of the stomach, including the tumor, along with regional lymphadenectomy (D1 or D2 depending on guidelines). The primary goal is to achieve an R0 resection (negative microscopic margins), which is paramount for long-term survival in gastric cancer. For distal antral lesions, this approach is oncologically sound and avoids the increased morbidity and nutritional sequelae associated with total gastrectomy when not indicated. The absence of metastasis on CT further supports a curative resection, and vagotomy is unnecessary as gastric cancer patients are often achlorhydric.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Whipple procedure (pancreaticoduodenectomy) is indicated for tumors of the pancreatic head, duodenum, or periampullary region, not for gastric adenocarcinoma.\nOption B (Incorrect): Vagotomy and antrectomy is a procedure primarily for benign peptic ulcer disease, aiming to reduce acid secretion and remove the antrum; it is inadequate for oncologic resection of gastric cancer.\nOption D (Incorrect): Vagotomy and pyloroplasty with wedge resection of the ulcer is a procedure for benign peptic ulcer disease and is completely insufficient for the treatment of adenocarcinoma, which requires wide margins and lymphadenectomy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Total gastrectomy involves removal of the entire stomach. While sometimes necessary for proximal or diffuse gastric cancers, it is generally not indicated for a distal antral lesion without diffuse involvement, as subtotal gastrectomy offers comparable oncologic outcomes with less morbidity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Subtotal Gastrectomy | Distal/Antral gastric adenocarcinoma (T1-T3, N0-N2, M0) | Resection of distal 2/3-3/4 stomach, D1/D2 lymphadenectomy, R0 margins |\n| Total Gastrectomy | Proximal/Cardia gastric adenocarcinoma, diffuse type, extensive disease | Resection of entire stomach, D2 lymphadenectomy, esophagojejunostomy |\n| Whipple Procedure | Pancreatic head, duodenal, periampullary, distal bile duct cancers | Pancreaticoduodenectomy, cholecystectomy, partial gastrectomy, lymphadenectomy |\n| Vagotomy & Antrectomy | Refractory benign peptic ulcer disease | Truncal/selective vagotomy, removal of gastric antrum, Billroth I/II reconstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Distal gastric cancer without metastasis = subtotal gastrectomy for curative intent.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would reveal a large, likely fungating or ulcerated mass in the distal antrum. CT scan would show a thickened gastric wall in the antrum, but crucially, no evidence of liver lesions or distant lymphadenopathy, confirming M0 status. Intraoperatively, the tumor would be localized to the distal stomach, allowing for clear proximal and distal margins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (e.g., Version 2.2023). These guidelines recommend subtotal gastrectomy with D1/D2 lymphadenectomy for resectable distal gastric adenocarcinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Whipple procedure (pancreaticoduodenectomy) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Vagotomy and antrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Subtotal gastrectomy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Vagotomy and pyloroplasty with wedge resection of the ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Asubtotal gastrectomy with negative mar-gins is appropriate treatment for gastric carci-noma. Vagoto** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
