  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the colon perforates and peritonitis blooms, Hartmann's saves the day!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Sigmoid resection and end sigmoid colostomy and oversew the rectum (Hartmann procedure). This approach effectively addresses the perforated diverticulitis by removing the source of infection while avoiding a high-risk anastomosis in a contaminated field.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Hartmann procedure is the gold standard for perforated diverticulitis with peritonitis, especially in unstable patients or those with significant inflammation/contamination. It involves resecting the diseased sigmoid colon, creating an end colostomy, and oversewing the rectal stump. This strategy achieves source control by removing the perforated segment, prevents anastomotic leak by avoiding a primary anastomosis in a septic field, and diverts the fecal stream, allowing the patient to recover before a potential reversal. The mobility of the colon and contained abscess make resection feasible, and the peritonitis dictates avoiding anastomosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Insertion of a sump drain and a transverse loop colostomy is inadequate as it does not resect the perforated segment, leaving the source of infection and inflammation in situ.\nOption B (Incorrect): Sigmoid resection including the abscess and colon-to-colon anastomosis is contraindicated in the presence of peritonitis due to a significantly increased risk of anastomotic leak and subsequent sepsis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Sigmoid loop colostomy alone does not remove the diseased, perforated segment of the colon, failing to address the primary source of infection and peritonitis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Abdominoperineal resection (APR) is a procedure for rectal cancer or severe inflammatory bowel disease affecting the rectum; it is not indicated for sigmoid diverticulitis as the rectum is typically spared and its removal is unnecessary.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Indication | Pros | Cons |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Hartmann's Procedure** | Perforated diverticulitis with peritonitis/sepsis | Source control, avoids anastomosis in contaminated field | Requires stoma, second surgery for reversal |\n| **Primary Anastomosis** | Elective resection, uncomplicated diverticulitis, stable patient with minimal contamination | Single-stage procedure, no stoma | High leak risk if contamination/inflammation present |\n| **Loop Colostomy** | Temporary diversion for distal obstruction or protection of distal anastomosis | Simple, reversible | Does not remove diseased segment, requires second surgery |\n| **Drainage Only** | Localized abscess without perforation, unfit for surgery | Minimally invasive | Does not address underlying pathology, high recurrence |\n| **APR** | Rectal cancer, severe rectal IBD | Curative for rectal pathology | Major surgery, permanent colostomy, not for diverticulitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Perforated diverticulitis + peritonitis = Hartmann's procedure.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, you would see sigmoid wall thickening, pericolic fat stranding, free air, and a contained abscess. Intraoperatively, the sigmoid colon would be inflamed and mobile, with a visible perforation and purulent material from the abscess, confirming peritonitis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASCRS Clinical Practice Guidelines for Diverticulitis (2020) recommend Hartmann's procedure for patients with diffuse peritonitis or hemodynamic instability due to perforated diverticulitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Insertion of a sump drain in the abscess and a transverse loop colostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sigmoid resection including the abscess and colon-to-colon anastomosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Sigmoid loop colostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Abdominoperineal resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sigmoid resection and end sigmoid colostomy and oversew the rectum (Hartman | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Whenever possible, the inflamed colon should be resected. Since the patient had peritonitis, the saf** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
