  "id": 130979,
  "question": "A10-month-old boy has recently been weaned and placed on solid food. He develops colicky abdominal pain with vomiting. Examination of the abdomen shows emptiness in the right iliac fossa and a mass in the epigatrium. Intussusception is suspected. Following ade-quate hydration, this condition should be treated by which of the following?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Laxatives",
    "B": "Gastrojejunostomy",
    "C": "Laparotomy and manual reduction",
    "D": "Radiologic reduction by barium with measured pressure control of column of barium",
    "E": "Right hemicolectomy"
  },
  "answer": "D) Treatment in infants is by controlled radi-ologic reduction initially, with surgery reserved for cases in which ischemia is expected or reduction is unsuccessful. The leading part of the intussusception is the apex. The outer sheath is the intussuscipiens, which receives the inner intussusceptum. The outer intussus-cipiens elicits peristalsis, which forces the intus-susceptum to extend distally.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut it if you can push it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D because radiologic reduction, typically with air or barium enema, is the initial treatment of choice for uncomplicated intussusception in stable pediatric patients. This non-operative approach aims to reduce the telescoped bowel segment without surgical intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadiologic reduction utilizes controlled pneumatic (air) or hydrostatic (barium/saline) pressure to gently push the intussusceptum (inner bowel segment) back out of the intussuscipiens (outer bowel segment). This method is highly effective (70-90% success rate) in reducing the intussusception, thereby restoring bowel patency and preventing ischemia. Careful pressure control is paramount to minimize the risk of bowel perforation, making it a safe and preferred first-line treatment in the absence of peritonitis or perforation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Laxatives) (Incorrect): Laxatives are used for constipation and would be ineffective and potentially harmful in a mechanical obstruction like intussusception.\nOption B (Gastrojejunostomy) (Incorrect): Gastrojejunostomy is a surgical procedure to bypass the pylorus, typically performed for gastric outlet obstruction, and has no role in the treatment of intussusception.\nOption C (Laparotomy and manual reduction) (Incorrect): While surgical reduction is an option, it is reserved for cases where radiologic reduction fails, or when there are signs of bowel perforation, peritonitis, or significant ischemia. It is not the initial treatment for a stable patient.\nOption E (Right hemicolectomy) (Incorrect): Right hemicolectomy involves resection of a portion of the colon and is indicated for intussusception with a pathologic lead point (e.g., Meckel's diverticulum, polyp) or for irreversible bowel necrosis, not as an initial treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Radiologic Reduction (Air/Barium Enema) | Surgical Reduction (Laparotomy) | Right Hemicolectomy |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------------------- | :------------------------------ | :------------------ |\n| Indication | Uncomplicated intussusception, stable patient | Failed radiologic reduction, peritonitis, perforation, ischemia | Pathologic lead point, irreversible ischemia/necrosis |\n| Method | Pneumatic or hydrostatic pressure | Manual reduction, often with milking | Resection of affected bowel segment |\n| Risks | Perforation, recurrence | Anesthesia, infection, adhesion, recurrence | Major surgery, short bowel syndrome |\n| Success Rate | High (70-90%) | High if viable bowel | Depends on underlying pathology |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intussusception in infants = enema first, surgery second.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the classic 'target sign' or 'donut sign' (transverse view) and 'pseudokidney sign' (longitudinal view) are diagnostic. Intraoperatively, the telescoped bowel segment is visible, often edematous and congested, and can be manually reduced by milking the intussusceptum out of the intussuscipiens.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Intussusception (e.g., 2018). Recommends initial non-operative reduction with air or hydrostatic enema in stable patients without signs of perforation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Laxatives | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gastrojejunostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Laparotomy and manual reduction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Radiologic reduction by barium with measured pressure control of column of  | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Right hemicolectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Treatment in infants is by controlled radi-ologic reduction initially, with surgery reserved for cas** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Clinical Cases MCQ's**\n",
